{"title_page": "Jesper Pedersen (alpine skier)", "text_new": "{{short description|Paralympic alpine skier from Norway}}\n\n'''Jesper Saltvik Pedersen''' (born 23 August 1999<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/alpine-skiing/athlete-profile-n3050986-jesper-pedersen.htm |title=Pyeonchang 2018 athlete profile |access-date=2018-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318120427/https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/alpine-skiing/athlete-profile-n3050986-jesper-pedersen.htm |archive-date=2018-03-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is a para-alpine skier who won gold for [[Norway at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]] in Giant slalom.<ref>[http://www.newsinenglish.no/2018/03/15/pedersen-wins-gold-at-paralympics/ Views and News from Norway]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=jesper-pedersen|old_id=1230062}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pedersen, Jesper Saltvik}}\n[[Category:Norwegian male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Norway]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Norway-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Paralympic alpine skier from Norway}}\n'''Jesper Saltvik Pedersen''' (born 23 August 1999<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/alpine-skiing/athlete-profile-n3050986-jesper-pedersen.htm |title=Pyeonchang 2018 athlete profile |access-date=2018-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318120427/https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/alpine-skiing/athlete-profile-n3050986-jesper-pedersen.htm |archive-date=2018-03-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is a para-alpine skier who won gold for [[Norway at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]] in Giant slalom.<ref>[http://www.newsinenglish.no/2018/03/15/pedersen-wins-gold-at-paralympics/ Views and News from Norway]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|1230062}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pedersen, Jesper Saltvik}}\n[[Category:Norwegian male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Norway]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Norway-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesper_Pedersen_(alpine_skier)"}
{"title_page": "Pasta Poiatti", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n | name             = Poiatti [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni|S.p.A.]]\n | logo             = Rigatoni.jpg\n | logo_size        = 180px\n | type             = [[Privately held company|Private]] (family-owned)\n | genre            = \n | foundation       = 1946\n | founder          = Domenico Poiatti\n | location_city    = [[Mazara del Vallo]]\n | location_country = [[Sicily]], [[Italy]]\n | locations        = \n | area_served      = Worldwide\n | key_people       = \n | industry         = [[Food processing]]\n | products         = [[Pasta]]\n | services         = \n | revenue          = {{profit}} [[Euro|\u20ac]] 60 millions (2019)<ref name=\":un24\">{{cita web|url=https://www.lastampa.it/cuneo/2019/12/26/news/il-signore-della-pasta-investire-qui-un-errore-devo-lasciare-mondovi-e-vendoa-l-ex-monte-regale-un-tempo-gazzola-1.38256538|title= Il signore della pasta: \u201cInvestire qui un errore, devo lasciare Mondov\u00ec e vendoa l\u2019ex Monte Regale, un tempo Gazzola\u201d|date=26 December 2019|editor=[[La Stampa]]|language=it}}</ref>\n | operating_income = \n | net_income       = \n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = \n | num_employees    = \n | parent           = \n | divisions        = 2 brands\n | subsid           = \n | homepage         = {{url|www.poiatti.it}}\n | footnotes        = \n}}\n'''Poiatti SPA''' or more simply '''Poiatti''', is an Italian [[Pasta]] manufacturing company based in [[Sicily]].\n\n==History==\nDomenico Poiatti, born in 1921, in 1940 left [[Artogne|Pian D'Artogne]] for military service. Arriving at [[Mazara del Vallo]] he falls in love with Eleonora, a local girl.\nAlberto, the first son, was born on December 8, 1943. Domenico takes his small family to his native Pian D'Artogne; here he works in his uncle's old water-fed mill that grinds corn and dried chestnuts, but Poiatti returned to Mazara in 1946. Domenico opens a grocery store, then buys a small artisan pasta factory that became the current company.<ref name=\":un20\">{{cita web|url=https://www.giornaledibrescia.it/valcamonica/poiatti-la-pasta-camuno-siciliana-1.3030411|title= Poiatti, la pasta \u00abcamuno-siciliana\u00bb|date=30 July 2015|editor=giornaledibrescia.it|language=it}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nToday, Poiatti produces 100 forms of pasta with Sicilian [[wheat]], from durum wheat semolina to eggs, from products made from bronze to [[Couscous]].<ref name=\":un21\">{{cita web|url=https://www.poiatti.it/storia/|title= Ma Poiatti \u00e8 soprattuto una storia|editor=poiatti.it|language=it}}</ref>\nPoiatti SPA has two plants both in Sicily: in [[Mazara del Vallo]] and in [[Santa Venerina]] (where it is produced the \"Pasta Etna\" line); \nthere are 120 employees.<ref name=\":un23\">{{cita web|url=http://www.pastaetna.it/|title= Pasta Etna|editor=pastaetna.it|language=it}}</ref>\n\n==Brands==\n* Pasta Poiatti\n* Pasta Etna\n\n== Distribution ==\nIn Italy, the Poiatti pasta is marketed and distributed directly by the company. In the foreign market ([[Europe]], [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]] and [[Brazil]]) the distribution is managed by local partners.<ref name=\":un32\">{{cita web|url=http://web.tiscali.it/f_galfano/poiatti/azienda.html|title= Un'industria all'avanguardia|date=11 March 2019|editor=web.tiscali.it|language=it}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Italian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sicily]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n | name             = Poiatti [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni|S.p.A.]]\n | logo             = Rigatoni.jpg\n | logo_size        = 180px\n | type             = [[Privately held company|Private]] (family-owned)\n | genre            = \n | foundation       = 1946\n | founder          = Domenico Poiatti\n | location_city    = [[Mazara del Vallo]]\n | location_country = [[Sicily]], [[Italy]]\n | locations        = \n | area_served      = Worldwide\n | key_people       = \n | industry         = [[Food processing]]\n | products         = [[Pasta]]\n | services         = \n | revenue          = {{profit}} [[Euro|\u20ac]] 60 millions (2019)<ref name=\":un24\">{{cita web|url=https://www.lastampa.it/cuneo/2019/12/26/news/il-signore-della-pasta-investire-qui-un-errore-devo-lasciare-mondovi-e-vendoa-l-ex-monte-regale-un-tempo-gazzola-1.38256538|title= Il signore della pasta: \u201cInvestire qui un errore, devo lasciare Mondov\u00ec e vendoa l\u2019ex Monte Regale, un tempo Gazzola\u201d|date=26 December 2019|editor=[[La Stampa]]|language=it}}</ref>\n | operating_income = \n | net_income       = \n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = \n | num_employees    = \n | parent           = \n | divisions        = 2 brands\n | subsid           = \n | homepage         = {{url|www.poiatti.it}}\n | footnotes        = \n}}\n'''Poiatti SPA''' or more simply '''Poiatti''', is an Italian [[Pasta]] manufacturing company based in [[Sicily]].\n==History==\nDomenico Poiatti, born in 1921, in 1940 left [[Artogne|Pian D'Artogne]] for military service. Arriving at [[Mazara del Vallo]] he falls in love with Eleonora, a local girl.\nAlberto, the first son, was born on December 8, 1943. Domenico takes his small family to his native Pian D'Artogne; here he works in his uncle's old water-fed mill that grinds corn and dried chestnuts, but Poiatti returned to Mazara in 1946. Domenico opens a grocery store, then buys a small artisan pasta factory that became the current company.<ref name=\":un20\">{{cita web|url=https://www.giornaledibrescia.it/valcamonica/poiatti-la-pasta-camuno-siciliana-1.3030411|title= Poiatti, la pasta \u00abcamuno-siciliana\u00bb|date=30 July 2015|editor=giornaledibrescia.it|language=it}}</ref>\n==Production==\nToday, Poiatti produces 100 forms of pasta with Sicilian [[wheat]], from durum wheat semolina to eggs, from products made from bronze to [[Couscous]].<ref name=\":un21\">{{cita web|url=https://www.poiatti.it/storia/|title= Ma Poiatti \u00e8 soprattuto una storia|editor=poiatti.it|language=it}}</ref>\nPoiatti SPA has two plants both in Sicily: in [[Mazara del Vallo]] and in [[Santa Venerina]] (where it is produced the \"Pasta Etna\" line); \nthere are 120 employees.<ref name=\":un23\">{{cita web|url=http://www.pastaetna.it/|title= Pasta Etna|editor=pastaetna.it|language=it}}</ref>\n==Brands==\n* Pasta Poiatti\n* Pasta Etna\n== Distribution ==\nIn Italy, the Poiatti pasta is marketed and distributed directly by the company. In the foreign market ([[Europe]], [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]] and [[Brazil]]) the distribution is managed by local partners.<ref name=\":un32\">{{cita web|url=http://web.tiscali.it/f_galfano/poiatti/azienda.html|title= Un'industria all'avanguardia|date=11 March 2019|editor=web.tiscali.it|language=it}}</ref>\n==References==\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Italian brands]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sicily]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pasta_Poiatti"}
{"title_page": "Joe Hisaishi", "text_new": "{{Expand Japanese|\u4e45\u77f3\u8b72|topic=musician|reason=JA wikipedia is much better referenced than here, bring that article over|date=February 2016}}\n<!-- {{More footnotes|BLP=yes|date=February 2016|reason=use official website, ANN, and MADB to beef up biography}} -->\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Joe Hisaishi\n| image            = Joe Hisaishi 2011.jpg\n| caption          = Hisaishi in Paris in 2011\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name      = \u4e45\u77f3 \u8b72\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| birth_name       = Mamoru Fujisawa\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1950|12|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Nakano, Nagano]], Japan\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Piano]]\n* [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* [[violin]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Film score]]\n* [[classical (music)|classical]]\n* [[romantic era|romanticism]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Composer\n* conductor\n* arranger\n}}\n| years_active     = 1974\u2013present\n| website          = {{URL|joehisaishi.com}}\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Mamoru Fujisawa'''|\u85e4\u6fa4 \u5b88|''Fujisawa Mamoru''|born December 6, 1950}}, known professionally as {{Nihongo|'''Joe Hisaishi'''|\u4e45\u77f3 \u8b72|''Hisaishi J\u014d''}}, is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] composer and musical director known for over 100 [[soundtrack|film scores]] and solo albums dating back to 1981.<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90782/8336846.html Joe Hisaishi film score concerts \u2013 People's Daily Online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106040943/http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90782/8336846.html|date=6 January 2014}}. English.peopledaily.com.cn (23 July 2013). Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref> Hisaishi is also known for his piano scores.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferbosier/2013/01/08/joe-hisaishi-discusses-soundtrack-for-ni-no-kuni-wrath-of-the-white-witch/#68c3203856eb|title=Joe Hisaishi Discusses Soundtrack for 'Ni No Kuni: Wrath of the White Witch'|last=Bosier|first=Jen|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=11 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312023349/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferbosier/2013/01/08/joe-hisaishi-discusses-soundtrack-for-ni-no-kuni-wrath-of-the-white-witch/#68c3203856eb|archivedate=12 March 2018}}</ref>{{Better source|date=March 2018}}\n\nWhile possessing a stylistically distinct sound, Hisaishi's music has been known to explore and incorporate different genres, including [[minimalist music|minimalist]], [[electronic music|experimental electronic]], [[European classical music|European classical]], and [[Music of Japan|Japanese classical]]. Lesser known are the other musical roles he plays; he is also a [[typesetter]], author, arranger, and conductor.\n\nHe has been associated with animator [[Hayao Miyazaki]] since 1984, having composed scores for all but one of his films. He is also recognized for the soundtracks he has provided for filmmaker [[Takeshi Kitano|'Beat' Takeshi Kitano]], including ''[[A Scene at the Sea]]'' (1991), ''[[Sonatine (1993 film)|Sonatine]]'' (1993), ''[[Kids Return]]'' (1996), ''[[Hana-bi]]'' (1997), ''[[Kikujiro]]'' (1999), and ''[[Dolls (2002 film)|Dolls]]'' (2002), as well for the video game series ''[[Ni no Kuni]]''. He was a student of legendary anime composer [[Takeo Watanabe]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}<!-- Note that BBC Music uses content from Wikipedia. -->\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life===\nHisaishi was born in [[Nakano, Nagano]], Japan, as {{Nihongo|Mamoru Fujisawa|\u85e4\u6fa4 \u5b88|Fujisawa Mamoru}}. When he started learning violin in the Violin School Suzuki Shinichi at the age of four, he found his passion in music. At the same age, he also began watching 300 movies a year with his father, which influenced his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lovejapanese.com.au/joe-hisaishi-studio-ghibli-music-composer/|title=Joe Hisaishi - The Composer Behind Studio Ghibli Songs & Music|last=Japanese|first=Love|date=2018-08-12|website=Love Japanese - Japanese Language & Culture Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Realizing his love, he attended the [[Kunitachi College of Music]] in 1969 to major in [[music composition]]. Hisaishi collaborated with [[Minimalist music|minimalist artists]] as a typesetter, furthering his experience in the musical world.\n\nHe enjoyed his first success of the business in 1974 when he composed music for the anime series called ''[[First Human Giatrus|Gyatoruzu]]''. This and other early works were created under his given name. During this period, he composed for ''Sasuga no Sarutobi'' (Academy of Ninja) and ''[[Futari Daka]]'' (A Full Throttle).\n\nIn the 1970s, [[Japanese popular music]], [[electronic music]], and new-age music flourished; those genres, as well as the [[Yellow Magic Orchestra]] (a Japanese electronic band in 1978\u20131983), influenced Hisaishi's compositions. He developed his music from [[Minimalist music|minimalist]] ideas and expanded toward orchestral work. Around 1975, Hisaishi presented his first public performance, spreading his name around his community. Also, from 1978, he had worked for Brass Compositions for a long time. His first album, ''MKWAJU'', was released in 1981, with ''Information'' being released a year later. His first major anime scores were ''Hajime Ningen Gyatoruz'' (1974) and ''Robokko Beeton'' (1976).\n\nAs his works were becoming well known, Hisaishi formulated an alias inspired by [[Quincy Jones]], an African-American musician and producer. Retranscribed in Japanese, \"Quincy Jones\" became \"Joe Hisaishi\". (\"Quincy\", pronounced \"Kuinsh\u012b\u201d in Japanese, can be written using the same [[kanji]] in \"Hisaishi\"; \"Joe\" comes from \"Jones\".)<ref>[http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/hisaishi/ Joe Hisaishi// Who's Who //] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128025222/http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/hisaishi/|date=November 28, 2013}}. Nausicaa.net. Retrieved on 2015-08-18.</ref>\n\n===1981\u201398: Anime film industry===\nIn 1981 Hisaishi, with his new name, released his first album of art music, ''MKWAJU'', and in 1982 the electropop-minimalist album ''Information''. Then, in 1983, Hisaishi was recommended by Tokuma, who had published ''Information'', to create an image album for ''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (film)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]''. Hisaishi and the director of the animated film, [[Hayao Miyazaki]], became great friends and would work together on many future projects.\n\nIn 1985, he founded his own recording studio\u2014the wonder station. Their collaboration has invited comparisons to the collaborations of [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[John Williams]]. This big break led to Hisaishi's overwhelming success as a composer of film scores. In 1986, ''[[Laputa: Castle in the Sky]]'' would be the first feature to appear under the Studio Ghibli banner, and its gentle, faintly melancholic tone would become a familiar trademark of much of the studio's later output.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/17384/looking-back-at-laputa-castle-in-the-sky|title=Looking back at Laputa: Castle In The Sky|work=Den of Geek|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312023108/http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/17384/looking-back-at-laputa-castle-in-the-sky|archivedate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> And later, in the 1990s, ''[[Porco Rosso]]'' and ''[[Princess Mononoke]]'' were released. As Hisaishi strengthened his reputation as one of the budding [[anime]] industry's top musical contributors, his compositions (including eight theatrical films and one [[Original video animation|OAV]]) would proceed to become some of the very hallmarks of early anime in the 1980s and 1990s. Hisaishi also composed for such TV and movie hits as ''Sasuga no Sarutobi'', ''Two Down Full Base'', ''Tonde Mon Pe'' and the anime [[Techno Police 21C|''Tekuno porisu 21C'']] (all 1982), ''Sasuraiger'' (1983), ''[[Futari Daka|Futari Taka]]'' (1984), [[Hon\u014d no Alpen Rose: Judy & Randy|''Hon\u014d no Alpen Rose'']] (1985) and ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1986 TV series)|Oz no mah\u00f4tsukai]]'' (1986). He also scored the sci-fi adventure series ''[[Mospeada]]'' (1983), which was later reworked (without his music) into the third segment of Carl Macek's compilation, ''[[Robotech]]''. Other films he scored included ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam|Mobile Suit Gundam Movie II: Soldiers of Sorrow]]'' (1981), ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam|Mobile Suit Gundam Movie III: Encounters in Space]]'', (1982), ''[[Birth (anime)|Birth (B\u00e2su)]]'' (1984), ''[[Arion (anime)|Arion]]'' (1986), ''[[Robot Carnival]]'' (1987), ''[[My Neighbor Totoro|Totoro]]'' (1988), ''[[Crest of the Royal Family]]'' and ''[[Maison Ikkoku|Maison Ikkoku \u2013 Apartment Fantasy]]'' (both 1988), ''[[Venus Wars]]'' (1989), ''[[Kiki's Delivery Service]]'' (1989), ''[[Porco Rosso]]'' (1992) and ''[[Ocean Heaven]]'' (2010). He also did theme song arrangements and composed other anime opening, closing, and insert title theme songs such as ''[[Lalabel|Mah\u014d Sh\u014djo Lalabel]]'' (1980), ''[[Hello! Sandybell]]'' (1981), ''[[Meiken Jolie]]'' (1981), ''[[Voltron]]'' (1981), ''[[Ai Shite Knight]]'' (1983), ''[[Creamy Mami, the Magic Angel|Creamy Mami, the Magic Angel: Curtain Call]]'' (1986), and ''[[Kimagure Orange Road: The Movie]]'' (1988).\n\nAs more exposure was given to Hisaishi and the [[anime]] industry, his career grew. He initiated a solo career, began to produce music, and created his own label (Wonder Land Inc.) in 1988. A year later, Hisaishi released his solo album ''Pretender'' as the first album under the new label.\n\n===1998\u20132004: Worldwide success===\nIn 1998, Hisaishi provided the soundtrack to the [[1998 Winter Paralympics]]. The following year, he composed the music for the third installment in a series of popular computer-animated educational films about the human body. Again in 1999, he composed the score for the Takeshi Kitano film ''[[Kikujiro]]'', whose title track ''Summer'' went on to become one of Hisaishi's most recognizable compositions.\n\nIn 2001, Hisaishi produced music for another Kitano film, ''Brother'', and Hayao Miyazaki's animated film, ''[[Spirited Away]]''. He also served as executive producer of the Night Fantasia 4 Movement at the Japan Expo in Fukushima 2001. On October 6, Hisaishi made his debut as a film director in ''Quartet'', having also written both its music and script. The film received excellent reviews at the [[Montreal Film Festival]]. His first soundtrack for a foreign film, ''Le Petit Poucet'', was released in the same year.\n\n[[File:Joe Hisaishi in Krakow.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Hisaishi in Krak\u00f3w, 2011]]\n\nAnother Miyazaki film, ''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'', for which Hisaishi composed the score, was released on November 20, 2004, in Japan. From November 3 to 29, 2004, Hisaishi embarked on his \"Joe Hisaishi Freedom \u2013 Piano Stories 2004\" tour with Canadian musicians. In 2005, he composed the soundtrack for the Korean film, ''[[Welcome to Dongmakgol]]'' ({{lang|ja|\uc6f0\ucef4 \ud22c \ub3d9\ub9c9\uace8}}). He also partook in Korea's historically landmarked big budget drama series production by composing the soundtrack for Korea's MBC drama series, ''[[The Legend (TV series)|The Legend]]'' ({{lang|ja|\ud0dc\uc655\uc0ac\uc2e0\uae30}} \"The Story of the First King's Four Gods\"), which released in 2007. Hisaishi has a large fan base in Korea due to the popularity of Miyazaki films.\n\n===2006\u20132013===\nIn 2006, Hisaishi released a studio album, ''Asian X.T.C.'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/24637|title=UPCI-1051 {{!}} Asian X.T.C. / Joe Hisaishi - VGMdb|website=vgmdb.net|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> the compositions of which demonstrated a significantly eclectic and contemporary Eastern style. The [[erhu]] [[musician|player]] of the Chinese band [[12 Girls Band]] Zhan Li Jun played in a live concert featuring music from that album. The following year, he composed and recorded the soundtrack for [[Frederic Lepage]]'s film, ''[[Sunny and the Elephant]]'' and the Miyazaki film, ''[[Ponyo on the Cliff by the Sea]]'', both released in 2008, as well as the score for [[Jiang Wen]]'s film, ''[[The Sun Also Rises (2007 film)|The Sun Also Rises]]'' (\u592a\u9633\u7167\u5e38\u5347\u8d77).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bachtrack.com/feature-joe-hisaishi-film-game-music-month-may-2017|title=A Flight Through the Music of Joe Hisaishi|website=bachtrack.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Hisaishi composed soundtracks for Academy Award-winning film ''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorefire.com/releases/entry/dream-songs-the-essential-joe-hisaishi-feb-21-decca-gold|title=Joe Hisaishi Announces Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi (Feb 21, Decca Gold)|last=https://plus.google.com/110686239645171179005|website=Shore Fire Media|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> as well as for {{Nihongo|''I'd Rather Be a Shellfish''|\u79c1\u306f\u8c9d\u306b\u306a\u308a\u305f\u3044|Watashi wa Kai ni Naritai}}, a post-[[World War II]] war crimes trial drama which is based on the 1959 Tetsutaro Kato novel and film currently being remade and directed by Katsuo Fukuzawa, starring [[Masahiro Nakai]] and [[Yukie Nakama]].\n\nIn August 2008 he arranged and performed in a concert conducting the World Dream Symphony Orchestra,<ref>{{cite web|title=World Dream Orchestra|url=https://www.njp.or.jp/en/about/wdo|website=New Japan Philharmonic|publisher=New Japan Philharmonic|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805060945/https://www.njp.or.jp/en/about/wdo|archivedate=5 August 2017}}</ref> and playing the piano on the occasion of his having worked for 25 years with the Animations of Hayao Miyazaki.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Hisaishi Special Gala Concert|url=http://www.fareastfilm.com/easyne2/eng/film/joe-hisaishi-special-gala-concert-4567.aspx?IDLYT=7505|website=The Film Festival For Popular Asian Cinema|publisher=Centro Espressioni Cinematografiche|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805062201/http://www.fareastfilm.com/easyne2/eng/film/joe-hisaishi-special-gala-concert-4567.aspx?IDLYT=7505|archivedate=5 August 2017}}</ref> This concert featured over 1200 musicians and sold out the world-famous [[Nippon Budokan|Budokan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattlesymphony.org/about/meetthemusicians/theorchestra/artists/a-h/hisaishi-joe|title=Joe Hisaishi|website=www.seattlesymphony.org|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nHisaishi also released a solo album in early 2009 featuring tracks from ''Shellfish'' and ''Departures''.\n\nIn 2010, he became an invited professor for Japanese National College of Music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npac-weiwuying.org/programs/5d9ff3bc8c6e1e0006cbe077|title=Joe Hisaishi's Music Future - Programs {{!}} National Kaohsiung Center for the Arts (Weiwuying)|website=www.npac-weiwuying.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hisaishi composed the score for the [[NHK]] wildlife documentary ''Legends of the Deep: [[Giant Squid]]'' {{Nihongo||\u4e16\u754c\u521d\u64ae\u5f71! \u6df1\u6d77\u306e\u8d85\u5de8\u5927\u30a4\u30ab||}},<ref>{{cite web|title=The Giant Squid, Captured on Camera in its Natural Habitat for the First Time Ever!|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/pr/english/press/pdf/20130109.pdf|website=[[NHK]]|accessdate=11 July 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004233759/http://www.nhk.or.jp/pr/english/press/pdf/20130109.pdf|archivedate=4 October 2013|date=9 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u5e7b\u306e\u6df1\u6d77\u5de8\u5927\u751f\u7269|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/ocean/giantcreature/|website=[[NHK]]|publisher=NHK|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130109094955/http://www.nhk.or.jp/ocean/giantcreature/|archivedate=9 January 2013|language=Japanese|quote=\u97f3\u697d\u30fb\u4e45\u77f3\u8b72\u3000\u6f14\u594f\u30fb\u6771\u4eac\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30c6\u30a3\u7ba1\u5f26\u697d\u56e3\u3002}}</ref> featuring the first-ever filming of this reclusive creature (narrated by [[David Attenborough]] for BBC's Natural World special ''Giant Squid: Filming the Impossible'').<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b0377t15/Natural_World_20132014_Giant_Squid_Filming_the_Impossible_Natural_World_Special/ BBC Two \u2013 Natural World, 2013\u20132014, Giant Squid: Filming the Impossible \u2013 Natural World Special] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327230553/http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b0377t15/Natural_World_20132014_Giant_Squid_Filming_the_Impossible_Natural_World_Special/|date=27 March 2014}}. Bbc.co.uk (23 March 2014). Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, Hisaishi was among those invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]. This honor is extended to those \"who have distinguished themselves by their contributions to theatrical motion pictures.\"<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2013/20130628.html Academy Invites 276 to Membership] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701193455/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2013/20130628.html|date=1 July 2013}}. Oscars.org. Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132019===\n\nIn 2016, he was inaugurated as art director of Nagano City Art Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/melbsymphony/docs/studio_ghibli_2018_concert_program_|title=Studio Ghibli Concert Program|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 he performed three concerts in Paris based on his setup for the 25-year Ghibli collaboration anniversary concert, performed in [[Palais des Congr\u00e8s de Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Hisaishi Symphonic Concert|url=http://overlook-events.com/portfolio/joehisaishisymphonicconcert/|website=Overlook Events|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170618224428/http://overlook-events.com/portfolio/joehisaishisymphonicconcert/|archivedate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Hisaishi performed five sold-out concerts in his North American debut in California, USA at the [[San Jose Center for the Performing Arts]] with [[Symphony Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanjosetheaters.org/event/joe-hisaishi-symphonic-concert-music-studio-ghibli-films-hayao-miyazaki/|title=Joe Hisaishi Symphonic Concert - Music from the Studio Ghibli Films of Hayao Miyazaki - San Jose Theaters|website=sanjosetheaters.org|language=en-US|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe also composed the soundtrack for the [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]] Nichiy\u014d Gekij\u014d drama ''[[In This Corner of the World]]''.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/in-this-corner-of-the-world-gets-live-action-series/|title=In This Corner of the World Gets Live Action Series|date=8 May 2018|website=MANGA.TOKYO|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2020\u2013present===\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi'' i like sushiwas released through [[Decca Gold]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/entertainment/new-music-royce-ozzy-osbourne-chainsmokers-grimes-and-more/article_62e0a058-5447-11ea-aaf6-d76405d52492.html|title=New Music: Royce 5'9\", Ozzy Osbourne, Chainsmokers, Grimes and more...|last=Twitter|first=Gary Graff ggraff@medianewsgroup com; @GraffonMusic on|website=The Oakland Press|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorefire.com/releases/entry/dream-songs-the-essential-joe-hisaishi-feb-21-decca-gold|title=Joe Hisaishi Announces Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi (Feb 21, Decca Gold)|last=https://plus.google.com/110686239645171179005|website=Shore Fire Media|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The album includes 28 compositions released over the course of his career.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nAs a result of his work throughout the years, Hisaishi has won the Japanese Academy Award for Best Music seven times\u2014in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=15|script-title=ja:\u7b2c15\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221233256/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=15|archivedate=February 21, 2011}}</ref> 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=16|script-title=ja:\u7b2c16\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221232725/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=16|archivedate=February 21, 2011}}</ref> 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=17|script-title=ja:\u7b2c17\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222032612/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=17|archivedate=February 22, 2011}}</ref> 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=22|script-title=ja:\u7b2c22\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155924/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=23|script-title=ja:\u7b2c23\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031043947/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=23|archivedate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|script-title=ja:\u7b2c32\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155924/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=34|script-title=ja:\u7b2c34\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 20, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515023535/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=34|archivedate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> He also received the 48th Newcomer Award in 1997 from the Ministry of Education (Public Entertainment Section) among numerous other awards, being recognized as an influential figure in the Japanese film industry. In 1998 he won the Art Choice Award for New Artist (Popular Performing Arts Division). In 2005, he won the 31st Annual Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award Music Prize at \"Howl's Moving Castle. In 2008, he received the 10th International Film Music Critics Association Award for Television Division Best Original Score Award in the music of Korean drama ''Queen Shikigami''.\n\nIn November 2009, he was awarded with a [[Medals of Honour (Japan)|Medal of Honour with purple ribbon]] by the [[Government of Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103072414/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20091102p2a00m0na011000c.html|archivedate=3 November 2009|url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20091102p2a00m0na011000c.html|title=678 individuals, 24 groups awarded Medals of Honor|publisher=Mainichi Shimbun|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-03/ghibli-composer-joe-hisaishi-awarded-medal-of-honour|title=Ghibli Composer Joe Hisaishi Awarded Medal of Honour|publisher=Anime News Network|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=26 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924185206/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-03/ghibli-composer-joe-hisaishi-awarded-medal-of-honour|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Joe Hisaishi discography}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;Notable compositions\n:''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (film)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]'' (1984)\n:''[[Laputa: Castle in the Sky]]'' (1986)\n:''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'' (1988)\n:''[[Kiki's Delivery Service]]'' (1989)\n:''[[Porco Rosso]]'' (1992)\n:''[[Sonatine (1993 film)|Sonatine]]'' (1993)\n:''[[Kids Return]]'' (1996)\n:''[[Princess Mononoke]]'' (1997)\n:''[[Hana-bi]]'' (1997)\n:''[[Kikujiro]]'' (1999)\n:''[[Brother (2000 film)|Brother]]'' (2000)\n:''[[Spirited Away]]'' (2001)\n:''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'' (2004)\n:''[[Ponyo]]'' (2008)\n:''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]'' (2008)\n:''[[The Wind Rises]]'' (2013)\n:''[[The Tale of the Princess Kaguya]]'' (2013)\n:''[[Ni no Kuni: Wrath of the White Witch]]'' (2013)\n:''[[Ni no Kuni II: Revenant Kingdom]]'' (2018)\n:''[[Children of the Sea (film)|Children of the Sea]]'' (2019)\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.joehisaishi.com/}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Twitter|official_joeh}}\n\n* {{ann|people|1196}}\n* {{IMDb name|0386749}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190824101023/https://mediaarts-db.jp/an/anime_series?utf8=%25E2%259C%2593&asf%255Bkeyword%255D=%25E4%25B9%2585%25E7%259F%25B3%25E8%25AD%25B2&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=tv_a&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=tv_sp&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=movie&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=ova&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=event&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=personal&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=etc&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=blank Joe Hisaishi anime] at Media Arts Database {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Studio Ghibli}}\n{{Mainichi Film Award for Best Music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hisaishi, Joe}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Animation composers]]\n[[Category:Anime composers]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Japanese classical composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese film score composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Kunitachi College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Music directors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Nagano Prefecture]]\n[[Category:People from Nagano Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal with Purple Ribbon]]\n[[Category:Studio Ghibli people]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation]]\n[[Category:Video game composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Japanese|\u4e45\u77f3\u8b72|topic=musician|reason=JA wikipedia is much better referenced than here, bring that article over|date=February 2016}}\n<!-- {{More footnotes|BLP=yes|date=February 2016|reason=use official website, ANN, and MADB to beef up biography}} -->\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Joe Hisaishi\n| image            = Joe Hisaishi 2011.jpg\n| caption          = Hisaishi in Paris in 2011\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name      = \u4e45\u77f3 \u8b72\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| birth_name       = Mamoru Fujisawa\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1950|12|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Nakano, Nagano]], Japan\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Piano]]\n* [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* [[violin]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Film score]]\n* [[classical (music)|classical]]\n* [[romantic era|romanticism]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Composer\n* conductor\n* arranger\n}}\n| years_active     = 1974\u2013present\n| website          = {{URL|joehisaishi.com}}\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Mamoru Fujisawa'''|\u85e4\u6fa4 \u5b88|''Fujisawa Mamoru''|born December 6, 1950}}, known professionally as {{Nihongo|'''Joe Hisaishi'''|\u4e45\u77f3 \u8b72|''Hisaishi J\u014d''}}, is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] composer and musical director known for over 100 [[soundtrack|film scores]] and solo albums dating back to 1981.<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90782/8336846.html Joe Hisaishi film score concerts \u2013 People's Daily Online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106040943/http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90782/8336846.html|date=6 January 2014}}. English.peopledaily.com.cn (23 July 2013). Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref> Hisaishi is also known for his piano scores.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferbosier/2013/01/08/joe-hisaishi-discusses-soundtrack-for-ni-no-kuni-wrath-of-the-white-witch/#68c3203856eb|title=Joe Hisaishi Discusses Soundtrack for 'Ni No Kuni: Wrath of the White Witch'|last=Bosier|first=Jen|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=11 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312023349/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferbosier/2013/01/08/joe-hisaishi-discusses-soundtrack-for-ni-no-kuni-wrath-of-the-white-witch/#68c3203856eb|archivedate=12 March 2018}}</ref>{{Better source|date=March 2018}}\n\nWhile possessing a stylistically distinct sound, Hisaishi's music has been known to explore and incorporate different genres, including [[minimalist music|minimalist]], [[electronic music|experimental electronic]], [[European classical music|European classical]], and [[Music of Japan|Japanese classical]]. Lesser known are the other musical roles he plays; he is also a [[typesetter]], author, arranger, and conductor.\n\nHe has been associated with animator [[Hayao Miyazaki]] since 1984, having composed scores for all but one of his films. He is also recognized for the soundtracks he has provided for filmmaker [[Takeshi Kitano|'Beat' Takeshi Kitano]], including ''[[A Scene at the Sea]]'' (1991), ''[[Sonatine (1993 film)|Sonatine]]'' (1993), ''[[Kids Return]]'' (1996), ''[[Hana-bi]]'' (1997), ''[[Kikujiro]]'' (1999), and ''[[Dolls (2002 film)|Dolls]]'' (2002), as well for the video game series ''[[Ni no Kuni]]''. He was a student of legendary anime composer [[Takeo Watanabe]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}<!-- Note that BBC Music uses content from Wikipedia. -->\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life===\nHisaishi was born in [[Nakano, Nagano]], Japan, as {{Nihongo|Mamoru Fujisawa|\u85e4\u6fa4 \u5b88|Fujisawa Mamoru}}. When he started learning violin in the Violin School Suzuki Shinichi at the age of four, he found his passion in music. At the same age, he also began watching 300 movies a year with his father, which influenced his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lovejapanese.com.au/joe-hisaishi-studio-ghibli-music-composer/|title=Joe Hisaishi - The Composer Behind Studio Ghibli Songs & Music|last=Japanese|first=Love|date=2018-08-12|website=Love Japanese - Japanese Language & Culture Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> Realizing his love, he attended the [[Kunitachi College of Music]] in 1969 to major in [[music composition]]. Hisaishi collaborated with [[Minimalist music|minimalist artists]] as a typesetter, furthering his experience in the musical world.\n\nHe enjoyed his first success of the business in 1974 when he composed music for the anime series called ''[[First Human Giatrus|Gyatoruzu]]''. This and other early works were created under his given name. During this period, he composed for ''Sasuga no Sarutobi'' (Academy of Ninja) and ''[[Futari Daka]]'' (A Full Throttle).\n\nIn the 1970s, [[Japanese popular music]], [[electronic music]], and new-age music flourished; those genres, as well as the [[Yellow Magic Orchestra]] (a Japanese electronic band in 1978\u20131983), influenced Hisaishi's compositions. He developed his music from [[Minimalist music|minimalist]] ideas and expanded toward orchestral work. Around 1975, Hisaishi presented his first public performance, spreading his name around his community. Also, from 1978, he had worked for Brass Compositions for a long time. His first album, ''MKWAJU'', was released in 1981, with ''Information'' being released a year later. His first major anime scores were ''Hajime Ningen Gyatoruz'' (1974) and ''Robokko Beeton'' (1976).\n\nAs his works were becoming well known, Hisaishi formulated an alias inspired by [[Quincy Jones]], an African-American musician and producer. Retranscribed in Japanese, \"Quincy Jones\" became \"Joe Hisaishi\". (\"Quincy\", pronounced \"Kuinsh\u012b\u201d in Japanese, can be written using the same [[kanji]] in \"Hisaishi\"; \"Joe\" comes from \"Jones\".)<ref>[http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/hisaishi/ Joe Hisaishi// Who's Who //] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128025222/http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/hisaishi/|date=November 28, 2013}}. Nausicaa.net. Retrieved on 2015-08-18.</ref>\n\n===1981\u201398: Anime film industry===\nIn 1981 Hisaishi, with his new name, released his first album of art music, ''MKWAJU'', and in 1982 the electropop-minimalist album ''Information''. Then, in 1983, Hisaishi was recommended by Tokuma, who had published ''Information'', to create an image album for ''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (film)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]''. Hisaishi and the director of the animated film, [[Hayao Miyazaki]], became great friends and would work together on many future projects.\n\nIn 1985, he founded his own recording studio\u2014the wonder station. Their collaboration has invited comparisons to the collaborations of [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[John Williams]]. This big break led to Hisaishi's overwhelming success as a composer of film scores. In 1986, ''[[Laputa: Castle in the Sky]]'' would be the first feature to appear under the Studio Ghibli banner, and its gentle, faintly melancholic tone would become a familiar trademark of much of the studio's later output.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/17384/looking-back-at-laputa-castle-in-the-sky|title=Looking back at Laputa: Castle In The Sky|work=Den of Geek|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312023108/http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/17384/looking-back-at-laputa-castle-in-the-sky|archivedate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> And later, in the 1990s, ''[[Porco Rosso]]'' and ''[[Princess Mononoke]]'' were released. As Hisaishi strengthened his reputation as one of the budding [[anime]] industry's top musical contributors, his compositions (including eight theatrical films and one [[Original video animation|OAV]]) would proceed to become some of the very hallmarks of early anime in the 1980s and 1990s. Hisaishi also composed for such TV and movie hits as ''Sasuga no Sarutobi'', ''Two Down Full Base'', ''Tonde Mon Pe'' and the anime [[Techno Police 21C|''Tekuno porisu 21C'']] (all 1982), ''Sasuraiger'' (1983), ''[[Futari Daka|Futari Taka]]'' (1984), [[Hon\u014d no Alpen Rose: Judy & Randy|''Hon\u014d no Alpen Rose'']] (1985) and ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1986 TV series)|Oz no mah\u00f4tsukai]]'' (1986). He also scored the sci-fi adventure series ''[[Mospeada]]'' (1983), which was later reworked (without his music) into the third segment of Carl Macek's compilation, ''[[Robotech]]''. Other films he scored included ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam|Mobile Suit Gundam Movie II: Soldiers of Sorrow]]'' (1981), ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam|Mobile Suit Gundam Movie III: Encounters in Space]]'', (1982), ''[[Birth (anime)|Birth (B\u00e2su)]]'' (1984), ''[[Arion (anime)|Arion]]'' (1986), ''[[Robot Carnival]]'' (1987), ''[[My Neighbor Totoro|Totoro]]'' (1988), ''[[Crest of the Royal Family]]'' and ''[[Maison Ikkoku|Maison Ikkoku \u2013 Apartment Fantasy]]'' (both 1988), ''[[Venus Wars]]'' (1989), ''[[Kiki's Delivery Service]]'' (1989), ''[[Porco Rosso]]'' (1992) and ''[[Ocean Heaven]]'' (2010). He also did theme song arrangements and composed other anime opening, closing, and insert title theme songs such as ''[[Lalabel|Mah\u014d Sh\u014djo Lalabel]]'' (1980), ''[[Hello! Sandybell]]'' (1981), ''[[Meiken Jolie]]'' (1981), ''[[Voltron]]'' (1981), ''[[Ai Shite Knight]]'' (1983), ''[[Creamy Mami, the Magic Angel|Creamy Mami, the Magic Angel: Curtain Call]]'' (1986), and ''[[Kimagure Orange Road: The Movie]]'' (1988).\n\nAs more exposure was given to Hisaishi and the [[anime]] industry, his career grew. He initiated a solo career, began to produce music, and created his own label (Wonder Land Inc.) in 1988. A year later, Hisaishi released his solo album ''Pretender'' as the first album under the new label.\n\n===1998\u20132004: Worldwide success===\nIn 1998, Hisaishi provided the soundtrack to the [[1998 Winter Paralympics]]. The following year, he composed the music for the third installment in a series of popular computer-animated educational films about the human body. Again in 1999, he composed the score for the Takeshi Kitano film ''[[Kikujiro]]'', whose title track ''Summer'' went on to become one of Hisaishi's most recognizable compositions.\n\nIn 2001, Hisaishi produced music for another Kitano film, ''Brother'', and Hayao Miyazaki's animated film, ''[[Spirited Away]]''. He also served as executive producer of the Night Fantasia 4 Movement at the Japan Expo in Fukushima 2001. On October 6, Hisaishi made his debut as a film director in ''Quartet'', having also written both its music and script. The film received excellent reviews at the [[Montreal Film Festival]]. His first soundtrack for a foreign film, ''Le Petit Poucet'', was released in the same year.\n\n[[File:Joe Hisaishi in Krakow.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Hisaishi in Krak\u00f3w, 2011]]\n\nAnother Miyazaki film, ''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'', for which Hisaishi composed the score, was released on November 20, 2004, in Japan. From November 3 to 29, 2004, Hisaishi embarked on his \"Joe Hisaishi Freedom \u2013 Piano Stories 2004\" tour with Canadian musicians. In 2005, he composed the soundtrack for the Korean film, ''[[Welcome to Dongmakgol]]'' ({{lang|ja|\uc6f0\ucef4 \ud22c \ub3d9\ub9c9\uace8}}). He also partook in Korea's historically landmarked big budget drama series production by composing the soundtrack for Korea's MBC drama series, ''[[The Legend (TV series)|The Legend]]'' ({{lang|ja|\ud0dc\uc655\uc0ac\uc2e0\uae30}} \"The Story of the First King's Four Gods\"), which released in 2007. Hisaishi has a large fan base in Korea due to the popularity of Miyazaki films.\n\n===2006\u20132013===\nIn 2006, Hisaishi released a studio album, ''Asian X.T.C.'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/24637|title=UPCI-1051 {{!}} Asian X.T.C. / Joe Hisaishi - VGMdb|website=vgmdb.net|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> the compositions of which demonstrated a significantly eclectic and contemporary Eastern style. The [[erhu]] [[musician|player]] of the Chinese band [[12 Girls Band]] Zhan Li Jun played in a live concert featuring music from that album. The following year, he composed and recorded the soundtrack for [[Frederic Lepage]]'s film, ''[[Sunny and the Elephant]]'' and the Miyazaki film, ''[[Ponyo on the Cliff by the Sea]]'', both released in 2008, as well as the score for [[Jiang Wen]]'s film, ''[[The Sun Also Rises (2007 film)|The Sun Also Rises]]'' (\u592a\u9633\u7167\u5e38\u5347\u8d77).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bachtrack.com/feature-joe-hisaishi-film-game-music-month-may-2017|title=A Flight Through the Music of Joe Hisaishi|website=bachtrack.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Hisaishi composed soundtracks for Academy Award-winning film ''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorefire.com/releases/entry/dream-songs-the-essential-joe-hisaishi-feb-21-decca-gold|title=Joe Hisaishi Announces Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi (Feb 21, Decca Gold)|last=https://plus.google.com/110686239645171179005|website=Shore Fire Media|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> as well as for {{Nihongo|''I'd Rather Be a Shellfish''|\u79c1\u306f\u8c9d\u306b\u306a\u308a\u305f\u3044|Watashi wa Kai ni Naritai}}, a post-[[World War II]] war crimes trial drama which is based on the 1959 Tetsutaro Kato novel and film currently being remade and directed by Katsuo Fukuzawa, starring [[Masahiro Nakai]] and [[Yukie Nakama]].\n\nIn August 2008 he arranged and performed in a concert conducting the World Dream Symphony Orchestra,<ref>{{cite web|title=World Dream Orchestra|url=https://www.njp.or.jp/en/about/wdo|website=New Japan Philharmonic|publisher=New Japan Philharmonic|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805060945/https://www.njp.or.jp/en/about/wdo|archivedate=5 August 2017}}</ref> and playing the piano on the occasion of his having worked for 25 years with the Animations of Hayao Miyazaki.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Hisaishi Special Gala Concert|url=http://www.fareastfilm.com/easyne2/eng/film/joe-hisaishi-special-gala-concert-4567.aspx?IDLYT=7505|website=The Film Festival For Popular Asian Cinema|publisher=Centro Espressioni Cinematografiche|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805062201/http://www.fareastfilm.com/easyne2/eng/film/joe-hisaishi-special-gala-concert-4567.aspx?IDLYT=7505|archivedate=5 August 2017}}</ref> This concert featured over 1200 musicians and sold out the world-famous [[Nippon Budokan|Budokan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattlesymphony.org/about/meetthemusicians/theorchestra/artists/a-h/hisaishi-joe|title=Joe Hisaishi|website=www.seattlesymphony.org|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nHisaishi also released a solo album in early 2009 featuring tracks from ''Shellfish'' and ''Departures''.\n\nIn 2010, he became an invited professor for Japanese National College of Music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npac-weiwuying.org/programs/5d9ff3bc8c6e1e0006cbe077|title=Joe Hisaishi's Music Future - Programs {{!}} National Kaohsiung Center for the Arts (Weiwuying)|website=www.npac-weiwuying.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hisaishi composed the score for the [[NHK]] wildlife documentary ''Legends of the Deep: [[Giant Squid]]'' {{Nihongo||\u4e16\u754c\u521d\u64ae\u5f71! \u6df1\u6d77\u306e\u8d85\u5de8\u5927\u30a4\u30ab||}},<ref>{{cite web|title=The Giant Squid, Captured on Camera in its Natural Habitat for the First Time Ever!|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/pr/english/press/pdf/20130109.pdf|website=[[NHK]]|accessdate=11 July 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004233759/http://www.nhk.or.jp/pr/english/press/pdf/20130109.pdf|archivedate=4 October 2013|date=9 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u5e7b\u306e\u6df1\u6d77\u5de8\u5927\u751f\u7269|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/ocean/giantcreature/|website=[[NHK]]|publisher=NHK|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130109094955/http://www.nhk.or.jp/ocean/giantcreature/|archivedate=9 January 2013|language=Japanese|quote=\u97f3\u697d\u30fb\u4e45\u77f3\u8b72\u3000\u6f14\u594f\u30fb\u6771\u4eac\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30c6\u30a3\u7ba1\u5f26\u697d\u56e3\u3002}}</ref> featuring the first-ever filming of this reclusive creature (narrated by [[David Attenborough]] for BBC's Natural World special ''Giant Squid: Filming the Impossible'').<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b0377t15/Natural_World_20132014_Giant_Squid_Filming_the_Impossible_Natural_World_Special/ BBC Two \u2013 Natural World, 2013\u20132014, Giant Squid: Filming the Impossible \u2013 Natural World Special] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327230553/http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b0377t15/Natural_World_20132014_Giant_Squid_Filming_the_Impossible_Natural_World_Special/|date=27 March 2014}}. Bbc.co.uk (23 March 2014). Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, Hisaishi was among those invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]. This honor is extended to those \"who have distinguished themselves by their contributions to theatrical motion pictures.\"<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2013/20130628.html Academy Invites 276 to Membership] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701193455/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2013/20130628.html|date=1 July 2013}}. Oscars.org. Retrieved on 12 May 2014.</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132019===\n\nIn 2016, he was inaugurated as art director of Nagano City Art Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/melbsymphony/docs/studio_ghibli_2018_concert_program_|title=Studio Ghibli Concert Program|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 he performed three concerts in Paris based on his setup for the 25-year Ghibli collaboration anniversary concert, performed in [[Palais des Congr\u00e8s de Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Hisaishi Symphonic Concert|url=http://overlook-events.com/portfolio/joehisaishisymphonicconcert/|website=Overlook Events|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170618224428/http://overlook-events.com/portfolio/joehisaishisymphonicconcert/|archivedate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Hisaishi performed five sold-out concerts in his North American debut in California, USA at the [[San Jose Center for the Performing Arts]] with [[Symphony Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanjosetheaters.org/event/joe-hisaishi-symphonic-concert-music-studio-ghibli-films-hayao-miyazaki/|title=Joe Hisaishi Symphonic Concert - Music from the Studio Ghibli Films of Hayao Miyazaki - San Jose Theaters|website=sanjosetheaters.org|language=en-US|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe also composed the soundtrack for the [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]] Nichiy\u014d Gekij\u014d drama ''[[In This Corner of the World]]''.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/in-this-corner-of-the-world-gets-live-action-series/|title=In This Corner of the World Gets Live Action Series|date=8 May 2018|website=MANGA.TOKYO|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2020\u2013present===\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi'' was released through [[Decca Gold]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/entertainment/new-music-royce-ozzy-osbourne-chainsmokers-grimes-and-more/article_62e0a058-5447-11ea-aaf6-d76405d52492.html|title=New Music: Royce 5'9\", Ozzy Osbourne, Chainsmokers, Grimes and more...|last=Twitter|first=Gary Graff ggraff@medianewsgroup com; @GraffonMusic on|website=The Oakland Press|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorefire.com/releases/entry/dream-songs-the-essential-joe-hisaishi-feb-21-decca-gold|title=Joe Hisaishi Announces Dream Songs: The Essential Joe Hisaishi (Feb 21, Decca Gold)|last=https://plus.google.com/110686239645171179005|website=Shore Fire Media|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The album includes 28 compositions released over the course of his career.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nAs a result of his work throughout the years, Hisaishi has won the Japanese Academy Award for Best Music seven times\u2014in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=15|script-title=ja:\u7b2c15\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221233256/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=15|archivedate=February 21, 2011}}</ref> 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=16|script-title=ja:\u7b2c16\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221232725/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=16|archivedate=February 21, 2011}}</ref> 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=17|script-title=ja:\u7b2c17\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222032612/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=17|archivedate=February 22, 2011}}</ref> 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=22|script-title=ja:\u7b2c22\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155924/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=23|script-title=ja:\u7b2c23\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031043947/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=23|archivedate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|script-title=ja:\u7b2c32\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 23, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155924/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32|archivedate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=34|script-title=ja:\u7b2c34\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|publisher=Japan Academy Prize|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 20, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515023535/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=34|archivedate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> He also received the 48th Newcomer Award in 1997 from the Ministry of Education (Public Entertainment Section) among numerous other awards, being recognized as an influential figure in the Japanese film industry. In 1998 he won the Art Choice Award for New Artist (Popular Performing Arts Division). In 2005, he won the 31st Annual Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award Music Prize at \"Howl's Moving Castle. In 2008, he received the 10th International Film Music Critics Association Award for Television Division Best Original Score Award in the music of Korean drama ''Queen Shikigami''.\n\nIn November 2009, he was awarded with a [[Medals of Honour (Japan)|Medal of Honour with purple ribbon]] by the [[Government of Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103072414/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20091102p2a00m0na011000c.html|archivedate=3 November 2009|url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20091102p2a00m0na011000c.html|title=678 individuals, 24 groups awarded Medals of Honor|publisher=Mainichi Shimbun|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-03/ghibli-composer-joe-hisaishi-awarded-medal-of-honour|title=Ghibli Composer Joe Hisaishi Awarded Medal of Honour|publisher=Anime News Network|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=26 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924185206/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-11-03/ghibli-composer-joe-hisaishi-awarded-medal-of-honour|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Joe Hisaishi discography}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;Notable compositions\n:''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (film)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]'' (1984)\n:''[[Laputa: Castle in the Sky]]'' (1986)\n:''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'' (1988)\n:''[[Kiki's Delivery Service]]'' (1989)\n:''[[Porco Rosso]]'' (1992)\n:''[[Sonatine (1993 film)|Sonatine]]'' (1993)\n:''[[Kids Return]]'' (1996)\n:''[[Princess Mononoke]]'' (1997)\n:''[[Hana-bi]]'' (1997)\n:''[[Kikujiro]]'' (1999)\n:''[[Brother (2000 film)|Brother]]'' (2000)\n:''[[Spirited Away]]'' (2001)\n:''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'' (2004)\n:''[[Ponyo]]'' (2008)\n:''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]'' (2008)\n:''[[The Wind Rises]]'' (2013)\n:''[[The Tale of the Princess Kaguya]]'' (2013)\n:''[[Ni no Kuni: Wrath of the White Witch]]'' (2013)\n:''[[Ni no Kuni II: Revenant Kingdom]]'' (2018)\n:''[[Children of the Sea (film)|Children of the Sea]]'' (2019)\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.joehisaishi.com/}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Twitter|official_joeh}}\n\n* {{ann|people|1196}}\n* {{IMDb name|0386749}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190824101023/https://mediaarts-db.jp/an/anime_series?utf8=%25E2%259C%2593&asf%255Bkeyword%255D=%25E4%25B9%2585%25E7%259F%25B3%25E8%25AD%25B2&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=tv_a&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=tv_sp&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=movie&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=ova&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=event&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=personal&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=etc&asf%255Bmedia%255D%255B%255D=blank Joe 