{"title_page": "Eighth Grade (film)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|2018 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Eighth Grade\n| image          = Eighth Grade.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Bo Burnham]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Scott Rudin]]|[[Eli Bush]]|Lila Yacoub|Christopher Storer}}\n| writer         = Bo Burnham\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Elsie Fisher]]|[[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]]|[[Emily Robinson]]|Jake Ryan|Fred Hechinger}}\n| music          = [[Anna Meredith]]\n| cinematography = Andrew Wehde\n| editing        = Jennifer Lilly\n| production companies = {{ubl|[[A24 (company)|A24]]|IAC Films|Scott Rudin Productions}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(United States)}}\n* [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] {{small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|1|19|[[2018 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2018|7|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/review/2018/07/19/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-is-exquisitely-awkward.html |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade is exquisitely awkward |first=Peter |last=Howell |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |date=October 11, 2018 |work=[[The Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727081103/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/review/2018/07/19/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-is-exquisitely-awkward.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million<ref name=\"Sandberg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-eighth-grade-how-bo-burnham-brought-his-anxiety-screen-1162239 |title=Making of 'Eighth Grade': How Bo Burnham Brought His Anxiety to Screen in the Form of a 13-Year-Old Girl |first=Bryn Elise |last=Sandberg |accessdate=November 23, 2018 |date=November 20, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120205033/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-eighth-grade-how-bo-burnham-brought-his-anxiety-screen-1162239 |archive-date=November 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> \n| gross          = $14.3 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Eighth-Grade-(2018)#tab=summary|title=''Eighth Grade'' (2018)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Eighth Grade''''' is a 2018 American [[coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Bo Burnham]]. It stars [[Elsie Fisher]] as Kayla, a [[middle school]] teenager who struggles with [[anxiety]] but strives to gain social acceptance from her peers on their final week of [[eighth grade]]. To cope, she publishes [[Vlog|video blogs]] as a self-styled motivational advice-giver, though spends much of her time obsessing over [[social media]]. This frustrates Kayla's otherwise supportive father ([[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]]), whom she alienates despite his wish to be present in her life as her sole parent.\n\nThe film is Burnham's feature-length debut as a writer and director. He began the screenplay in 2014 to reflect on his own anxiety and [[panic attack]]s stemming from his career as a [[comedian]]. Deciding to convey his experience through Kayla, he also wanted to explore how [[Generation Z|her generation]] cope with mental illness, grow with the presence of social media, navigate [[sexuality]] and [[Sexual consent|consent]], relate to their parents and develop their [[Self-awareness|sense of self]]. Burnham aimed for realism, casting actual eighth graders \u2014 including lead actress Fisher \u2014 who informed his script and directing. For research, he watched vlogs from teenagers on [[YouTube]], where he also discovered Fisher. [[Independent film|Independently financed]] with a small $2 million budget, production took place in 2017, in the suburban town of [[Suffern, New York]].\n\n''Eighth Grade'' premiered on January 19, 2018 at [[Sundance Film Festival]]. It was later given wide theatrical release in the United States on July 13, 2018 by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. Instead of appealing the Motion Picture Association of America's [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film rating|R (Restricted)]] rating of the film, A24 and Burnham arranged free all-ages theatrical screenings in every state to let their young intended audience to more easily see it.\n\nUpon release, the film was a critical and commercial success. Burnham's writing, direction and Fisher's performance drew the most praise from critics, while domestic box office sales topped $13.5 million. The filmmakers won [[List of accolades received by Eighth Grade|many awards and nominations]], with Burnham winning both [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2018|Writers Guild]] and [[71st Directors Guild of America Awards|Directors Guild of America]] Awards, and Fisher nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe]] for Best Actress and winning the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Gotham Award for Breakthrough Actor]]. At years' end, the [[National Board of Review Awards 2018|National Board of Review]] and the [[American Film Institute Awards 2018#Top 10 Films|American Film Institute]] each chose ''Eighth Grade''  as one of the top-ten films of 2018, with the former naming Burnham's film as the year's Best Directorial Debut.\n\n==Plot==\nKayla Day is an [[eighth grade]] student finishing her final week at Miles Grove Middle School, a public school in the state of New York. She posts motivational videos on [[YouTube]] about confidence and self-image that get little to no views. Shy and struggling to make friends at school, she is voted \"Most Quiet\" by her classmates. Meanwhile, Mark, her single father, struggles to connect with her and break her reliance on social media.\n\nShe is invited to a pool party hosted by her classmate, Kennedy, who has done so only after being forced by her mother. At the party, Kayla has an [[panic attack]] in the bathroom but eventually goes outside to swim, where she meets Gabe, Kennedy's eccentric cousin. After trying to leave the party, Kayla has an awkward encounter with her crush, Aiden, who suggests that she rejoin the group. She overcomes her fear and volunteers to sing karaoke.\n\nHearing that Aiden broke up with his last girlfriend because she refused to send him nude photos, Kayla mentions to him in passing that she has a dirty photos folder on her phone, a fabricated story that piques his interest. He asks if she gives [[Fellatio|blowjobs]], and she says yes, unsure of what to say. She later looks up oral-sex instructions online and is disgusted.\n\nKayla attends a [[high school]] shadow program, where she meets Olivia, a friendly twelfth grader who shows her around the high school. Olivia gives Kayla her number, and she later invites Kayla to visit the [[Palisades Center|mall]] with some of her friends. They have a good time, though Kayla spots her father spying from afar and, embarrassed, tells him to leave. Olivia's friend Riley gives Kayla a ride home late at night. He initiates an awkward game of [[truth or dare]] where he asks about her sexual experience, takes off his shirt, and asks her to remove hers. She refuses, and he backs off, angrily claiming he was just trying to help her gain some experience. Kayla breaks down at home and is comforted by her father. She makes a video announcing that she intends to stop making videos, as she is not the person she pretends to be and feels unfit to give advice.\n\nKayla then opens a time capsule she created for herself in [[sixth grade]]. She watches a video she made where her past self asks questions about her current friends and love life. She asks her dad to help her burn the time capsule and asks if she makes him sad. He says that she fills him with pride and he could never be sad about her, and she hugs him tightly.\n\nAt graduation, Kayla rebukes Kennedy for ignoring her thank-you letter and acting indifferent towards her despite Kayla's attempts to be nice. She later has dinner at Gabe's house and they enjoy their time together. Kayla makes a new time capsule which she and her father bury in the backyard; she leaves a video message for her high school self encouraging her to persevere through tough times.\n\n==Cast==\nThe cast includes:<ref name=\"Debruge\"/>\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Elsie Fisher]] as Kayla Day\n* [[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]] as Mark Day\n* [[Emily Robinson]] as Olivia\n* Catherine Oliviere as Kennedy Graves\n* Jake Ryan as Gabe\n* Luke Prael as Aiden Wilson\n* Daniel Zolghadri as Riley\n* Fred Hechinger as Trevor\n* Imani Lewis as Aniyah\n}}\n\n==Themes==\nThe film explores anxiety.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/07/how-kanye-helped-bo-burnham-go-from-stand-up-to-eighth-grade.html |title=How Kanye Helped Bo Burnham Go From Having Panic Attacks Onstage to a Creative Breakthrough to Making Eighth Grade |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Fox |first=Jesse David |date=July 2, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204150036/https://www.vulture.com/2018/07/how-kanye-helped-bo-burnham-go-from-stand-up-to-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=December 4, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Burham: 'I wanted to make a movie about someone that\u2019s living with the internet as a texture, someone that\u2019s living with their anxiety untethered'. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/18/630069876/director-bo-burnham-on-growing-up-with-anxiety-and-an-audience |title=Director Bo Burnham On Growing Up With Anxiety \u2014 And An Audience |publisher=[[NPR]] |last=Gross |first=Terry |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219090848/https://www.npr.org/2018/07/18/630069876/director-bo-burnham-on-growing-up-with-anxiety-and-an-audience |archive-date=December 19, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Burnham says the character was inspired by a period in his early 20s when he was dealing with panic attacks onstage. }}</ref> Professor Julianna W. Miner, writing in 2018 about ''Eighth Grade'', reflects that 22% of teenagers were struggling with depression and anxiety, and teenage girls were committing suicide at higher rates in 2015 than they were in the previous 40 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/parenting/wp/2018/09/06/how-to-use-eighth-grade-to-jump-start-some-important-conversations-with-your-teen/?noredirect=on |title=How to use 'Eighth Grade' to jump-start some important conversations with your teen |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Miner |first=Julianna W. |date=September 6, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909024530/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/parenting/wp/2018/09/06/how-to-use-eighth-grade-to-jump-start-some-important-conversations-with-your-teen/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.c772696929b5 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The anxiety depicted is typical in middle school, but according to reporter Valerie Strauss, also reflects life in 2018 where people of all ages see a \"cacophony of indifference and downright meanness\".<ref name=\"Strauss\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2018/08/16/bo-burnhams-dead-on-film-eighth-grade-is-about-more-than-the-angst-of-eighth-grade/ |title=Bo Burnham's dead-on film 'Eighth Grade' is about more than the angst of eighth grade |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |date=August 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909024638/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2018/08/16/bo-burnhams-dead-on-film-eighth-grade-is-about-more-than-the-angst-of-eighth-grade/?utm_term=.4b28eb7261b1 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The words \"um\" and \"like\" in the screenplay also reflect \"the process of struggling\", rather than the characters' lack of intelligence.<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/how-bo-burnham-uses-like-language-to-um-capture-an-age-of-like-anxiety-in-eighth-grade |title=How Bo Burnham uses, like, language to, um, capture an age of, like, anxiety in Eighth Grade |work=[[National Post]] |last=Knight |first=Chris |date=July 19, 2018  |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20180909024145/https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/how-bo-burnham-uses-like-language-to-um-capture-an-age-of-like-anxiety-in-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[file:textinginclass.jpg|thumb|Texting and social media are featured prominently in the film.]]\nCritic [[Owen Gleiberman]] wrote that ''Eighth Grade'' was a trailblazer in examining youth who never knew a world without the [[Internet]], touching on [[sexting]] as well.<ref name=\"Gleiberman\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/eighth-grade-nails-youth-culture-in-the-digital-age-elsie-fisher-bo-burnham-1202895674/ |title='Eighth Grade' Is the First Movie to Nail Youth Culture in the Digital Age |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |date=August 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908210817/https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/eighth-grade-nails-youth-culture-in-the-digital-age-elsie-fisher-bo-burnham-1202895674/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[CBS News]] also commented that besides \"the usual teen angst and acne\", ''Eighth Grade'' depicts how Kayla spends a great deal of time on the Internet and engaging in [[text messaging]]. This reflects general trends in \"[[Generation Z|iGen]]\" (post-[[millennials]]), where 94% of youth have used [[smartphones]] by age 14.<ref name=\"DAmelio\"/> A 2018 U.S. poll found 45% of teenagers reported \"almost constantly\" using the Internet. 24% called its effects \"mostly negative\", while 45% characterized it as \"neither negative nor positive\".<ref name=\"Arkin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/movies/eighth-grade-goes-inside-mind-iphone-addled-teen-girl-n890606 |title='Eighth Grade' goes inside the mind of an iPhone-addled teen girl |publisher=[[NBC News]] |last=Arkin |first=Daniel |date=July 14, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817232206/https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/movies/eighth-grade-goes-inside-mind-iphone-addled-teen-girl-n890606 |archive-date=August 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Elsie Fisher, \"for Kayla, social media is almost religious\".<ref name=\"Arkin\"/> Burnham explained, \"social media has made me think differently as a person. It's made me more anxious, I think\". Professor [[Jean Twenge]] also connected an increase in Internet usage to a decline in juvenile [[mental health]].<ref name=\"DAmelio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/social-media-and-adolescence-eighth-grade-bo-burnham/ |title=Social media, the scourge of adolescence |publisher=[[CBS News]] |last=D'Amelio |first=John |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035444/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/social-media-and-adolescence-eighth-grade-bo-burnham/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Gleiberman called the depiction an examination of \"overwhelming \u2014 and, I would argue, unprecedented \u2014 woe that teenagers today can feel\".<ref name=\"Gleiberman\"/> Author Robert Barker contrasted ''Eighth Grade'' to earlier coming-of-age films such as ''[[Fast Times at Ridgemont High]]'' (1982) and ''[[Mean Girls]]'' (2004). Rather than work through cliques, Barker wrote Kayla and others are on \"a digital war of all against all, preening, pretending, and pontificating as much to themselves as to an anonymous audience\". Barker also saw the sexting between characters as representing their obliviousness to lost innocence.<ref name=\"Barker\">{{cite web |url=https://brightlightsfilm.com/wp-content/cache/all/coming-of-digital-age-on-bo-burnhams-eighth-grade/#.W5NSbuhKjIV |title=Coming of Digital Age: On Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade |work=[[Bright Lights Film Journal]] |last=Barker |first=Robert |date=August 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180908210817/https://brightlightsfilm.com/wp-content/cache/all/coming-of-digital-age-on-bo-burnhams-eighth-grade/%23.W5Q6MdLLfK6#.W5NSbuhKjIV |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[NPR]] interpreted the impact of the Internet during maturation as \"one of the key subjects of ''Eighth Grade''\", commenting on how many people may not remember the age fondly, but social media has added complications. Even so, NPR stated Kayla is still able to grow despite great challenges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/13/628385837/eighth-grade-captures-awkwardness-and-impermanence-of-american-adolescence |title='Eighth Grade' Captures Awkwardness And Impermanence Of American Adolescence |publisher=[[NPR]] |last=Chang |first=Justin |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822022306/https://www.npr.org/2018/07/13/628385837/eighth-grade-captures-awkwardness-and-impermanence-of-american-adolescence |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to critic Kyle Buchanan, \"The biggest mystery to ... [Kayla] is the opposite sex\", considering her interest in Aiden and taking online lessons about fellatio.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |title=How Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade Reflects Our #MeToo Moment |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |date=January 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819174125/http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, journalist Chris O'Falt suggested Kayla is not truly ready for sex, but simply is \"pressured to barter [her] sexuality for social acceptance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-rated-r-mpaa-teenagers-problem-1201983811/ |title='Eighth Grade': Why 13-Year-Olds Aren\u2019t Allowed to See a Movie About Themselves |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=O'Falt |first=Chris |date=July 14, 2018 |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510020119/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-rated-r-mpaa-teenagers-problem-1201983811/ |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' mentioned Kayla's claim to Aiden that she has nude selfies as being among the \"classic middle-school indignities\" depicted in ''Eighth Grade''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/5336639/bo-burnham-eighth-grade/ |title=How Bo Burnham Turns Anxiety Into a Work of Art |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |last=Luscombe |first=Belinda |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717204221/http://time.com/5336639/bo-burnham-eighth-grade/ |archive-date=July 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham also criticized American [[sex education]] for not exploring [[sexual consent]], as reflected in the \"truth or dare\" scene.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |title=Q&A: 'Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham says sex ed needs to be better |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Chval |first=Lauren |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035622/http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Although Kayla is shown to be in a sex education class earlier in the film, she does not know how to react when Riley sexually coerces her, and apologizes to him for rejecting his advances.<ref name=\"Buchanan\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-director-bo-burnham-uncomfortable-car-scene/ |title='Eighth Grade' Director on Why 'Uncomfortable' Car Scene Reflects 'Culture's Failure of These Kids' |work=[[The Wrap]] |last1=Williams |first1=Trey |last2=Verhoeven |first2=Beatrice |date=July 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035657/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-director-bo-burnham-uncomfortable-car-scene/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Film critics connected the scene with the [[Me Too movement]],<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |title=Q&A: 'Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham says sex ed needs to be better |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Chval |first=Lauren |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=The scene between Kayla and Riley really struck a chord with me and felt somewhat parallel to the #MeToo movement. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035622/http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/07/eighths-grades-me-too-scene-bo-burnham-movie-review.html |title=Eighth Grade's #MeToo Scene Will Shake You to Your Core |website=[[Thecut.com]] |last=Silman |first=Anna |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=One of the most powerful #MeToo moments on-screen this year features not an actual sexual assault but the implied threat of one. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035816/https://www.thecut.com/2018/07/eighths-grades-me-too-scene-bo-burnham-movie-review.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |title=How Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade Reflects Our #MeToo Moment |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |date=January 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=After months of sexual-misconduct claims in Hollywood and an ensuing wave of change and debate that has happened all over the world, it was hard not to think of those real-life events while watching ''Eighth Grade''. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819174125/http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> though it written before the movement began. At festival screenings, moviegoers were visibly uncomfortable and yelled during the scene.<ref name=\"RyanMeToo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/12/eighth-grade-me-too-moment-plays-like-horror-movie/775581002/ |title=Why that disturbing #MeToo moment in 'Eighth Grade' has everyone talking |work=[[USA Today]] |last=Ryan |first=Patrick |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035641/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/12/eighth-grade-me-too-moment-plays-like-horror-movie/775581002/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe story also explores Kayla's relationship with her father Mark, a member of [[Generation X]],<ref name=\"Knight\"/> whom she is breaking away from, exhibiting typical behavior for her age.<ref name=\"Strauss\"/> His attempts to communicate with her are frustrated by her fixation with her smartphone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/20/eighth-grade-dad-13-year-old-relatable-scene/ |title=Eighth Grade: Dad trying to relate to his 13-year-old is most relatable scene of the year |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |last=Schwartz |first=Dana |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909073614/https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/20/eighth-grade-dad-13-year-old-relatable-scene/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, journalist Sonia Rao judged Mark to be \"the only constant presence in her life\";<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20180916/sensitive-single-dads-raising-daughters-have-taken-over-our-movie-screens |title=Sensitive single dads raising daughters have taken over our movie screens |work=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]] |last=Rao |first=Sonia |date=September 16, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917125829/https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20180916/sensitive-single-dads-raising-daughters-have-taken-over-our-movie-screens |archive-date=September 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Mark is devoted to Kayla and later tells her he is proud of her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/07/eight-grade-is-a-great-movie-about-josh-hamiltons-hot-dad.html |title=Eighth Grade Is a Great Movie About a Dad Who Is Hot |website=[[Slate.com]] |last=Kang |first=Inkoo |date=July 23, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823031245/https://slate.com/culture/2018/07/eight-grade-is-a-great-movie-about-josh-hamiltons-hot-dad.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Bo Burnham Montaclair Film Festival (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Bo Burnham]] said his anxieties inspired him to begin working on the screenplay in 2014.]]\nAs a touring comedian, [[Bo Burnham]] suffered from [[panic attack]]s related to his performances since 2013. While his main intention was to write a story about anxiety, he chose the setting of eighth grade because of his perspective that \"anxiety makes me feel like a terrified thirteen-year-old.\"<ref name=\"Schulman\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/07/02/bo-burnhams-age-of-anxiety |title=Bo Burnham's Age of Anxiety |work=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Michael |last=Schulman |date=July 2, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802020738/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/07/02/bo-burnhams-age-of-anxiety |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He also reflected on his notion that eighth grade is a crucial year for forming [[self-awareness]]:<ref name=\"Blickley\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/bo-burnham-eighth-grade_us_5b3bd2a6e4b07b827cbbad82 |title=That Time Bo Burnham Wrote A Sappy Letter To Enya For 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |first=Leigh |last=Blickley |date=July 11, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904011409/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/bo-burnham-eighth-grade_us_5b3bd2a6e4b07b827cbbad82 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I wanted to talk about anxiety and what it feels like to be alive right now, and what it is to be unsure and nervous. That felt more like middle school than high school to me. I think the country and the culture is going through an eighth-grade moment right now.<ref name=\"Ryan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/10/middle-school-movie-eighth-grade-feels-painfully-real/768647002/ |title=Why 'Eighth Grade' is the most painfully real middle-school movie you've ever seen |work=[[USA Today]] |first=Patrick |last=Ryan |date=July 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904090142/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/10/middle-school-movie-eighth-grade-feels-painfully-real/768647002/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nBurnham was also inspired by observing a girl in a mall taking [[selfie]]s while alone; he believed she was concerned about her appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/bo-burnham-made-a-movie-to-work-out-his-anxiety-it-ended-up-explaining-our-instagram-age/2018/07/12/86d40f08-8384-11e8-8553-a3ce89036c78_story.html |title=Bo Burnham made a movie to work out his anxiety. It ended up explaining our Instagram age |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Telford |first=Taylor |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909025014/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/bo-burnham-made-a-movie-to-work-out-his-anxiety-it-ended-up-explaining-our-instagram-age/2018/07/12/86d40f08-8384-11e8-8553-a3ce89036c78_story.html?utm_term=.e704fa8662e5 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Given his career started with producing [[YouTube]] videos, he also wanted to explore the life of a character whose videos have very small audiences.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\"/> Work on the screenplay began in March 2014.<ref name=\"Menta\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/eighth-grade-film-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-interview-1014866 |title=Bo Burnham On 'Eighth Grade' And Why The Internet Makes Him Anxious |work=[[Newsweek]] |last=Menta |first=Anna |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822201217/https://www.newsweek.com/eighth-grade-film-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-interview-1014866 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla was not the sole protagonist in an initial draft of the screenplay, but Burnham decided to focus on her because her voice felt the most true of the characters.<ref name=\"Schulman\"/> He decided his protagonist would be female after watching YouTube, saying, \"the boys talk about ''[[Minecraft]]'' and the girls talk about their souls ... probably half because girls are just actually maturing more quickly and half because culture asks way deeper questions of young women earlier than men\".<ref name=\"Blickley\"/> He also liked the idea of a female protagonist to avoid \"projecting\" his personal memories of eighth grade as a male.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\"/> The film's working title was ''The Coolest Girl in the World''.<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\">{{cite AV media |first=Bo |last=Burnham |date=2018 |title=Eighth Grade audio commentary |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref>\n\nTo write dialogue representing [[Generation Z]], Burnham watched YouTube.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Burnham's personal views on the differences between Generation Z and its predecessors inspired a scene where the character Trevor theorizes access to social media at an early age molded the generation's minds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-700514/ |title=Bo Burnham on 'Eighth Grade,' Anxiety and Why Social Media Is a Curse |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |first=Logan |last=Hill |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052520/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-700514/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla and Mark's relationship is based on Burnham's relationship with his mother.<ref name=\"Rubin\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/features/bo-burnham-interview-eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-1202877506/ |title=Bo Burnham Wishes 'Eighth Grade' Wasn't Rated R |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Rebecca |last=Rubin |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815112353/https://variety.com/2018/film/features/bo-burnham-interview-eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-1202877506/ |archive-date=August 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham viewed a teenager's relationship with his or her parent as a stage where \"You want independence, and you also want affirmation\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/bo-burnham-on-the-incredible-honesty-of-middle-schoolers-online/566579/ |title=In Middle School, 'You're Trying to Build a Parachute as You're Falling' |work=[[The Atlantic]] |first=Julie |last=Beck |date=August 1, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052525/https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/bo-burnham-on-the-incredible-honesty-of-middle-schoolers-online/566579/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Rudin]], [[Eli Bush]] and [[A24 (company)|A24]] would go on to produce the movie with a budget of $2 million.<ref name=\"Sandberg\"/> A24 executive Nicolette Aizenberg remarked ''Eighth Grade'' was \"personal\" to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/03/business/media/a24-studio.html |title=The Little Movie Studio That Could |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Barnes |first=Brooks |date=March 3, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617192730/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/03/business/media/a24-studio.html |archive-date=June 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham spent years seeking financing, confident he was marketable with his success as a comedian.<ref name=\"Nemiroff\">{{cite interview |url=http://collider.com/bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-eighth-grade-interview/#images |title=Bo Burnham & Elsie Fisher on 'Eighth Grade' and Avoiding Teen Tropes |first1=Perri |last1=Nemiroff |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=2018 |website=[[Collider.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823035828/http://collider.com/bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-eighth-grade-interview/#images |archivedate=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"EricJohnson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.recode.net/2018/7/30/17631478/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-social-media-movie-peter-kafka-recode-podcast|title='Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham is happy that a lot of people 'have no idea who I am' |first=Eric |last=Johnson |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |date=July 30, 2018 |work=[[Recode]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731111649/https://www.recode.net/2018/7/30/17631478/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-social-media-movie-peter-kafka-recode-podcast |archive-date=July 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Although he had not directed a feature before, Burnham was adamant to be allowed to direct, and spent eight months before principal photography reading books such as [[Sidney Lumet]]'s ''Making Movies''.<ref name=\"Sandberg\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nFifty teenagers auditioned for the role of Kayla.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Burnham discovered [[Elsie Fisher]] on YouTube and had her audition three times.<ref name=\"FisherBurnham\" /> Fisher, then 13, said she had struggled to find a part realistically depicting a teenager before auditioning for ''Eighth Grade''.<ref name=\"Bahr\"/> Burnham cast Fisher because, \"She was the only one who felt like a shy kid pretending to be confident \u2013 everyone else felt like a confident kid pretending to be shy\".<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Fisher said one reason she was apprehensive at the first audition was that she was a fan of Burnham's comedy. She was drawn to the part because Kayla's speech mannerisms are similar to hers.<ref name=\"Nemiroff\"/> She was graduated eighth grade one week before the production began.<ref name=\"Bitran\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-1202871281/ |title=How Casting a Girl Kept Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' Current |first=Tara |last=Bitran |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014147/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-1202871281/ |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Upon reviewing the screenplay, Fisher's father shouted and swore reading the \"truth or dare\" scene, but made sure his daughter was comfortable with the material.<ref name=\"Bahr\">{{cite news |title=Bo Burnham explores the awkwardness of 'Eighth Grade' |first=Lindsey |last=Bahr |url=https://apnews.com/2171ca14b0bc423fac2b0ee6735ebc42 |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824145442/https://apnews.com/2171ca14b0bc423fac2b0ee6735ebc42 |archivedate=August 24, 2018 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |location=Los Angeles |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBurnham considered [[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]] to have a \"dad vibe\".<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> Daniel Zolghadri was cast as Riley. Because of the \"truth or dare\" scene, many young actors who auditioned played the part as sinister, but Burnham coached Zolghadri to be \"the opposite of creepy\".<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> [[Emily Robinson]] and Imani Lewis were teenagers when cast and both said they found the depiction of anxiety relatable.<ref name=\"Juzwiak\"/> Jake Ryan, who played Gabe, remarked that in the screenplay Gabe \"was supposed to be off-centered\", and not knowing the meaning of this phrase, played himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/scene-stealer-jake-ryan-just-tried-to-be-himself-in-eighth-grade-1203099711/ |title=Scene Stealer Jake Ryan Just Tried to Be Himself in 'Eighth Grade' |first=Susan |last=Young |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |date=January 10, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105200707/https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/scene-stealer-jake-ryan-just-tried-to-be-himself-in-eighth-grade-1203099711/ |archive-date=January 5, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nActual teachers and students at Suffern Middle School in New York were used as [[extra (acting)|extras]], with principal Brian Fox saying five to 10 students were cast.<ref name=\"Goldblatt\"/> During the audition process for the real-life eighth graders, one student claimed having [[eczema]] was her \"special talent\" and another auditioned by \"eating a [[bell pepper]] like an apple.\" Burnham accepted this as a qualification.<ref>{{cite interview |first1=John |last1=Dickerson |first2=Gayle |last2=King |first3=John |last3=Dickerson  |title=Bo Burnham talk about his new acclaimed coming of age film Eighth Grade |date=July 23, 2018 |work=[[CBS This Morning]]  }}</ref> Band teacher Dave Yarrington said Burnham cast him because he \"liked my look\".<ref name=\"Goldblatt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/local/rockland/suffern/2018/07/19/suffern-students-eighth-grade-movie/799603002/ |title=Suffern students talk about appearing in movie 'Eighth Grade' and being in eighth grade |work=[[The Journal News]] |first=Rochel Leah |last=Goldblatt |date=July 19, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910205546/https://www.lohud.com/story/news/local/rockland/suffern/2018/07/19/suffern-students-eighth-grade-movie/799603002/?from=new-cookie |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:9.6.07.PalisadesCenterMall.JPG|thumb|Filming took place at the exterior of the [[Palisades Center]].]]\nThe film was shot in [[Suffern, New York]] in summer 2017, over 27 days,<ref name=\"Blickley\" /><ref name=\"Sandberg\"/> with shooting at Suffern Middle School in July.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/><ref name=\"Goldblatt\"/> For the mall scenes, exterior shots were taken at [[Palisades Center]] in [[West Nyack, New York]], while interior scenes were shot at the nearby [[The Galleria at White Plains]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westchestermagazine.com/Bo-Burnhams-Film-Eighth-Grade-Jacob-Burns/ |title=Spot the Local Scenery in Bo Burnham's Debut Film 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[Westchester Magazine]] |first=Dave |last=Zucker |date=July 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820005949/http://www.westchestermagazine.com/Bo-Burnhams-Film-Eighth-Grade-Jacob-Burns/ |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham chose not to obscure the natural look of Fisher's skin,<ref name=\"Rubin\"/> who wore some make-up but her acne was left visible.<ref name=\"Juzwiak\">{{cite web |url=https://themuse.jezebel.com/what-eighth-grade-means-to-its-teen-stars-1827804845 |title=What Eighth Grade Means to Its Teen Stars |work=[[Jezebel.com]] |last=Juzwiak |first=Rich |date=July 23, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726005811/https://themuse.jezebel.com/what-eighth-grade-means-to-its-teen-stars-1827804845 |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla's use of the phrase \"Gucci!\" to [[Sign-on and sign-off|sign-off]] her video blogs came from Fisher's habit of ending conversations this way, which was also imitated by Burnham and others on set.<ref name=\"FisherBurnham\">{{cite interview |url=https://variety.com/video/eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-sundance-interview/ |title=Gucci! How 'Eighth Grade' Got Their Catch Phrase |first1=Elsie |last1=Fisher |first2=Burnham |last2=Bo |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014247/https://variety.com/video/eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-sundance-interview/ |archivedate=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fisher's other habits of slouching and rubbing her arm were also incorporated into her character.<ref>{{cite AV media |first=Elsie |last=Fisher |date=2018 |title=You're Not Alone: Life in Eighth Grade |work=Eighth Grade |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> The filmmakers adopted Fisher's advice that \"no one uses [[Facebook]] anymore\", and it was substituted in the film with [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-interview-comedy-sundance-london-a8369081.html |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade finally tells the truth about growing up with the internet |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Loughrey |first=Clarisse |date=May 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909025206/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-interview-comedy-sundance-london-a8369081.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Beyond minor changes, [[improvisation]] was rarely employed.<ref name=\"Mulcahey\"/>\n\nTo depict texting, Burnham rejected using [[visual effects]] to show messages as on-screen [[Speech balloon|bubbles]], as in ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''. He opted for a \"practical\" portrayal, filming the phones themselves.<ref name=\"Arkin\"/> Kayla's video blogs were shot with an actual [[MacBook Pro]].<ref name=\"Mulcahey\">{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/105023-zooms-are-totally-underutilized-bo-burnham-on-eighth-grade-at-sxsw-2018/#.W5EtTuhKjIU |title='Zooms are Totally Underutilized': Bo Burnham on Eighth Grade |work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] |last=Mulcahey |first=Matt |date=July 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906195748/https://filmmakermagazine.com/105023-zooms-are-totally-underutilized-bo-burnham-on-eighth-grade-at-sxsw-2018/#.W5EtTuhKjIU |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Because the actual Internet was depicted, production designer Sam Lisenco and [[theatrical property|prop]] designer Erica Severson created many false Instagram and Twitter accounts.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\">{{cite AV media |first=Bo |last=Burnham |date=2018 |title=You're Not Alone: Life in Eighth Grade |work=Eighth Grade |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> The filmmakers primarily used [[Red Digital Cinema]] cameras and wide lenses, with Burnham favoring the use of camera [[Zooming (filmmaking)|zooming]].<ref name=\"Mulcahey\" />\n\nThe \"truth or dare\" scene was shot with only eight crew members along with Fisher and Zolghadri.<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> Fisher had the screenplay on her lap to read when her character was looking down.<ref name=\"FisherCommentary\">{{cite AV media |first=Elsie |last=Fisher |date=2018 |title=Eighth Grade audio commentary |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> She explained, \"We just wanted to take a sensitive approach and just be honest about this, and portray a type of toxic event that can happen.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-film-coming-of-age-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-1201983071/ |title='Eighth Grade': How a Twentysomething Dude Made the Year's Best Film About Female Coming-of-Age |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816110603/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-film-coming-of-age-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-1201983071/ |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Due to Fisher being underage when shooting the banana scene, it was similarly shot with minimal crew present.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-director-star-talk-sexually-suggestive-scenes-casting-real-life-kids-1133659 |title='Eighth Grade' Director, Star Talk 'Sexually Suggestive' Scenes, Casting 'Real-Life Kids' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Geschwind |first=Max |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510014921/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-director-star-talk-sexually-suggestive-scenes-casting-real-life-kids-1133659 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\n[[File:Anna Meredith.jpg|thumb|left|Electronic music composer [[Anna Meredith]] wrote the score.]]\nEditor Jennifer Lilly and Burnham did not complete post-production until three days before the premiere at [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] in January 2018.<ref name=\"Sandberg\" /> Fisher singing in ''[[Masha and the Bear]]'' at age 11 was used in the film.<ref name=\"FisherCommentary\" />{{Unclear inline|reason=Not clear if her character in 'Masha and the Bear' or Fisher herself at age 11 was shown in the film.|date=February 2020}}\n\nBritish [[electronic music|electronic]] composer and solo musician [[Anna Meredith]] wrote and recorded the film's score in her [[London]] studio. Deliberately avoiding a \"cute\" score, Burnham turned to electronic music because \"Kayla\u2019s experience feels so intense to her,\" and chose Meredith since her style was unlike \"a lot of electronic music [\u2026] very cold and masculine.\"<ref name=\"Mulcahey\" /> As her first film score, Meredith described the process as a \"challenge,\" emphasizing that as a composer, \"you don\u2019t just present the music you want. You try to do what the film needs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/08/anna-meredith-is-it-classical-is-it-pop-proms |title=Anna Meredith: 'Is it classical, is it pop? I don't really think about it that way' |first=Fiona |last=Maddocks |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 8, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221227/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/08/anna-meredith-is-it-classical-is-it-pop-proms |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham used \"[[Orinoco Flow]]\" by Irish musician [[Enya]] for a [[Montage (filmmaking)|montage]] scene of Kayla browsing social media. He wanted to use the song to convey that the Internet was \"religious\" and \"spiritual\" for Kayla. Burnham wrote a letter to Enya for her personal permission to use the song, which she granted.<ref name=\"Blickley\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered in competition at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]] on January 19,<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sundance-film-festival-2018-lineup-program-1202625522/ |title=Sundance Film Festival Unveils Full 2018 Features Lineup |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 29, 2017 |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |last=Debruge |first=Peter |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130092712/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/sundance-film-festival-2018-lineup-program-1202625522/ |archive-date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/104473-my-own-feeling-of-unease-in-living-with-and-on-the-internet-director-bo-burnham-eighth-grade/#.W5BK0ehKjIU |title='My Own Feeling of Unease in Living with and on the Internet': Director Bo Burnham, Eighth Grade |work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] |date=January 19, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014144/https://filmmakermagazine.com/104473-my-own-feeling-of-unease-in-living-with-and-on-the-internet-director-bo-burnham-eighth-grade/#.W5BK0ehKjIU |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and was subsequently screened at the [[San Francisco International Film Festival]] in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailycal.org/2018/04/18/2018-san-francisco-international-film-festival/ |title=2018 San Francisco International Film Festival offers profound variety of films |author=Staff |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=April 18, 2018 |work=[[The Daily Californian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221237/http://www.dailycal.org/2018/04/18/2018-san-francisco-international-film-festival/ |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' also screened at the [[Seattle International Film Festival]] at its closing weekend in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/siff-2018-the-best-of-the-fests-final-weekend/ |title=SIFF 2018: The best of the fest's final weekend |first=Hunter |last=Harris |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=June 6, 2018 |work=[[Seattle Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014246/https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/siff-2018-the-best-of-the-fests-final-weekend/ |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[A24 (company)|A24]] gave ''Eighth Grade'' its [[limited release]] on July 13,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/03/eighth-grade-trailer-bo-burnhams-directorial-debut.html |title=Eighth Grade Trailer: Being a Tween Right Now Looks Rough |first=Hunter |last=Harris |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018 |website=[[Vulture.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014116/http://www.vulture.com/2018/03/eighth-grade-trailer-bo-burnhams-directorial-debut.html |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> before moving it to wide release August 3.<ref name=\"Mendelson\"/> The [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave ''Eighth Grade'' an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film rating|R rating]] for profanity and content about fellatio.<ref name=\"Axelrod\"/> Burnham had the option to edit the film to secure a more permissive PG-13 but chose not to do so, commenting, \"It didn't feel like our responsibility to portray a reality that was appropriate for kids, but rather portray the reality that the kids are actually living in\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/07/21/bo-burnham-refused-to-edit-r-rated-eighth-grade-into-pg-13-and-advises-teenagers-to-sneak-in/ |title=Bo Burnham refused to edit R-rated 'Eighth Grade' into PG-13 and advises teenagers to 'sneak in' |first=Alexanda |last=Clinton |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 21, 2018 |website=[[Salon.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823014536/https://www.salon.com/2018/07/21/bo-burnham-refused-to-edit-r-rated-eighth-grade-into-pg-13-and-advises-teenagers-to-sneak-in/ |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Critics decried the MPAA's decision for denying teenage viewers a film with positive messages.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Some critics think the film could have a positive impact on teenagers, allowing them to relate to characters going through a complicated phase in their lives and opening dialogue about sex, bullying and self-image.}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/summer-movies/2018/7/18/17574516/eighth-grade-r-rating-mpaa-teen-movies |title=Eighth Grade's R rating deters actual 8th-graders from seeing it. What a shame |first=Charles |last=Bramesco |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 18, 2018 |website=[[Vox.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014100/https://www.vox.com/summer-movies/2018/7/18/17574516/eighth-grade-r-rating-mpaa-teen-movies |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |title=Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' isn't trying to teach you anything, and that's the beauty of it |first=Taylor |last=Seely |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822111608/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Parents should see this with their kids (and ignore the R rating).}}</ref> MPAA representative Chris Ortman stated A24 never appealed the R rating, though having the right to do so.<ref name=\"Seely\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |title=Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' isn't trying to teach you anything, and that's the beauty of it |first=Taylor |last=Seely |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822111608/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham regretted the rating because it excluded middle school-aged youth.<ref name=\"Rubin\"/> To get around the rating, A24 arranged one free, unrated screening in each U.S. state on August 8.<ref name=\"Axelrod\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham approved of Canada's [[Canadian motion picture rating system|14A rating]]. ''Eighth Grade'' began screening in Canadian cities on August 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timescolonist.com/eighth-grade-director-says-film-s-14a-rating-in-canada-reflects-ideal-audience-1.23380841 |title='Eighth Grade' directorsays film's 14A rating in Canada reflects ideal audience |first=Ryan |last=Porter |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 26, 2018 |work=[[Times Colonist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906124539/https://www.timescolonist.com/eighth-grade-director-says-film-s-14a-rating-in-canada-reflects-ideal-audience-1.23380841 |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, [[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] acquired international distribution rights to the film.<ref name=\"DAlessandro\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-a24-oscars-sony-worldwide-box-office-1202471593/|title='Eighth Grade' Graduates: Sony Pictures WW Takes Foreign As A24 Positions Bo Burnham's Indie Wonder For Awards Season|website=Deadline|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=September 26, 2018|accessdate=September 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926195538/https://deadline.com/2018/09/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-a24-oscars-sony-worldwide-box-office-1202471593/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lionsgate]] prepared the DVD and [[Blu-ray]] release in [[DVD region code#Region 1|Region 1]] with a director's commentary and deleted scenes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-new-video-eighth-grade-20180928-story.html |title=New video: 'Eighth Grade' is a sublime and profound look at the world of a young teen |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Noel |last=Murray |date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004140154/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-new-video-eighth-grade-20180928-story.html |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> for distribution beginning October 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/entertainmentlife/20181004/new-on-dvd-oct-9-have-no-reservations-about-hotel-artemis-on-dvd |title=New on DVD Oct. 9: Have no reservations about 'Hotel Artemis' on DVD |work =[[Providence Journal]] |first=Rick |last=Bentley |date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006003754/http://www.providencejournal.com/entertainmentlife/20181004/new-on-dvd-oct-9-have-no-reservations-about-hotel-artemis-on-dvd |archive-date=October 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released in Belgium and the Netherlands in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lesoir.be/207644/article/2019-02-19/le-charme-de-robert-redford-opere-toujours-nos-critiques-des-sorties-cinema |title=Le charme de Robert Redford op\u00e8re toujours: nos critiques des sorties cin\u00e9ma |last=Staff |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |date=February 19, 2019 |work=[[Le Soir]] |language=French |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190510013553/https://www.lesoir.be/207644/article/2019-02-19/le-charme-de-robert-redford-opere-toujours-nos-critiques-des-sorties-cinema |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/uit/5748771/deze-films-draaien-vanaf-deze-week-in-de-bioscoop-week-8.html |title=Deze films draaien vanaf deze week in de bioscoop (week 8) |last=Staff |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |website=[[Nu.nl]] |language=Dutch |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190510013419/https://www.nu.nl/uit/5748771/deze-films-draaien-vanaf-deze-week-in-de-bioscoop-week-8.html |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> United Kingdom and Irish releases occurred on April 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/uk-trailer-eighth-grade/ |title=UK Trailer For Eighth Grade |first=James |last=White |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |date=January 28, 2018 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208064213/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/uk-trailer-eighth-grade/ |archive-date=February 8, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/bo-burnham-takes-to-red-carpet-for-irish-premiere-of-eighth-grade-1.3804590 |title=Bo Burnham takes to red carpet for Irish premiere of 'Eighth Grade' |first=Tara |last=Brady |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |date=February 25, 2019 |work=[[Irish Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226050704/https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/bo-burnham-takes-to-red-carpet-for-irish-premiere-of-eighth-grade-1.3804590 |archive-date=February 26, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Eighth Grade''{{'}}s opening weekend in four theaters beginning July 13 saw a gross of $252,284, an average of $63,071 per screen.<ref>{{cite news |title='Screenscaper' collapses as 'Hotel' Soars |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 16, 2018 |first=Sonaiya |last=Kelley }}</ref> It surpassed [[Wes Anderson]]'s ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]'' ($60,011) for the best per-screen average of 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-lights-up-indie-box-office-with-top-per-screen-average-of-2018/ |title='Eighth Grade' Lights Up Indie Box Office With Best Per Screen Average of 2018 |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |date=July 15, 2018 |work=[[The Wrap]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815135259/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-lights-up-indie-box-office-with-top-per-screen-average-of-2018/ |archive-date=August 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/dwayne-johnson-skyscraper-ant-man-and-the-wasp-hotel-transylvania-3-weekend-box-office-1202426089/ |title='Skyscraper' Up In Flames With $24M+ As 'Hotel Transylvania 3' Books $42M+ Weekend Voyage |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=July 15, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=July 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715074033/https://deadline.com/2018/07/dwayne-johnson-skyscraper-ant-man-and-the-wasp-hotel-transylvania-3-weekend-box-office-1202426089/ |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and was in-turn surpassed by ''[[Free Solo]]'' ($75,201) at the end of September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/free-solo-top-screen-average-1202962594/ |title='Free Solo' Documentary Climbs Indie Box Office With Best Screen Average of 2018 |last=Rubin |first=Rebecca |date=September 30, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205850/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/free-solo-top-screen-average-1202962594/ |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' expanded to 33 theaters in its second weekend, grossing $794,370,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/mcqueen-blindspotting-box-office-results-eighth-grade-1202431444/ |title='McQueen' Stylish And 'Blindspotting' Solid In Debuts, 'Eighth Grade' Gets High Marks In Week 2 \u2013 Specialty Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 22, 2018 |first=Brian |last=Brooks |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205949/https://deadline.com/2018/07/mcqueen-blindspotting-box-office-results-eighth-grade-1202431444/ |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and then made $1.3 million from 158 theaters in its third weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-fallout-opening-weekend-1202434739/ |title='Mission' Accomplished: 'Fallout' $61M+ Opening Reps Record For Tom Cruise Franchise \u2013 Sunday |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=July 29, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=July 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729085704/https://deadline.com/2018/07/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-fallout-opening-weekend-1202434739/ |archive-date=July 29, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The film began its wide release on August 3 at 1,084 theaters,<ref name=\"Mendelson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/04/friday-box-office-teen-titans-go-drops-66-as-incredibles-2-passes-the-dark-knight/#6049bb1f5c99 |title=Friday Box Office: 'Teen Titans Go' Drops 66% As 'Incredibles 2' Passes 'The Dark Knight' |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 4, 2018 |first=Scott |last=Mendelson |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930210127/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/04/friday-box-office-teen-titans-go-drops-66-as-incredibles-2-passes-the-dark-knight/#6049bb1f5c99 |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and earned $6.6 million by August 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-screenings-not-enforcing-r-rating-1132476 |title='Eighth Grade': Free Screenings Across Country Won't Enforce R-Rating |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 6, 2018 |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820062054/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-screenings-not-enforcing-r-rating-1132476 |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBy August 16 the film earned $10.5 million, the sixth-highest grossing independent domestic film of the summer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/7-highest-grossing-indie-movies-at-the-us-box-office-this-summer-2018-8 |title=The 7 highest-grossing indie movies at the US box office this summer |last=Clark |first=Travis |date=August 16, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820113737/https://www.businessinsider.com/7-highest-grossing-indie-movies-at-the-us-box-office-this-summer-2018-8 |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> By September 26 it had grossed $13.5 million in North America.<ref name=\"DAlessandro\"/> {{asof|2019|6|20|df=US}} it has grossed $14.3 million worldwide.<ref name=\"Numbers\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 99% based on 294 reviews, with an average rating of 8.85/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Eighth Grade'' takes a look at its titular time period that offers a rare and resounding ring of truth while heralding breakthroughs for writer-director Bo Burnham and captivating star Elsie Fisher.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Eighth Grade (2018)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eighth_grade|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=July 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816044516/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eighth_grade/|archive-date=August 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 89 out of 100, based on 49 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Eighth Grade Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/eighth-grade|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=August 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726011326/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/eighth-grade|archive-date=July 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] judged the film \"sweet and intelligent\" and credited Fisher for \"an authentic and utterly natural performance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/eighth-grade-brilliantly-captures-the-agony-and-ecstasy-of-adolescence/ |title='Eighth Grade' brilliantly captures the agony and ecstasy of adolescence |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 18, 2018 |first=Richard |last=Roeper |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102145/https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/eighth-grade-brilliantly-captures-the-agony-and-ecstasy-of-adolescence/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  [[Ty Burr]] also cited Fisher for a performance showing \"supreme awkwardness and not a shred of vanity\" and Josh Hamilton for playing his part with \"an empathetic cringe\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2018/07/18/eighth-grade-middle-school-marvel/6JhM75hqC1PTuYDsjxwSrK/story.html |title='Eighth Grade' is a middle school marvel |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 18, 2018 |first=Ty |last=Burr |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102109/https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2018/07/18/eighth-grade-middle-school-marvel/6JhM75hqC1PTuYDsjxwSrK/story.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} Manohla Dargis cited Josh Hamilton as \"note-perfect\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/11/movies/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham.html |title=Review: All the Feels, Hurts and Laughs of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Manohla |last=Dargis |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816144855/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/11/movies/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham.html |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Ann Hornaday of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' highlighted Fisher for \"a raw, radiantly generous performance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/eighth-grade-has-given-us-a-new-iconic-teenage-heroine-for-the-ages/2018/07/18/6ea2a590-860c-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on |title='Eighth Grade' has given us a new iconic teenage heroine for the ages |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 19, 2018 |first=Ann |last=Hornaday |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905042938/https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/eighth-grade-has-given-us-a-new-iconic-teenage-heroine-for-the-ages/2018/07/18/6ea2a590-860c-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on&utm_term=.1082c3d23287 |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Peter Debruge judged the film \"achingly honest\" but clich\u00e9d in having Kayla infatuated with one boy (played by Luke Prael) and ignoring a better love interest (played by Jake Ryan) until the later acts.<ref name=\"Debruge\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/eighth-grade-review-1202670924/ |title=Film Review: 'Eighth Grade' |first=Peter |last=Debruge |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=January 20, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615111236/https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/eighth-grade-review-1202670924/ |archive-date=June 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] hailed ''Eighth Grade'' as \"special and unique\" for its \"empathy\", writing it is neutral on the Internet's effects on society but Kayla is addicted to electronics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/eighth-grade-review-tender-take-on-teen-angst-is-flat-out-triumph-696153/ |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Tender Take on Teen Angst Is Flat-Out Triumph |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Peter |last=Travers |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102133/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/eighth-grade-review-tender-take-on-teen-angst-is-flat-out-triumph-696153/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> For ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Naomi Fry credited ''Eighth Grade'' with \"queasy verisimilitude\" and exploring the impact of [[social media]] on the lives of teenagers.<ref name=\"Fry\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |title=The Cringey Teen Spirit of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 1, 2018 |first=Naomi |last=Fry |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919084831/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' contributor Dani Di Placido wrote the depiction of electronics was better than in most films, showing they were \"powerful communicative tools that can isolate us, or bring us together, depending on how we choose to use them\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/05/eighth-grade-review-coming-of-age-in-the-modern-world/#2d0be9c93974 |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Coming-Of-Age In The Modern World |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 5, 2018 |first=Dani |last=Di Placido |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907183920/https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/05/eighth-grade-review-coming-of-age-in-the-modern-world/#2d0be9c93974 |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Considering how Burnham first achieved notoriety on the Internet, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' critic Michael Phillips wrote Burnham was familiar with \"the agitating seductions of our online lives\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-eighth-grade-rev-0716-story.html |title='Eighth Grade' review: Hello 12, hello 13, hello 'likes' in the age of techno-anxiety |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 16, 2018 |first=Michael |last=Phillips |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907053444/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-eighth-grade-rev-0716-story.html |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:MollyRingwaldApr2013.jpg|thumb|Media outlets quoted actress [[Molly Ringwald]]'s [[Twitter|tweet]] praising ''Eighth Grade'' as a film about adolescence.]] \nIn ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', Justin Chang evaluated ''Eighth Grade'' as \"sharp, sensitive and enormously affecting\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-eighth-grade-review-20180711-story.html |title=Review: Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' is a beautifully honest portrait of adolescent girlhood |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Justin |last=Chang |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822160806/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-eighth-grade-review-20180711-story.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it an A, with Chris Nashawaty praising Burnham for capturing Kayla's anxiety and hopes, depicted \"in all of their miraculous, cringeworthy, universal beauty\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/10/eighth-grade-review/ |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade is heartbreaking, heartwarming, and a total charmer: EW review |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 10, 2018 |first=Chris |last=Nashawaty |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102118/https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/10/eighth-grade-review/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' named the scenes between Fisher and Hamilton to be among the \"funniest, most poignant\" scenes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/eighth-grade-sucks-eighth-grade-doesn-t-1827547509 |title=Eighth grade sucks. Eighth Grade doesn't |first=A.A. |last=Dowd |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221327/https://film.avclub.com/eighth-grade-sucks-eighth-grade-doesn-t-1827547509 |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[SF Gate]]'' critic Peter Hartlaub wrote the comedy is combined with \"pure social and sexual horror\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Eighth-Grade-is-an-authentic-compassionate-13086976.php |title='Eighth Grade' is an authentic, compassionate debut film from Bo Burnham |first=Peter |last=Hartlaub |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 19, 2018 |work=[[SF Gate]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822023326/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Eighth-Grade-is-an-authentic-compassionate-13086976.php |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Benjamin Lee commented on the score in ''[[The Guardian]]'', writing the use of [[electronic music]] was unexpected but \"effective\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/11/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher |title=Eighth Grade review \u2013 adolescence is excruciating in finely observed gem |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Benjamin |last=Lee |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822121836/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/11/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nMedia outlets also referenced actress [[Molly Ringwald]]'s approval.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |quote=One such fan is Molly Ringwald, cinema's queen of the coming-of-age flick. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |title=The Cringey Teen Spirit of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 1, 2018 |first=Naomi |last=Fry |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |quote=Ringwald tweeted that ''Eighth Grade'' is 'the best movie about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever'\u2014words that carry some weight, coming from a performer who made her name in John Hughes's iconic teen dramedies of the nineteen-eighties. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919084831/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/molly_ringwald_calls_eight_grade_the_best_teen_film_maybe_ever |title=Molly Ringwald Calls 'Eighth Grade' the Best Teen Film 'Maybe Ever' |first=Alex |last=Hudson |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 26, 2018 |work=[[Exclaim!]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014703/http://exclaim.ca/film/article/molly_ringwald_calls_eight_grade_the_best_teen_film_maybe_ever |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Ringwald tweeted \"I just saw [''Eighth Grade''] and thought it was the best film about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MollyRingwald |number=1022250943298121728 |date=July 25, 2018 |title=I just saw @eighthgrademov and thought it was the best film about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever.}}</ref> Ringwald contrasted the depiction of consent in ''Eighth Grade'' to that in [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]]' ''[[The Breakfast Club]]'' (1985), which she starred in, concluding Burnham's film was more updated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/stevens/ct-life-stevens-thursday-eighth-grade-movie-0726-story.html |title='Eighth Grade' is the anti-'Breakfast Club,' and I'm here for it |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 26, 2018 |first=Heidi |last=Stevens |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014528/http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/stevens/ct-life-stevens-thursday-eighth-grade-movie-0726-story.html |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' has been favorably compared with Hughes' filmography generally.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/eighth-grade-is-instant-classic-by-youtube-star-bo-burnham-2018-7 |title='Eighth Grade' is an instant classic written and directed by a 27-year-old \u2014 and it's our indie movie pick for this weekend |first=Jason |last=Guerrasio |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 27, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |quote=The high school genre has its fair share of classics ... anything by John Hughes. But those all feel like they were made by a bunch of adults far removed from adolescence. And that's why ''Eighth Grade'' will go down as a special movie. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910061000/https://www.businessinsider.com/eighth-grade-is-instant-classic-by-youtube-star-bo-burnham-2018-7 |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/07/eighth-grade-is-a-mesmerizing-heartfelt-portrait-of-teenhood/565013/ |title=Eighth Grade Is a Mesmerizing, Heartfelt Portrait of Teenhood |first=David |last=Sims |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |quote=The film never seemed to lean into the operatic awkwardness of a [[Todd Solondz]] movie, or the verbose emotionality of a John Hughes work. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014750/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/07/eighth-grade-is-a-mesmerizing-heartfelt-portrait-of-teenhood/565013/ |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-film-review-bo-burnham-memorably-illuminates-the-psyche-of-a-fraught-middle-schooler/ |title='Eighth Grade' Film Review: Bo Burnham Captures Middle School Angst |first=Robert |last=Abele |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[TheWrap]] |quote=Unlike the put-upon adolescents of John Hughes' oeuvre ... [Kayla] isn't armed with barbed one-liners and Hollywoodized nerd-cutes. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014734/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-film-review-bo-burnham-memorably-illuminates-the-psyche-of-a-fraught-middle-schooler/ |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAdam Chitwood wrote a mixed review on [[Collider.com]], calling it \"a rough draft\" that needed editing to convey its points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham/#sundance |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Bo Burnham's Directorial Debut Is Awkward AF |website=[[Collider.com]] |date=July 13, 2018 |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507183204/http://collider.com/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham/#sundance |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Richard Brody]] in ''The New Yorker'' wrote the film was let down by \"sentiment, stereotypes, and good intentions\", and despite Fisher's performance, \"Kayla remains merely a collection of traits\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/eighth-grade |title=Eighth Grade |work=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Richard |last=Brody |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802020735/https://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/eighth-grade |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The ''[[Missoula Independent]]''{{'}}s Molly Laich compared the realism to being \"drilled at the dentist\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://missoulanews.com/entertainment/the-unbearable-heaviness-of-bo-burnham-s-eighth-grade/article_937363c0-95cd-11e8-87bd-37fd16e07643.html |title=The unbearable heaviness of Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[Missoula Independent]] |date=August 2, 2018 |first=Molly |last=Laich |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905141108/https://missoulanews.com/entertainment/the-unbearable-heaviness-of-bo-burnham-s-eighth-grade/article_937363c0-95cd-11e8-87bd-37fd16e07643.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Eighth Grade}}\nThe film was entered into competition for the Grand Jury Prize at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Debruge\"/> It had four nominations at the [[Independent Spirit Awards]], including [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Film|Best Film]],<ref name=\"Indie Noms\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/2019-independent-spirit-awards-nominations-1202021241/|title=2019 Independent Spirit Awards Nominees, 'Eighth Grade' & 'We the Animals' Lead |first=Kate |last=Erbland |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |date=November 16, 2018 |website=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117011630/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/2019-independent-spirit-awards-nominations-1202021241/ |archive-date=November 17, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> winning [[Independent Spirit Award for Best First Screenplay|Best First Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2019-spirit-awards-winners-complete-list-1203147196/ |title=2019 Indie Spirit Awards Winners: Complete List (Updating Live) |author=Staff |accessdate=February 23, 2019 |date=February 23, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190224004705/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2019-spirit-awards-winners-complete-list-1203147196/ |archive-date=February 24, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fisher received her first [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination for the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-mn-golden-globes-elsie-fisher-20181206-story.html |title=Elsie Fisher of 'Eighth Grade' on scoring her first Golden Globe nomination and her social media reaction |last=Kaufman |first=Amy |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207224638/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-mn-golden-globes-elsie-fisher-20181206-story.html |archivedate=December 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> but the film was not nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] despite reporter Kyle Buchanan considering it to be A24's best candidate for the category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/06/movies/golden-globes-movies.html |title=Golden Globes' Biggest Snubs: 'Widows' and 'First Man' Take Hits |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207121547/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/06/movies/golden-globes-movies.html |archivedate=December 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBurnham and Fisher each won Breakthrough awards at the [[Gotham Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/gotham-awards-winners-list-2018-new-york-1203037073/ |title='The Rider' Wins Best Feature at Gotham Awards (Complete Winners List) |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=November 26, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127031716/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/gotham-awards-winners-list-2018-new-york-1203037073/ |archive-date=November 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' additionally won two [[National Board of Review|National Board of Review Awards]], including being named in the [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films of 2018]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/national-board-of-review-2018-winners-1202023489/ |title=National Board of Review 2018 Winners: 'Green Book' Named Best Film, Lady Gaga Best Actress |first=Zack |last=Sharf |accessdate=November 27, 2018 |date=November 27, 2018 |website=[[Indiewire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127230303/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/national-board-of-review-2018-winners-1202023489/ |archive-date=November 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> the [[American Film Institute]] also included it in its annual top 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/afi-top-10-movies-of-2018-list |title=AFI Reveals Its Top 10 Films of 2018, Including 'Black Panther' and 'Eighth Grade' |website=[[Collider.com]] |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=December 4, 2018 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205041752/http://collider.com/afi-top-10-movies-of-2018-list |archivedate=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film was nominated for three [[Satellite Awards]], including Best Independent Film,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/2018_Press_Academy_NOMINATIONS.pdf |title=2018 Nominations Ballot |accessdate=December 2, 2018 |date=November 28, 2018 |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130052029/http://www.pressacademy.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/2018_Press_Academy_NOMINATIONS.pdf |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and three [[Critics' Choice Awards]], winning [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer|Best Young Performer]] for Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/2019-critics-choice-awards-winners-nominees-full-list-1203106702/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards: Winners and Nominees |first=Kristopher |last=Tapley |accessdate=January 13, 2019 |date=January 13, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114010818/https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/2019-critics-choice-awards-winners-nominees-full-list-1203106702/ |archive-date=January 14, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Additionally, Burnham won the [[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 First-Time Feature Film|Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding First-Time Feature]] and the [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Original Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dga-awards-2019-winners-list-1203127035/ |title=DGA Awards: The Complete Winners List (Updating Live) |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Staff |date=February 2, 2019 |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203063226/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dga-awards-2019-winners-list-1203127035/ |archivedate=February 3, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/writers-guild-awards-2019-winners-list-1202044753/ |title=Writers Guild Awards 2019: Full Winners List (Updating Live) |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=February 17, 2019 |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218023224/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/writers-guild-awards-2019-winners-list-1202044753/ |archivedate=February 18, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|7014006|Eighth Grade}}\n\n{{Bo Burnham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eighth Grade}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about children]]\n[[Category:Films about social media]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bo Burnham]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2017]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bo Burnham]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|2018 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Eighth Grade\n| image          = Eighth Grade.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Bo Burnham]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Scott Rudin]]|[[Eli Bush]]|Lila Yacoub|Christopher Storer}}\n| writer         = Bo Burnham\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Elsie Fisher]]|[[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]]|[[Emily Robinson]]|Jake Ryan|Fred Hechinger}}\n| music          = [[Anna Meredith]]\n| cinematography = Andrew Wehde\n| editing        = Jennifer Lilly\n| production companies = {{ubl|[[A24 (company)|A24]]|IAC Films|Scott Rudin Productions}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(United States)}}\n* [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] {{small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|1|19|[[2018 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2018|7|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/review/2018/07/19/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-is-exquisitely-awkward.html |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade is exquisitely awkward |first=Peter |last=Howell |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |date=October 11, 2018 |work=[[The Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727081103/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/review/2018/07/19/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-is-exquisitely-awkward.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million<ref name=\"Sandberg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-eighth-grade-how-bo-burnham-brought-his-anxiety-screen-1162239 |title=Making of 'Eighth Grade': How Bo Burnham Brought His Anxiety to Screen in the Form of a 13-Year-Old Girl |first=Bryn Elise |last=Sandberg |accessdate=November 23, 2018 |date=November 20, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120205033/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/making-eighth-grade-how-bo-burnham-brought-his-anxiety-screen-1162239 |archive-date=November 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> \n| gross          = $14.3 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Eighth-Grade-(2018)#tab=summary|title=''Eighth Grade'' (2018)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Eighth Grade''''' is a 2018 American [[coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Bo Burnham]]. It stars [[Elsie Fisher]] as Kayla, a [[middle school]] teenager who struggles with [[anxiety]] but strives to gain social acceptance from her peers on their final week of [[eighth grade]]. To cope, she publishes [[Vlog|video blogs]] as a self-styled motivational advice-giver, though spends much of her time obsessing over [[social media]]. This frustrates Kayla's otherwise supportive father ([[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]]), whom she alienates despite his wish to be present in her life as her sole parent.\n\nThe film is Burnham's feature-length debut as a writer and director. He began the screenplay in 2014 to reflect on his own anxiety and [[panic attack]]s stemming from his career as a [[comedian]]. Deciding to convey his experience through Kayla, he also wanted to explore how [[Generation Z|her generation]] cope with mental illness, grow with the presence of social media, navigate [[sexuality]] and [[Sexual consent|consent]], relate to their parents and develop their [[Self-awareness|sense of self]]. Burnham aimed for realism, casting actual eighth graders \u2014 including lead actress Fisher \u2014 who informed his script and directing. For research, he watched vlogs from teenagers on [[YouTube]], where he also discovered Fisher. [[Independent film|Independently financed]] with a small $2 million budget, production took place in 2017, in the suburban town of [[Suffern, New York]].\n\n''Eighth Grade'' premiered on January 19, 2018 at [[Sundance Film Festival]]. It was later given wide theatrical release in the United States on July 13, 2018 by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. Instead of appealing the Motion Picture Association of America's [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film rating|R (Restricted)]] rating of the film, A24 and Burnham arranged free all-ages theatrical screenings in every state to let their young intended audience to more easily see it.\n\nUpon release, the film was a critical and commercial success. Burnham's writing, direction and Fisher's performance drew the most praise from critics, while domestic box office sales topped $13.5 million. The filmmakers won [[List of accolades received by Eighth Grade|many awards and nominations]], with Burnham winning both [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2018|Writers Guild]] and [[71st Directors Guild of America Awards|Directors Guild of America]] Awards, and Fisher nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe]] for Best Actress and winning the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Gotham Award for Breakthrough Actor]]. At years' end, the [[National Board of Review Awards 2018|National Board of Review]] and the [[American Film Institute Awards 2018#Top 10 Films|American Film Institute]] each chose ''Eighth Grade''  as one of the top-ten films of 2018, with the former naming Burnham's film as the year's Best Directorial Debut.\n\n==Plot==\nKayla Day is an [[eighth grade]] student finishing her final week at Miles Grove Middle School, a public school in the state of New York. She posts motivational videos on [[YouTube]] about confidence and self-image that get little to no views. Shy and struggling to make friends at school, she is voted \"Most Quiet\" by her classmates. Meanwhile, Mark, her single father, struggles to connect with her and break her reliance on social media.\n\nShe is invited to a pool party hosted by her classmate, Kennedy, who has done so only after being forced by her mother. At the party, Kayla has an [[panic attack]] in the bathroom but eventually goes outside to swim, where she meets Gabe, Kennedy's eccentric cousin. After trying to leave the party, Kayla has an awkward encounter with her crush, Aiden, who suggests that she rejoin the group. She overcomes her fear and volunteers to sing karaoke.\n\nHearing that Aiden broke up with his last girlfriend because she refused to send him nude photos, Kayla mentions to him in passing that she has a dirty photos folder on her phone, a fabricated story that piques his interest. He asks if she gives [[Fellatio|blowjobs]], and she says yes, unsure of what to say. She later looks up oral-sex instructions online and is disgusted.\n\nKayla attends a [[high school]] shadow program, where she meets Olivia, a friendly twelfth grader who shows her around the high school. Olivia gives Kayla her number, and she later invites Kayla to visit the [[Palisades Center|mall]] with some of her friends. They have a good time, though Kayla spots her father spying from afar and, embarrassed, tells him to leave. Olivia's friend Riley gives Kayla a ride home late at night. He initiates an awkward game of [[truth or dare]] where he asks about her sexual experience, takes off his shirt, and asks her to remove hers. She refuses, and he backs off, angrily claiming he was just trying to help her gain some experience. Kayla breaks down at home and is comforted by her father. She makes a video announcing that she intends to stop making videos, as she is not the person she pretends to be and feels unfit to give advice.\n\nKayla then opens a time capsule she created for herself in [[sixth grade]]. She watches a video she made where her past self asks questions about her current friends and love life. She asks her dad to help her burn the time capsule and asks if she makes him sad. He says that she fills him with pride and he could never be sad about her, and she hugs him tightly.\n\nAt graduation, Kayla rebukes Kennedy for ignoring her thank-you letter and acting indifferent towards her despite Kayla's attempts to be nice. She later has dinner at Gabe's house and they enjoy their time together. Kayla makes a new time capsule which she and her father bury in the backyard; she leaves a video message for her high school self encouraging her to persevere through tough times.\n\n==Cast==\nThe cast includes:<ref name=\"Debruge\"/>\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Elsie Fisher]] as Kayla Day\n* [[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]] as Mark Day\n* [[Emily Robinson]] as Olivia\n* Catherine Oliviere as Kennedy Graves\n* Jake Ryan as Gabe\n* Luke Prael as Aiden Wilson\n* Daniel Zolghadri as Riley\n* Fred Hechinger as Trevor\n* Imani Lewis as Aniyah\n}}\n\n==Themes==\nThe film explores anxiety.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/07/how-kanye-helped-bo-burnham-go-from-stand-up-to-eighth-grade.html |title=How Kanye Helped Bo Burnham Go From Having Panic Attacks Onstage to a Creative Breakthrough to Making Eighth Grade |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Fox |first=Jesse David |date=July 2, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204150036/https://www.vulture.com/2018/07/how-kanye-helped-bo-burnham-go-from-stand-up-to-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=December 4, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Burham: 'I wanted to make a movie about someone that\u2019s living with the internet as a texture, someone that\u2019s living with their anxiety untethered'. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/18/630069876/director-bo-burnham-on-growing-up-with-anxiety-and-an-audience |title=Director Bo Burnham On Growing Up With Anxiety \u2014 And An Audience |publisher=[[NPR]] |last=Gross |first=Terry |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219090848/https://www.npr.org/2018/07/18/630069876/director-bo-burnham-on-growing-up-with-anxiety-and-an-audience |archive-date=December 19, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Burnham says the character was inspired by a period in his early 20s when he was dealing with panic attacks onstage. }}</ref> Professor Julianna W. Miner, writing in 2018 about ''Eighth Grade'', reflects that 22% of teenagers were struggling with depression and anxiety, and teenage girls were committing suicide at higher rates in 2015 than they were in the previous 40 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/parenting/wp/2018/09/06/how-to-use-eighth-grade-to-jump-start-some-important-conversations-with-your-teen/?noredirect=on |title=How to use 'Eighth Grade' to jump-start some important conversations with your teen |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Miner |first=Julianna W. |date=September 6, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909024530/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/parenting/wp/2018/09/06/how-to-use-eighth-grade-to-jump-start-some-important-conversations-with-your-teen/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.c772696929b5 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The anxiety depicted is typical in middle school, but according to reporter Valerie Strauss, also reflects life in 2018 where people of all ages see a \"cacophony of indifference and downright meanness\".<ref name=\"Strauss\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2018/08/16/bo-burnhams-dead-on-film-eighth-grade-is-about-more-than-the-angst-of-eighth-grade/ |title=Bo Burnham's dead-on film 'Eighth Grade' is about more than the angst of eighth grade |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |date=August 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909024638/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2018/08/16/bo-burnhams-dead-on-film-eighth-grade-is-about-more-than-the-angst-of-eighth-grade/?utm_term=.4b28eb7261b1 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The words \"um\" and \"like\" in the screenplay also reflect \"the process of struggling\", rather than the characters' lack of intelligence.<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/how-bo-burnham-uses-like-language-to-um-capture-an-age-of-like-anxiety-in-eighth-grade |title=How Bo Burnham uses, like, language to, um, capture an age of, like, anxiety in Eighth Grade |work=[[National Post]] |last=Knight |first=Chris |date=July 19, 2018  |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20180909024145/https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/how-bo-burnham-uses-like-language-to-um-capture-an-age-of-like-anxiety-in-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[file:textinginclass.jpg|thumb|Texting and social media are featured prominently in the film.]]\nCritic [[Owen Gleiberman]] wrote that ''Eighth Grade'' was a trailblazer in examining youth who never knew a world without the [[Internet]], touching on [[sexting]] as well.<ref name=\"Gleiberman\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/eighth-grade-nails-youth-culture-in-the-digital-age-elsie-fisher-bo-burnham-1202895674/ |title='Eighth Grade' Is the First Movie to Nail Youth Culture in the Digital Age |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |date=August 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908210817/https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/eighth-grade-nails-youth-culture-in-the-digital-age-elsie-fisher-bo-burnham-1202895674/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[CBS News]] also commented that besides \"the usual teen angst and acne\", ''Eighth Grade'' depicts how Kayla spends a great deal of time on the Internet and engaging in [[text messaging]]. This reflects general trends in \"[[Generation Z|iGen]]\" (post-[[millennials]]), where 94% of youth have used [[smartphones]] by age 14.<ref name=\"DAmelio\"/> A 2018 U.S. poll found 45% of teenagers reported \"almost constantly\" using the Internet. 24% called its effects \"mostly negative\", while 45% characterized it as \"neither negative nor positive\".<ref name=\"Arkin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/movies/eighth-grade-goes-inside-mind-iphone-addled-teen-girl-n890606 |title='Eighth Grade' goes inside the mind of an iPhone-addled teen girl |publisher=[[NBC News]] |last=Arkin |first=Daniel |date=July 14, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817232206/https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/movies/eighth-grade-goes-inside-mind-iphone-addled-teen-girl-n890606 |archive-date=August 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Elsie Fisher, \"for Kayla, social media is almost religious\".<ref name=\"Arkin\"/> Burnham explained, \"social media has made me think differently as a person. It's made me more anxious, I think\". Professor [[Jean Twenge]] also connected an increase in Internet usage to a decline in juvenile [[mental health]].<ref name=\"DAmelio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/social-media-and-adolescence-eighth-grade-bo-burnham/ |title=Social media, the scourge of adolescence |publisher=[[CBS News]] |last=D'Amelio |first=John |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035444/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/social-media-and-adolescence-eighth-grade-bo-burnham/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Gleiberman called the depiction an examination of \"overwhelming \u2014 and, I would argue, unprecedented \u2014 woe that teenagers today can feel\".<ref name=\"Gleiberman\"/> Author Robert Barker contrasted ''Eighth Grade'' to earlier coming-of-age films such as ''[[Fast Times at Ridgemont High]]'' (1982) and ''[[Mean Girls]]'' (2004). Rather than work through cliques, Barker wrote Kayla and others are on \"a digital war of all against all, preening, pretending, and pontificating as much to themselves as to an anonymous audience\". Barker also saw the sexting between characters as representing their obliviousness to lost innocence.<ref name=\"Barker\">{{cite web |url=https://brightlightsfilm.com/wp-content/cache/all/coming-of-digital-age-on-bo-burnhams-eighth-grade/#.W5NSbuhKjIV |title=Coming of Digital Age: On Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade |work=[[Bright Lights Film Journal]] |last=Barker |first=Robert |date=August 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180908210817/https://brightlightsfilm.com/wp-content/cache/all/coming-of-digital-age-on-bo-burnhams-eighth-grade/%23.W5Q6MdLLfK6#.W5NSbuhKjIV |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[NPR]] interpreted the impact of the Internet during maturation as \"one of the key subjects of ''Eighth Grade''\", commenting on how many people may not remember the age fondly, but social media has added complications. Even so, NPR stated Kayla is still able to grow despite great challenges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/07/13/628385837/eighth-grade-captures-awkwardness-and-impermanence-of-american-adolescence |title='Eighth Grade' Captures Awkwardness And Impermanence Of American Adolescence |publisher=[[NPR]] |last=Chang |first=Justin |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822022306/https://www.npr.org/2018/07/13/628385837/eighth-grade-captures-awkwardness-and-impermanence-of-american-adolescence |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to critic Kyle Buchanan, \"The biggest mystery to ... [Kayla] is the opposite sex\", considering her interest in Aiden and taking online lessons about fellatio.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |title=How Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade Reflects Our #MeToo Moment |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |date=January 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819174125/http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, journalist Chris O'Falt suggested Kayla is not truly ready for sex, but simply is \"pressured to barter [her] sexuality for social acceptance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-rated-r-mpaa-teenagers-problem-1201983811/ |title='Eighth Grade': Why 13-Year-Olds Aren\u2019t Allowed to See a Movie About Themselves |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=O'Falt |first=Chris |date=July 14, 2018 |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510020119/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-rated-r-mpaa-teenagers-problem-1201983811/ |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' mentioned Kayla's claim to Aiden that she has nude selfies as being among the \"classic middle-school indignities\" depicted in ''Eighth Grade''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/5336639/bo-burnham-eighth-grade/ |title=How Bo Burnham Turns Anxiety Into a Work of Art |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |last=Luscombe |first=Belinda |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717204221/http://time.com/5336639/bo-burnham-eighth-grade/ |archive-date=July 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham also criticized American [[sex education]] for not exploring [[sexual consent]], as reflected in the \"truth or dare\" scene.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |title=Q&A: 'Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham says sex ed needs to be better |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Chval |first=Lauren |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035622/http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Although Kayla is shown to be in a sex education class earlier in the film, she does not know how to react when Riley sexually coerces her, and apologizes to him for rejecting his advances.<ref name=\"Buchanan\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-director-bo-burnham-uncomfortable-car-scene/ |title='Eighth Grade' Director on Why 'Uncomfortable' Car Scene Reflects 'Culture's Failure of These Kids' |work=[[The Wrap]] |last1=Williams |first1=Trey |last2=Verhoeven |first2=Beatrice |date=July 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035657/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-director-bo-burnham-uncomfortable-car-scene/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Film critics connected the scene with the [[Me Too movement]],<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |title=Q&A: 'Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham says sex ed needs to be better |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Chval |first=Lauren |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=The scene between Kayla and Riley really struck a chord with me and felt somewhat parallel to the #MeToo movement. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035622/http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-20180718-story.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/07/eighths-grades-me-too-scene-bo-burnham-movie-review.html |title=Eighth Grade's #MeToo Scene Will Shake You to Your Core |website=[[Thecut.com]] |last=Silman |first=Anna |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=One of the most powerful #MeToo moments on-screen this year features not an actual sexual assault but the implied threat of one. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035816/https://www.thecut.com/2018/07/eighths-grades-me-too-scene-bo-burnham-movie-review.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |title=How Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade Reflects Our #MeToo Moment |website=[[Vulture.com]] |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |date=January 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=After months of sexual-misconduct claims in Hollywood and an ensuing wave of change and debate that has happened all over the world, it was hard not to think of those real-life events while watching ''Eighth Grade''. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819174125/http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/how-bo-burnham-tackles-sexuality-in-his-film-eighth-grade.html |archive-date=August 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> though it written before the movement began. At festival screenings, moviegoers were visibly uncomfortable and yelled during the scene.<ref name=\"RyanMeToo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/12/eighth-grade-me-too-moment-plays-like-horror-movie/775581002/ |title=Why that disturbing #MeToo moment in 'Eighth Grade' has everyone talking |work=[[USA Today]] |last=Ryan |first=Patrick |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035641/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/12/eighth-grade-me-too-moment-plays-like-horror-movie/775581002/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe story also explores Kayla's relationship with her father Mark, a member of [[Generation X]],<ref name=\"Knight\"/> whom she is breaking away from, exhibiting typical behavior for her age.<ref name=\"Strauss\"/> His attempts to communicate with her are frustrated by her fixation with her smartphone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/20/eighth-grade-dad-13-year-old-relatable-scene/ |title=Eighth Grade: Dad trying to relate to his 13-year-old is most relatable scene of the year |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |last=Schwartz |first=Dana |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909073614/https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/20/eighth-grade-dad-13-year-old-relatable-scene/ |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, journalist Sonia Rao judged Mark to be \"the only constant presence in her life\";<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20180916/sensitive-single-dads-raising-daughters-have-taken-over-our-movie-screens |title=Sensitive single dads raising daughters have taken over our movie screens |work=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]] |last=Rao |first=Sonia |date=September 16, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917125829/https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20180916/sensitive-single-dads-raising-daughters-have-taken-over-our-movie-screens |archive-date=September 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Mark is devoted to Kayla and later tells her he is proud of her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/07/eight-grade-is-a-great-movie-about-josh-hamiltons-hot-dad.html |title=Eighth Grade Is a Great Movie About a Dad Who Is Hot |website=[[Slate.com]] |last=Kang |first=Inkoo |date=July 23, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823031245/https://slate.com/culture/2018/07/eight-grade-is-a-great-movie-about-josh-hamiltons-hot-dad.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Bo Burnham Montaclair Film Festival (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Bo Burnham]] said his anxieties inspired him to begin working on the screenplay in 2014.]]\nAs a touring comedian, [[Bo Burnham]] suffered from [[panic attack]]s related to his performances since 2013. While his main intention was to write a story about anxiety, he chose the setting of eighth grade because of his perspective that \"anxiety makes me feel like a terrified thirteen-year-old.\"<ref name=\"Schulman\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/07/02/bo-burnhams-age-of-anxiety |title=Bo Burnham's Age of Anxiety |work=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Michael |last=Schulman |date=July 2, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802020738/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/07/02/bo-burnhams-age-of-anxiety |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He also reflected on his notion that eighth grade is a crucial year for forming [[self-awareness]]:<ref name=\"Blickley\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/bo-burnham-eighth-grade_us_5b3bd2a6e4b07b827cbbad82 |title=That Time Bo Burnham Wrote A Sappy Letter To Enya For 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |first=Leigh |last=Blickley |date=July 11, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904011409/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/bo-burnham-eighth-grade_us_5b3bd2a6e4b07b827cbbad82 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I wanted to talk about anxiety and what it feels like to be alive right now, and what it is to be unsure and nervous. That felt more like middle school than high school to me. I think the country and the culture is going through an eighth-grade moment right now.<ref name=\"Ryan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/10/middle-school-movie-eighth-grade-feels-painfully-real/768647002/ |title=Why 'Eighth Grade' is the most painfully real middle-school movie you've ever seen |work=[[USA Today]] |first=Patrick |last=Ryan |date=July 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904090142/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/07/10/middle-school-movie-eighth-grade-feels-painfully-real/768647002/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nBurnham was also inspired by observing a girl in a mall taking [[selfie]]s while alone; he believed she was concerned about her appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/bo-burnham-made-a-movie-to-work-out-his-anxiety-it-ended-up-explaining-our-instagram-age/2018/07/12/86d40f08-8384-11e8-8553-a3ce89036c78_story.html |title=Bo Burnham made a movie to work out his anxiety. It ended up explaining our Instagram age |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Telford |first=Taylor |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909025014/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/bo-burnham-made-a-movie-to-work-out-his-anxiety-it-ended-up-explaining-our-instagram-age/2018/07/12/86d40f08-8384-11e8-8553-a3ce89036c78_story.html?utm_term=.e704fa8662e5 |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Given his career started with producing [[YouTube]] videos, he also wanted to explore the life of a character whose videos have very small audiences.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\"/> Work on the screenplay began in March 2014.<ref name=\"Menta\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/eighth-grade-film-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-interview-1014866 |title=Bo Burnham On 'Eighth Grade' And Why The Internet Makes Him Anxious |work=[[Newsweek]] |last=Menta |first=Anna |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822201217/https://www.newsweek.com/eighth-grade-film-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-interview-1014866 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla was not the sole protagonist in an initial draft of the screenplay, but Burnham decided to focus on her because her voice felt the most true of the characters.<ref name=\"Schulman\"/> He decided his protagonist would be female after watching YouTube, saying, \"the boys talk about ''[[Minecraft]]'' and the girls talk about their souls ... probably half because girls are just actually maturing more quickly and half because culture asks way deeper questions of young women earlier than men\".<ref name=\"Blickley\"/> He also liked the idea of a female protagonist to avoid \"projecting\" his personal memories of eighth grade as a male.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\"/> The film's working title was ''The Coolest Girl in the World''.<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\">{{cite AV media |first=Bo |last=Burnham |date=2018 |title=Eighth Grade audio commentary |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref>\n\nTo write dialogue representing [[Generation Z]], Burnham watched YouTube.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Burnham's personal views on the differences between Generation Z and its predecessors inspired a scene where the character Trevor theorizes access to social media at an early age molded the generation's minds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-700514/ |title=Bo Burnham on 'Eighth Grade,' Anxiety and Why Social Media Is a Curse |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |first=Logan |last=Hill |date=July 18, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052520/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-interview-700514/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla and Mark's relationship is based on Burnham's relationship with his mother.<ref name=\"Rubin\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/features/bo-burnham-interview-eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-1202877506/ |title=Bo Burnham Wishes 'Eighth Grade' Wasn't Rated R |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Rebecca |last=Rubin |date=July 20, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815112353/https://variety.com/2018/film/features/bo-burnham-interview-eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-1202877506/ |archive-date=August 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham viewed a teenager's relationship with his or her parent as a stage where \"You want independence, and you also want affirmation\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/bo-burnham-on-the-incredible-honesty-of-middle-schoolers-online/566579/ |title=In Middle School, 'You're Trying to Build a Parachute as You're Falling' |work=[[The Atlantic]] |first=Julie |last=Beck |date=August 1, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052525/https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/bo-burnham-on-the-incredible-honesty-of-middle-schoolers-online/566579/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Rudin]], [[Eli Bush]] and [[A24 (company)|A24]] would go on to produce the movie with a budget of $2 million.<ref name=\"Sandberg\"/> A24 executive Nicolette Aizenberg remarked ''Eighth Grade'' was \"personal\" to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/03/business/media/a24-studio.html |title=The Little Movie Studio That Could |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Barnes |first=Brooks |date=March 3, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617192730/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/03/business/media/a24-studio.html |archive-date=June 17, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham spent years seeking financing, confident he was marketable with his success as a comedian.<ref name=\"Nemiroff\">{{cite interview |url=http://collider.com/bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-eighth-grade-interview/#images |title=Bo Burnham & Elsie Fisher on 'Eighth Grade' and Avoiding Teen Tropes |first1=Perri |last1=Nemiroff |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=2018 |website=[[Collider.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823035828/http://collider.com/bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-eighth-grade-interview/#images |archivedate=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"EricJohnson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.recode.net/2018/7/30/17631478/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-social-media-movie-peter-kafka-recode-podcast|title='Eighth Grade' director Bo Burnham is happy that a lot of people 'have no idea who I am' |first=Eric |last=Johnson |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |date=July 30, 2018 |work=[[Recode]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731111649/https://www.recode.net/2018/7/30/17631478/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-social-media-movie-peter-kafka-recode-podcast |archive-date=July 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Although he had not directed a feature before, Burnham was adamant to be allowed to direct, and spent eight months before principal photography reading books such as [[Sidney Lumet]]'s ''Making Movies''.<ref name=\"Sandberg\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nFifty teenagers auditioned for the role of Kayla.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Burnham discovered [[Elsie Fisher]] on YouTube and had her audition three times.<ref name=\"FisherBurnham\" /> Fisher, then 13, said she had struggled to find a part realistically depicting a teenager before auditioning for ''Eighth Grade''.<ref name=\"Bahr\"/> Burnham cast Fisher because, \"She was the only one who felt like a shy kid pretending to be confident \u2013 everyone else felt like a confident kid pretending to be shy\".<ref name=\"Ryan\"/> Fisher said one reason she was apprehensive at the first audition was that she was a fan of Burnham's comedy. She was drawn to the part because Kayla's speech mannerisms are similar to hers.<ref name=\"Nemiroff\"/> She was graduated eighth grade one week before the production began.<ref name=\"Bitran\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-1202871281/ |title=How Casting a Girl Kept Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' Current |first=Tara |last=Bitran |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014147/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-1202871281/ |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Upon reviewing the screenplay, Fisher's father shouted and swore reading the \"truth or dare\" scene, but made sure his daughter was comfortable with the material.<ref name=\"Bahr\">{{cite news |title=Bo Burnham explores the awkwardness of 'Eighth Grade' |first=Lindsey |last=Bahr |url=https://apnews.com/2171ca14b0bc423fac2b0ee6735ebc42 |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824145442/https://apnews.com/2171ca14b0bc423fac2b0ee6735ebc42 |archivedate=August 24, 2018 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |location=Los Angeles |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBurnham considered [[Josh Hamilton (actor)|Josh Hamilton]] to have a \"dad vibe\".<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> Daniel Zolghadri was cast as Riley. Because of the \"truth or dare\" scene, many young actors who auditioned played the part as sinister, but Burnham coached Zolghadri to be \"the opposite of creepy\".<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> [[Emily Robinson]] and Imani Lewis were teenagers when cast and both said they found the depiction of anxiety relatable.<ref name=\"Juzwiak\"/> Jake Ryan, who played Gabe, remarked that in the screenplay Gabe \"was supposed to be off-centered\", and not knowing the meaning of this phrase, played himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/scene-stealer-jake-ryan-just-tried-to-be-himself-in-eighth-grade-1203099711/ |title=Scene Stealer Jake Ryan Just Tried to Be Himself in 'Eighth Grade' |first=Susan |last=Young |accessdate=January 4, 2019 |date=January 10, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105200707/https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/scene-stealer-jake-ryan-just-tried-to-be-himself-in-eighth-grade-1203099711/ |archive-date=January 5, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nActual teachers and students at Suffern Middle School in New York were used as [[extra (acting)|extras]], with principal Brian Fox saying five to 10 students were cast.<ref name=\"Goldblatt\"/> During the audition process for the real-life eighth graders, one student claimed having [[eczema]] was her \"special talent\" and another auditioned by \"eating a [[bell pepper]] like an apple.\" Burnham accepted this as a qualification.<ref>{{cite interview |first1=John |last1=Dickerson |first2=Gayle |last2=King |first3=John |last3=Dickerson  |title=Bo Burnham talk about his new acclaimed coming of age film Eighth Grade |date=July 23, 2018 |work=[[CBS This Morning]]  }}</ref> Band teacher Dave Yarrington said Burnham cast him because he \"liked my look\".<ref name=\"Goldblatt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/local/rockland/suffern/2018/07/19/suffern-students-eighth-grade-movie/799603002/ |title=Suffern students talk about appearing in movie 'Eighth Grade' and being in eighth grade |work=[[The Journal News]] |first=Rochel Leah |last=Goldblatt |date=July 19, 2018 |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910205546/https://www.lohud.com/story/news/local/rockland/suffern/2018/07/19/suffern-students-eighth-grade-movie/799603002/?from=new-cookie |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:9.6.07.PalisadesCenterMall.JPG|thumb|Filming took place at the exterior of the [[Palisades Center]].]]\nThe film was shot in [[Suffern, New York]] in summer 2017, over 27 days,<ref name=\"Blickley\" /><ref name=\"Sandberg\"/> with shooting at Suffern Middle School in July.<ref name=\"Ryan\"/><ref name=\"Goldblatt\"/> For the mall scenes, exterior shots were taken at [[Palisades Center]] in [[West Nyack, New York]], while interior scenes were shot at the nearby [[The Galleria at White Plains]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westchestermagazine.com/Bo-Burnhams-Film-Eighth-Grade-Jacob-Burns/ |title=Spot the Local Scenery in Bo Burnham's Debut Film 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[Westchester Magazine]] |first=Dave |last=Zucker |date=July 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820005949/http://www.westchestermagazine.com/Bo-Burnhams-Film-Eighth-Grade-Jacob-Burns/ |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham chose not to obscure the natural look of Fisher's skin,<ref name=\"Rubin\"/> who wore some make-up but her acne was left visible.<ref name=\"Juzwiak\">{{cite web |url=https://themuse.jezebel.com/what-eighth-grade-means-to-its-teen-stars-1827804845 |title=What Eighth Grade Means to Its Teen Stars |work=[[Jezebel.com]] |last=Juzwiak |first=Rich |date=July 23, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726005811/https://themuse.jezebel.com/what-eighth-grade-means-to-its-teen-stars-1827804845 |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Kayla's use of the phrase \"Gucci!\" to [[Sign-on and sign-off|sign-off]] her video blogs came from Fisher's habit of ending conversations this way, which was also imitated by Burnham and others on set.<ref name=\"FisherBurnham\">{{cite interview |url=https://variety.com/video/eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-sundance-interview/ |title=Gucci! How 'Eighth Grade' Got Their Catch Phrase |first1=Elsie |last1=Fisher |first2=Burnham |last2=Bo |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014247/https://variety.com/video/eighth-grade-elsie-fisher-sundance-interview/ |archivedate=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fisher's other habits of slouching and rubbing her arm were also incorporated into her character.<ref>{{cite AV media |first=Elsie |last=Fisher |date=2018 |title=You're Not Alone: Life in Eighth Grade |work=Eighth Grade |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> The filmmakers adopted Fisher's advice that \"no one uses [[Facebook]] anymore\", and it was substituted in the film with [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-interview-comedy-sundance-london-a8369081.html |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade finally tells the truth about growing up with the internet |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Loughrey |first=Clarisse |date=May 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909025206/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/eighth-grade-bo-burnham-interview-comedy-sundance-london-a8369081.html |archive-date=September 9, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Beyond minor changes, [[improvisation]] was rarely employed.<ref name=\"Mulcahey\"/>\n\nTo depict texting, Burnham rejected using [[visual effects]] to show messages as on-screen [[Speech balloon|bubbles]], as in ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]''. He opted for a \"practical\" portrayal, filming the phones themselves.<ref name=\"Arkin\"/> Kayla's video blogs were shot with an actual [[MacBook Pro]].<ref name=\"Mulcahey\">{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/105023-zooms-are-totally-underutilized-bo-burnham-on-eighth-grade-at-sxsw-2018/#.W5EtTuhKjIU |title='Zooms are Totally Underutilized': Bo Burnham on Eighth Grade |work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] |last=Mulcahey |first=Matt |date=July 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906195748/https://filmmakermagazine.com/105023-zooms-are-totally-underutilized-bo-burnham-on-eighth-grade-at-sxsw-2018/#.W5EtTuhKjIU |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Because the actual Internet was depicted, production designer Sam Lisenco and [[theatrical property|prop]] designer Erica Severson created many false Instagram and Twitter accounts.<ref name=\"BurnhamFeaturette\">{{cite AV media |first=Bo |last=Burnham |date=2018 |title=You're Not Alone: Life in Eighth Grade |work=Eighth Grade |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> The filmmakers primarily used [[Red Digital Cinema]] cameras and wide lenses, with Burnham favoring the use of camera [[Zooming (filmmaking)|zooming]].<ref name=\"Mulcahey\" />\n\nThe \"truth or dare\" scene was shot with only eight crew members along with Fisher and Zolghadri.<ref name=\"BurnhamCommentary\"/> Fisher had the screenplay on her lap to read when her character was looking down.<ref name=\"FisherCommentary\">{{cite AV media |first=Elsie |last=Fisher |date=2018 |title=Eighth Grade audio commentary |medium=Blu-ray |publisher=[[Elevation Pictures]]}}</ref> She explained, \"We just wanted to take a sensitive approach and just be honest about this, and portray a type of toxic event that can happen.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-film-coming-of-age-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-1201983071/ |title='Eighth Grade': How a Twentysomething Dude Made the Year's Best Film About Female Coming-of-Age |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816110603/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/eighth-grade-film-coming-of-age-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher-1201983071/ |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Due to Fisher being underage when shooting the banana scene, it was similarly shot with minimal crew present.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-director-star-talk-sexually-suggestive-scenes-casting-real-life-kids-1133659 |title='Eighth Grade' Director, Star Talk 'Sexually Suggestive' Scenes, Casting 'Real-Life Kids' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Geschwind |first=Max |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510014921/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-director-star-talk-sexually-suggestive-scenes-casting-real-life-kids-1133659 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\n[[File:Anna Meredith.jpg|thumb|left|Electronic music composer [[Anna Meredith]] wrote the score.]]\nEditor Jennifer Lilly and Burnham did not complete post-production until three days before the premiere at [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] in January 2018.<ref name=\"Sandberg\" /> Fisher singing in ''[[Masha and the Bear]]'' at age 11 was used in the film.<ref name=\"FisherCommentary\" />{{Unclear inline|reason=Not clear if her character in 'Masha and the Bear' or Fisher herself at age 11 was shown in the film.|date=February 2020}}\n\nBritish [[electronic music|electronic]] composer and solo musician [[Anna Meredith]] wrote and recorded the film's score in her [[London]] studio. Deliberately avoiding a \"cute\" score, Burnham turned to electronic music because \"Kayla\u2019s experience feels so intense to her,\" and chose Meredith since her style was unlike \"a lot of electronic music [\u2026] very cold and masculine.\"<ref name=\"Mulcahey\" /> As her first film score, Meredith described the process as a \"challenge,\" emphasizing that as a composer, \"you don\u2019t just present the music you want. You try to do what the film needs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/08/anna-meredith-is-it-classical-is-it-pop-proms |title=Anna Meredith: 'Is it classical, is it pop? I don't really think about it that way' |first=Fiona |last=Maddocks |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 8, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221227/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/08/anna-meredith-is-it-classical-is-it-pop-proms |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBurnham used \"[[Orinoco Flow]]\" by Irish musician [[Enya]] for a [[Montage (filmmaking)|montage]] scene of Kayla browsing social media. He wanted to use the song to convey that the Internet was \"religious\" and \"spiritual\" for Kayla. Burnham wrote a letter to Enya for her personal permission to use the song, which she granted.<ref name=\"Blickley\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered in competition at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]] on January 19,<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sundance-film-festival-2018-lineup-program-1202625522/ |title=Sundance Film Festival Unveils Full 2018 Features Lineup |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 29, 2017 |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |last=Debruge |first=Peter |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130092712/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/sundance-film-festival-2018-lineup-program-1202625522/ |archive-date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/104473-my-own-feeling-of-unease-in-living-with-and-on-the-internet-director-bo-burnham-eighth-grade/#.W5BK0ehKjIU |title='My Own Feeling of Unease in Living with and on the Internet': Director Bo Burnham, Eighth Grade |work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] |date=January 19, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014144/https://filmmakermagazine.com/104473-my-own-feeling-of-unease-in-living-with-and-on-the-internet-director-bo-burnham-eighth-grade/#.W5BK0ehKjIU |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and was subsequently screened at the [[San Francisco International Film Festival]] in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailycal.org/2018/04/18/2018-san-francisco-international-film-festival/ |title=2018 San Francisco International Film Festival offers profound variety of films |author=Staff |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=April 18, 2018 |work=[[The Daily Californian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221237/http://www.dailycal.org/2018/04/18/2018-san-francisco-international-film-festival/ |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' also screened at the [[Seattle International Film Festival]] at its closing weekend in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/siff-2018-the-best-of-the-fests-final-weekend/ |title=SIFF 2018: The best of the fest's final weekend |first=Hunter |last=Harris |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=June 6, 2018 |work=[[Seattle Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014246/https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/siff-2018-the-best-of-the-fests-final-weekend/ |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[A24 (company)|A24]] gave ''Eighth Grade'' its [[limited release]] on July 13,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/03/eighth-grade-trailer-bo-burnhams-directorial-debut.html |title=Eighth Grade Trailer: Being a Tween Right Now Looks Rough |first=Hunter |last=Harris |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018 |website=[[Vulture.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014116/http://www.vulture.com/2018/03/eighth-grade-trailer-bo-burnhams-directorial-debut.html |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> before moving it to wide release August 3.<ref name=\"Mendelson\"/> The [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave ''Eighth Grade'' an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film rating|R rating]] for profanity and content about fellatio.<ref name=\"Axelrod\"/> Burnham had the option to edit the film to secure a more permissive PG-13 but chose not to do so, commenting, \"It didn't feel like our responsibility to portray a reality that was appropriate for kids, but rather portray the reality that the kids are actually living in\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/07/21/bo-burnham-refused-to-edit-r-rated-eighth-grade-into-pg-13-and-advises-teenagers-to-sneak-in/ |title=Bo Burnham refused to edit R-rated 'Eighth Grade' into PG-13 and advises teenagers to 'sneak in' |first=Alexanda |last=Clinton |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 21, 2018 |website=[[Salon.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823014536/https://www.salon.com/2018/07/21/bo-burnham-refused-to-edit-r-rated-eighth-grade-into-pg-13-and-advises-teenagers-to-sneak-in/ |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Critics decried the MPAA's decision for denying teenage viewers a film with positive messages.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Some critics think the film could have a positive impact on teenagers, allowing them to relate to characters going through a complicated phase in their lives and opening dialogue about sex, bullying and self-image.}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/summer-movies/2018/7/18/17574516/eighth-grade-r-rating-mpaa-teen-movies |title=Eighth Grade's R rating deters actual 8th-graders from seeing it. What a shame |first=Charles |last=Bramesco |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 18, 2018 |website=[[Vox.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906014100/https://www.vox.com/summer-movies/2018/7/18/17574516/eighth-grade-r-rating-mpaa-teen-movies |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |title=Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' isn't trying to teach you anything, and that's the beauty of it |first=Taylor |last=Seely |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822111608/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  |quote=Parents should see this with their kids (and ignore the R rating).}}</ref> MPAA representative Chris Ortman stated A24 never appealed the R rating, though having the right to do so.<ref name=\"Seely\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |title=Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' isn't trying to teach you anything, and that's the beauty of it |first=Taylor |last=Seely |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822111608/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/allthemoms/2018/08/08/bo-burnhams-eighth-grade-opens-communication-parents-kids/934133002/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham regretted the rating because it excluded middle school-aged youth.<ref name=\"Rubin\"/> To get around the rating, A24 arranged one free, unrated screening in each U.S. state on August 8.<ref name=\"Axelrod\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Burnham approved of Canada's [[Canadian motion picture rating system|14A rating]]. ''Eighth Grade'' began screening in Canadian cities on August 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timescolonist.com/eighth-grade-director-says-film-s-14a-rating-in-canada-reflects-ideal-audience-1.23380841 |title='Eighth Grade' directorsays film's 14A rating in Canada reflects ideal audience |first=Ryan |last=Porter |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=July 26, 2018 |work=[[Times Colonist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906124539/https://www.timescolonist.com/eighth-grade-director-says-film-s-14a-rating-in-canada-reflects-ideal-audience-1.23380841 |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, [[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] acquired international distribution rights to the film.<ref name=\"DAlessandro\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-a24-oscars-sony-worldwide-box-office-1202471593/|title='Eighth Grade' Graduates: Sony Pictures WW Takes Foreign As A24 Positions Bo Burnham's Indie Wonder For Awards Season|website=Deadline|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=September 26, 2018|accessdate=September 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926195538/https://deadline.com/2018/09/bo-burnham-eighth-grade-a24-oscars-sony-worldwide-box-office-1202471593/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lionsgate]] prepared the DVD and [[Blu-ray]] release in [[DVD region code#Region 1|Region 1]] with a director's commentary and deleted scenes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-new-video-eighth-grade-20180928-story.html |title=New video: 'Eighth Grade' is a sublime and profound look at the world of a young teen |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Noel |last=Murray |date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004140154/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-new-video-eighth-grade-20180928-story.html |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> for distribution beginning October 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/entertainmentlife/20181004/new-on-dvd-oct-9-have-no-reservations-about-hotel-artemis-on-dvd |title=New on DVD Oct. 9: Have no reservations about 'Hotel Artemis' on DVD |work =[[Providence Journal]] |first=Rick |last=Bentley |date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006003754/http://www.providencejournal.com/entertainmentlife/20181004/new-on-dvd-oct-9-have-no-reservations-about-hotel-artemis-on-dvd |archive-date=October 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released in Belgium and the Netherlands in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lesoir.be/207644/article/2019-02-19/le-charme-de-robert-redford-opere-toujours-nos-critiques-des-sorties-cinema |title=Le charme de Robert Redford op\u00e8re toujours: nos critiques des sorties cin\u00e9ma |last=Staff |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |date=February 19, 2019 |work=[[Le Soir]] |language=French |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190510013553/https://www.lesoir.be/207644/article/2019-02-19/le-charme-de-robert-redford-opere-toujours-nos-critiques-des-sorties-cinema |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/uit/5748771/deze-films-draaien-vanaf-deze-week-in-de-bioscoop-week-8.html |title=Deze films draaien vanaf deze week in de bioscoop (week 8) |last=Staff |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |date=February 21, 2019 |website=[[Nu.nl]] |language=Dutch |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190510013419/https://www.nu.nl/uit/5748771/deze-films-draaien-vanaf-deze-week-in-de-bioscoop-week-8.html |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> United Kingdom and Irish releases occurred on April 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/uk-trailer-eighth-grade/ |title=UK Trailer For Eighth Grade |first=James |last=White |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |date=January 28, 2018 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208064213/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/uk-trailer-eighth-grade/ |archive-date=February 8, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/bo-burnham-takes-to-red-carpet-for-irish-premiere-of-eighth-grade-1.3804590 |title=Bo Burnham takes to red carpet for Irish premiere of 'Eighth Grade' |first=Tara |last=Brady |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |date=February 25, 2019 |work=[[Irish Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226050704/https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/bo-burnham-takes-to-red-carpet-for-irish-premiere-of-eighth-grade-1.3804590 |archive-date=February 26, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Eighth Grade''{{'}}s opening weekend in four theaters beginning July 13 saw a gross of $252,284, an average of $63,071 per screen.<ref>{{cite news |title='Screenscaper' collapses as 'Hotel' Soars |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 16, 2018 |first=Sonaiya |last=Kelley }}</ref> It surpassed [[Wes Anderson]]'s ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]'' ($60,011) for the best per-screen average of 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-lights-up-indie-box-office-with-top-per-screen-average-of-2018/ |title='Eighth Grade' Lights Up Indie Box Office With Best Per Screen Average of 2018 |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |date=July 15, 2018 |work=[[The Wrap]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815135259/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-lights-up-indie-box-office-with-top-per-screen-average-of-2018/ |archive-date=August 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/dwayne-johnson-skyscraper-ant-man-and-the-wasp-hotel-transylvania-3-weekend-box-office-1202426089/ |title='Skyscraper' Up In Flames With $24M+ As 'Hotel Transylvania 3' Books $42M+ Weekend Voyage |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=July 15, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=July 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715074033/https://deadline.com/2018/07/dwayne-johnson-skyscraper-ant-man-and-the-wasp-hotel-transylvania-3-weekend-box-office-1202426089/ |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and was in-turn surpassed by ''[[Free Solo]]'' ($75,201) at the end of September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/free-solo-top-screen-average-1202962594/ |title='Free Solo' Documentary Climbs Indie Box Office With Best Screen Average of 2018 |last=Rubin |first=Rebecca |date=September 30, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205850/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/free-solo-top-screen-average-1202962594/ |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' expanded to 33 theaters in its second weekend, grossing $794,370,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/mcqueen-blindspotting-box-office-results-eighth-grade-1202431444/ |title='McQueen' Stylish And 'Blindspotting' Solid In Debuts, 'Eighth Grade' Gets High Marks In Week 2 \u2013 Specialty Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 22, 2018 |first=Brian |last=Brooks |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205949/https://deadline.com/2018/07/mcqueen-blindspotting-box-office-results-eighth-grade-1202431444/ |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and then made $1.3 million from 158 theaters in its third weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-fallout-opening-weekend-1202434739/ |title='Mission' Accomplished: 'Fallout' $61M+ Opening Reps Record For Tom Cruise Franchise \u2013 Sunday |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=July 29, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=July 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729085704/https://deadline.com/2018/07/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-fallout-opening-weekend-1202434739/ |archive-date=July 29, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The film began its wide release on August 3 at 1,084 theaters,<ref name=\"Mendelson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/04/friday-box-office-teen-titans-go-drops-66-as-incredibles-2-passes-the-dark-knight/#6049bb1f5c99 |title=Friday Box Office: 'Teen Titans Go' Drops 66% As 'Incredibles 2' Passes 'The Dark Knight' |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 4, 2018 |first=Scott |last=Mendelson |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930210127/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/04/friday-box-office-teen-titans-go-drops-66-as-incredibles-2-passes-the-dark-knight/#6049bb1f5c99 |archive-date=September 30, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and earned $6.6 million by August 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-screenings-not-enforcing-r-rating-1132476 |title='Eighth Grade': Free Screenings Across Country Won't Enforce R-Rating |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 6, 2018 |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820062054/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eighth-grade-screenings-not-enforcing-r-rating-1132476 |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nBy August 16 the film earned $10.5 million, the sixth-highest grossing independent domestic film of the summer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/7-highest-grossing-indie-movies-at-the-us-box-office-this-summer-2018-8 |title=The 7 highest-grossing indie movies at the US box office this summer |last=Clark |first=Travis |date=August 16, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820113737/https://www.businessinsider.com/7-highest-grossing-indie-movies-at-the-us-box-office-this-summer-2018-8 |archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> By September 26 it had grossed $13.5 million in North America.<ref name=\"DAlessandro\"/> {{asof|2019|6|20|df=US}} it has grossed $14.3 million worldwide.<ref name=\"Numbers\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 99% based on 294 reviews, with an average rating of 8.85/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Eighth Grade'' takes a look at its titular time period that offers a rare and resounding ring of truth while heralding breakthroughs for writer-director Bo Burnham and captivating star Elsie Fisher.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Eighth Grade (2018)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eighth_grade|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=July 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816044516/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eighth_grade/|archive-date=August 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 89 out of 100, based on 49 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Eighth Grade Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/eighth-grade|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=August 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726011326/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/eighth-grade|archive-date=July 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] judged the film \"sweet and intelligent\" and credited Fisher for \"an authentic and utterly natural performance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/eighth-grade-brilliantly-captures-the-agony-and-ecstasy-of-adolescence/ |title='Eighth Grade' brilliantly captures the agony and ecstasy of adolescence |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 18, 2018 |first=Richard |last=Roeper |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102145/https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/eighth-grade-brilliantly-captures-the-agony-and-ecstasy-of-adolescence/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  [[Ty Burr]] also cited Fisher for a performance showing \"supreme awkwardness and not a shred of vanity\" and Josh Hamilton for playing his part with \"an empathetic cringe\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2018/07/18/eighth-grade-middle-school-marvel/6JhM75hqC1PTuYDsjxwSrK/story.html |title='Eighth Grade' is a middle school marvel |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 18, 2018 |first=Ty |last=Burr |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102109/https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2018/07/18/eighth-grade-middle-school-marvel/6JhM75hqC1PTuYDsjxwSrK/story.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} Manohla Dargis cited Josh Hamilton as \"note-perfect\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/11/movies/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham.html |title=Review: All the Feels, Hurts and Laughs of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Manohla |last=Dargis |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816144855/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/11/movies/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham.html |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Ann Hornaday of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' highlighted Fisher for \"a raw, radiantly generous performance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/eighth-grade-has-given-us-a-new-iconic-teenage-heroine-for-the-ages/2018/07/18/6ea2a590-860c-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on |title='Eighth Grade' has given us a new iconic teenage heroine for the ages |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 19, 2018 |first=Ann |last=Hornaday |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905042938/https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/eighth-grade-has-given-us-a-new-iconic-teenage-heroine-for-the-ages/2018/07/18/6ea2a590-860c-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on&utm_term=.1082c3d23287 |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Peter Debruge judged the film \"achingly honest\" but clich\u00e9d in having Kayla infatuated with one boy (played by Luke Prael) and ignoring a better love interest (played by Jake Ryan) until the later acts.<ref name=\"Debruge\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/eighth-grade-review-1202670924/ |title=Film Review: 'Eighth Grade' |first=Peter |last=Debruge |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=January 20, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615111236/https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/eighth-grade-review-1202670924/ |archive-date=June 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] hailed ''Eighth Grade'' as \"special and unique\" for its \"empathy\", writing it is neutral on the Internet's effects on society but Kayla is addicted to electronics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/eighth-grade-review-tender-take-on-teen-angst-is-flat-out-triumph-696153/ |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Tender Take on Teen Angst Is Flat-Out Triumph |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Peter |last=Travers |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102133/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/eighth-grade-review-tender-take-on-teen-angst-is-flat-out-triumph-696153/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> For ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Naomi Fry credited ''Eighth Grade'' with \"queasy verisimilitude\" and exploring the impact of [[social media]] on the lives of teenagers.<ref name=\"Fry\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |title=The Cringey Teen Spirit of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 1, 2018 |first=Naomi |last=Fry |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919084831/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' contributor Dani Di Placido wrote the depiction of electronics was better than in most films, showing they were \"powerful communicative tools that can isolate us, or bring us together, depending on how we choose to use them\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/05/eighth-grade-review-coming-of-age-in-the-modern-world/#2d0be9c93974 |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Coming-Of-Age In The Modern World |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 5, 2018 |first=Dani |last=Di Placido |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907183920/https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/05/eighth-grade-review-coming-of-age-in-the-modern-world/#2d0be9c93974 |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Considering how Burnham first achieved notoriety on the Internet, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' critic Michael Phillips wrote Burnham was familiar with \"the agitating seductions of our online lives\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-eighth-grade-rev-0716-story.html |title='Eighth Grade' review: Hello 12, hello 13, hello 'likes' in the age of techno-anxiety |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 16, 2018 |first=Michael |last=Phillips |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907053444/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-eighth-grade-rev-0716-story.html |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:MollyRingwaldApr2013.jpg|thumb|Media outlets quoted actress [[Molly Ringwald]]'s [[Twitter|tweet]] praising ''Eighth Grade'' as a film about adolescence.]] \nIn ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', Justin Chang evaluated ''Eighth Grade'' as \"sharp, sensitive and enormously affecting\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-eighth-grade-review-20180711-story.html |title=Review: Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' is a beautifully honest portrait of adolescent girlhood |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Justin |last=Chang |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822160806/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-eighth-grade-review-20180711-story.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it an A, with Chris Nashawaty praising Burnham for capturing Kayla's anxiety and hopes, depicted \"in all of their miraculous, cringeworthy, universal beauty\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/10/eighth-grade-review/ |title=Bo Burnham's Eighth Grade is heartbreaking, heartwarming, and a total charmer: EW review |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 10, 2018 |first=Chris |last=Nashawaty |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102118/https://ew.com/movies/2018/07/10/eighth-grade-review/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' named the scenes between Fisher and Hamilton to be among the \"funniest, most poignant\" scenes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/eighth-grade-sucks-eighth-grade-doesn-t-1827547509 |title=Eighth grade sucks. Eighth Grade doesn't |first=A.A. |last=Dowd |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221327/https://film.avclub.com/eighth-grade-sucks-eighth-grade-doesn-t-1827547509 |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''[[SF Gate]]'' critic Peter Hartlaub wrote the comedy is combined with \"pure social and sexual horror\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Eighth-Grade-is-an-authentic-compassionate-13086976.php |title='Eighth Grade' is an authentic, compassionate debut film from Bo Burnham |first=Peter |last=Hartlaub |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=July 19, 2018 |work=[[SF Gate]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822023326/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Eighth-Grade-is-an-authentic-compassionate-13086976.php |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Benjamin Lee commented on the score in ''[[The Guardian]]'', writing the use of [[electronic music]] was unexpected but \"effective\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/11/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher |title=Eighth Grade review \u2013 adolescence is excruciating in finely observed gem |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=July 11, 2018 |first=Benjamin |last=Lee |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822121836/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/11/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham-elsie-fisher |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nMedia outlets also referenced actress [[Molly Ringwald]]'s approval.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |title='Eighth Grade' fights its R rating with free screenings Wednesday |first=Josh |last=Axelrod |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |date=August 8, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |quote=One such fan is Molly Ringwald, cinema's queen of the coming-of-age flick. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822113241/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/07/movies/eighth-grade-free-screenings-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |title=The Cringey Teen Spirit of 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 1, 2018 |first=Naomi |last=Fry |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |quote=Ringwald tweeted that ''Eighth Grade'' is 'the best movie about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever'\u2014words that carry some weight, coming from a performer who made her name in John Hughes's iconic teen dramedies of the nineteen-eighties. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919084831/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-cringey-teen-spirit-of-eighth-grade |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/molly_ringwald_calls_eight_grade_the_best_teen_film_maybe_ever |title=Molly Ringwald Calls 'Eighth Grade' the Best Teen Film 'Maybe Ever' |first=Alex |last=Hudson |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 26, 2018 |work=[[Exclaim!]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014703/http://exclaim.ca/film/article/molly_ringwald_calls_eight_grade_the_best_teen_film_maybe_ever |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Ringwald tweeted \"I just saw [''Eighth Grade''] and thought it was the best film about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MollyRingwald |number=1022250943298121728 |date=July 25, 2018 |title=I just saw @eighthgrademov and thought it was the best film about adolescence I've seen in a long time. Maybe ever.}}</ref> Ringwald contrasted the depiction of consent in ''Eighth Grade'' to that in [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]]' ''[[The Breakfast Club]]'' (1985), which she starred in, concluding Burnham's film was more updated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/stevens/ct-life-stevens-thursday-eighth-grade-movie-0726-story.html |title='Eighth Grade' is the anti-'Breakfast Club,' and I'm here for it |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 26, 2018 |first=Heidi |last=Stevens |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014528/http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/stevens/ct-life-stevens-thursday-eighth-grade-movie-0726-story.html |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' has been favorably compared with Hughes' filmography generally.<ref>Examples:\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/eighth-grade-is-instant-classic-by-youtube-star-bo-burnham-2018-7 |title='Eighth Grade' is an instant classic written and directed by a 27-year-old \u2014 and it's our indie movie pick for this weekend |first=Jason |last=Guerrasio |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 27, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |quote=The high school genre has its fair share of classics ... anything by John Hughes. But those all feel like they were made by a bunch of adults far removed from adolescence. And that's why ''Eighth Grade'' will go down as a special movie. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910061000/https://www.businessinsider.com/eighth-grade-is-instant-classic-by-youtube-star-bo-burnham-2018-7 |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/07/eighth-grade-is-a-mesmerizing-heartfelt-portrait-of-teenhood/565013/ |title=Eighth Grade Is a Mesmerizing, Heartfelt Portrait of Teenhood |first=David |last=Sims |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |quote=The film never seemed to lean into the operatic awkwardness of a [[Todd Solondz]] movie, or the verbose emotionality of a John Hughes work. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014750/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/07/eighth-grade-is-a-mesmerizing-heartfelt-portrait-of-teenhood/565013/ |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-film-review-bo-burnham-memorably-illuminates-the-psyche-of-a-fraught-middle-schooler/ |title='Eighth Grade' Film Review: Bo Burnham Captures Middle School Angst |first=Robert |last=Abele |accessdate=September 9, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[TheWrap]] |quote=Unlike the put-upon adolescents of John Hughes' oeuvre ... [Kayla] isn't armed with barbed one-liners and Hollywoodized nerd-cutes. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910014734/https://www.thewrap.com/eighth-grade-film-review-bo-burnham-memorably-illuminates-the-psyche-of-a-fraught-middle-schooler/ |archive-date=September 10, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAdam Chitwood wrote a mixed review on [[Collider.com]], calling it \"a rough draft\" that needed editing to convey its points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham/#sundance |title='Eighth Grade' Review: Bo Burnham's Directorial Debut Is Awkward AF |website=[[Collider.com]] |date=July 13, 2018 |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507183204/http://collider.com/eighth-grade-review-bo-burnham/#sundance |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Richard Brody]] in ''The New Yorker'' wrote the film was let down by \"sentiment, stereotypes, and good intentions\", and despite Fisher's performance, \"Kayla remains merely a collection of traits\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/eighth-grade |title=Eighth Grade |work=[[The New Yorker]] |first=Richard |last=Brody |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802020735/https://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/eighth-grade |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The ''[[Missoula Independent]]''{{'}}s Molly Laich compared the realism to being \"drilled at the dentist\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://missoulanews.com/entertainment/the-unbearable-heaviness-of-bo-burnham-s-eighth-grade/article_937363c0-95cd-11e8-87bd-37fd16e07643.html |title=The unbearable heaviness of Bo Burnham's 'Eighth Grade' |work=[[Missoula Independent]] |date=August 2, 2018 |first=Molly |last=Laich |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905141108/https://missoulanews.com/entertainment/the-unbearable-heaviness-of-bo-burnham-s-eighth-grade/article_937363c0-95cd-11e8-87bd-37fd16e07643.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Eighth Grade}}\nThe film was entered into competition for the Grand Jury Prize at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Debruge\"/> It had four nominations at the [[Independent Spirit Awards]], including [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Film|Best Film]],<ref name=\"Indie Noms\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/2019-independent-spirit-awards-nominations-1202021241/|title=2019 Independent Spirit Awards Nominees, 'Eighth Grade' & 'We the Animals' Lead |first=Kate |last=Erbland |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |date=November 16, 2018 |website=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117011630/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/2019-independent-spirit-awards-nominations-1202021241/ |archive-date=November 17, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> winning [[Independent Spirit Award for Best First Screenplay|Best First Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2019-spirit-awards-winners-complete-list-1203147196/ |title=2019 Indie Spirit Awards Winners: Complete List (Updating Live) |author=Staff |accessdate=February 23, 2019 |date=February 23, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190224004705/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2019-spirit-awards-winners-complete-list-1203147196/ |archive-date=February 24, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fisher received her first [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination for the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-mn-golden-globes-elsie-fisher-20181206-story.html |title=Elsie Fisher of 'Eighth Grade' on scoring her first Golden Globe nomination and her social media reaction |last=Kaufman |first=Amy |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207224638/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-mn-golden-globes-elsie-fisher-20181206-story.html |archivedate=December 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> but the film was not nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] despite reporter Kyle Buchanan considering it to be A24's best candidate for the category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/06/movies/golden-globes-movies.html |title=Golden Globes' Biggest Snubs: 'Widows' and 'First Man' Take Hits |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207121547/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/06/movies/golden-globes-movies.html |archivedate=December 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBurnham and Fisher each won Breakthrough awards at the [[Gotham Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/gotham-awards-winners-list-2018-new-york-1203037073/ |title='The Rider' Wins Best Feature at Gotham Awards (Complete Winners List) |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=November 26, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127031716/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/gotham-awards-winners-list-2018-new-york-1203037073/ |archive-date=November 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> ''Eighth Grade'' additionally won two [[National Board of Review|National Board of Review Awards]], including being named in the [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films|Top Ten Films of 2018]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/national-board-of-review-2018-winners-1202023489/ |title=National Board of Review 2018 Winners: 'Green Book' Named Best Film, Lady Gaga Best Actress |first=Zack |last=Sharf |accessdate=November 27, 2018 |date=November 27, 2018 |website=[[Indiewire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127230303/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/11/national-board-of-review-2018-winners-1202023489/ |archive-date=November 27, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> the [[American Film Institute]] also included it in its annual top 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/afi-top-10-movies-of-2018-list |title=AFI Reveals Its Top 10 Films of 2018, Including 'Black Panther' and 'Eighth Grade' |website=[[Collider.com]] |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=December 4, 2018 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205041752/http://collider.com/afi-top-10-movies-of-2018-list |archivedate=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film was nominated for three [[Satellite Awards]], including Best Independent Film,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/2018_Press_Academy_NOMINATIONS.pdf |title=2018 Nominations Ballot |accessdate=December 2, 2018 |date=November 28, 2018 |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130052029/http://www.pressacademy.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/2018_Press_Academy_NOMINATIONS.pdf |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and three [[Critics' Choice Awards]], winning [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer|Best Young Performer]] for Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/2019-critics-choice-awards-winners-nominees-full-list-1203106702/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards: Winners and Nominees |first=Kristopher |last=Tapley |accessdate=January 13, 2019 |date=January 13, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114010818/https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/2019-critics-choice-awards-winners-nominees-full-list-1203106702/ |archive-date=January 14, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Additionally, Burnham won the [[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 First-Time Feature Film|Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding First-Time Feature]] and the [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Original Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dga-awards-2019-winners-list-1203127035/ |title=DGA Awards: The Complete Winners List (Updating Live) |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Staff |date=February 2, 2019 |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203063226/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dga-awards-2019-winners-list-1203127035/ |archivedate=February 3, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/writers-guild-awards-2019-winners-list-1202044753/ |title=Writers Guild Awards 2019: Full Winners List (Updating Live) |website=[[IndieWire]] |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=February 17, 2019 |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218023224/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/writers-guild-awards-2019-winners-list-1202044753/ |archivedate=February 18, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|7014006|Eighth Grade}}\n\n{{Bo Burnham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eighth Grade}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about children]]\n[[Category:Films about social media]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bo Burnham]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2017]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bo Burnham]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eighth_Grade_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Winged Migration", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 film}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{prose|date=September 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = Winged Migration\n| image           = Winged Migration movie.jpg\n| image_size      = 225px\n| caption         = theatrical poster\n| director        = [[Jacques Perrin]],<br>[[Jacques Cluzaud]],<br>[[Michel Debats]]\n| writer          = [[Jean Dorst]]<br>Jacques Perrin\n| narrator        = Jacques Perrin<br>[[Philippe Labro]]\n| producer        = [[Christophe Barratier]],<br>Jacques Perrin\n| music           = [[Bruno Coulais]]\n| cinematographer =\n| editing         =\n| distributor     = [[BAC Films]]\n| released        = 12 December 2001 ''(<small>France</small>)''\n| runtime         = 98 minutes\n| country        = France<br>Italy<br>Germany<br>Switzerland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.unifrance.org/movie/15634/winged-migration|title=Winged Migration (2000)|website=en.unifrance.org}}</ref>\n| language        = English, French\n| budget          = $23.6 million\n| gross           = $52.8 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=2089|title=Le Peuple migrateur (Winged Migration) (2001)- JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Winged Migration''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Le Peuple Migrateur'''}}, also known as '''''The Travelling Birds''''' in some UK releases, or '''''The Travelling Birds: An Adventure in Flight''''' in Australia) is a 2001 [[documentary film]] directed by [[Jacques Cluzaud]], [[Michel Debats]] and [[Jacques Perrin]], who was also one of the writers and narrators, showcasing the immense journeys routinely made by birds during their [[Bird migration|migrations]].\n\nThe film is dedicated to the French [[ornithologist]] [[Jean Dorst]].\n\n==Production==\nThe movie was shot over the course of four years on all seven continents. It was shot using in-flight cameras, most of the footage is aerial, and the viewer appears to be flying alongside birds of successive species, especially [[Canada geese]]. They traverse every kind of weather and [[landscape]], covering vast distances in a flight for survival. The filmmakers exposed over 590 miles of film to create an 89-minute piece. In one case, two months of filming in one location was edited down to less than one minute in the final film.\n\nMuch of the aerial footage was taken of \"tame\" birds. The filmmakers raised birds of several species, including [[stork]]s and [[pelican]]s, from birth. The newborn birds [[imprinting (psychology)|imprinted]] on staff members, and were trained to fly along with the film crews. The birds were also exposed to the film equipment over the course of their lives to ensure that the birds would react the way the filmmakers want. Several of these species had never been imprinted before. Film was shot from [[ultralight aviation|ultralights]], [[paraglider]]s, and [[hot air balloon]]s, as well as [[truck]]s, [[motorcycle]]s, [[motorboat]]s, remote-controlled [[robot]]s, and a [[French Navy]] warship. Its producer says that \"Winged Migration\" is neither a documentary nor [[fiction]], but rather a \"natural tale\".<ref name=\"makingof\">\"Making of\" special feature on the DVD</ref>\n\nThe film states that no [[special effect]]s were used in the filming of the birds, although some entirely [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] segments that view Earth from outer space augment the real-life footage.\n\nThe film's soundtrack by [[Bruno Coulais]] was recorded by Bulgarian vocal group [[Bulgarka Junior Quartet]] in Bulgarian, as well as [[Nick Cave]] in English and [[Robert Wyatt]]. The vocal effects include sequences in which panting is superimposed on wingbeats to give the effect that the viewer is a bird.\n\n'''Release date'''\n\n*\tFrance  2001/12/12                    \n*\tBelgium  2001/12/12\n*\tSwitzerland  2001/12/13...(German speaking region)\n*\tGreece  2001/12/14\n*\tSouth Korea  2002/03/29\n*\tGermany  2002/04/04\n*\tNetherlands  2002/04/18\n*\tHong Kong  2002/06/20\n*\tRussia  2002/06/21...(Moscow Film Festival)\n*\tCzech Republic  2002/07/8...(Karlovy Vary Film Festival)\n*\tCzech Republic  2002/07/18\n*\tCanada  2002/09/08...(Toronto Film Festival)\n*\tTurkey  2002/09/13\n*\tIsrael  2002/09/19\n*\tHungary  2002/09/19\n*\tSpain  2002/09/27\n*\tItaly  2002/11/15\n*\tLithuania  2002/12/27\n*\tPoland  2003/04/04\n*\tJapan  2003/04/05...(Tokyo)\n*\tUSA  2003/04/5...(Philadelphia International Film Festival)\n*\tSlovenia  2003/04/17\n*\tUSA  2003/04/18...(Limited)\n*\tNorway  2003/05/02...(Kristiansand International Children's Film Festival)\n*\tCanada  2003/05/30\n*\tAustralia  2003/06/19\n*\tNorway  2003/06/20\n*\tNew Zealand  2003/07/13...(Auckland International Film Festival)\n*\tMexico  2003/07/25\n*\tDenmark  2003/08/15...(Copenhagen International Film Festival)\n*\tFinland  2003/09/05\n*\tUK  2003/09/05\n*\tDenmark  2003/09/12\n*\tSweden  2003/ 11/07\n*\tIceland  2004/01/23...(French Film Festival)\n*\tArgentina  2004/07/29\n*\tChile  2005/03/31\n*\tIreland  2011/07/10...(Galway Film Fleadh)\n\n==Reception==\n''Winged Migration'' has an overall approval rating of 96% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/winged_migration/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>\nBy gross ticket sales, the film still holds seventh place in nature documentaries <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=naturedoc.htm|title=BoxOfficeMojo.org |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref> and eighteenth in documentary overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=documentary.htm |title=BoxOfficeMojo.org |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/259504/Winged-Migration/details |title=NY Times: Le Peuple Migrateur |accessdate=2008-11-23|work=NY Times}}</ref> It won [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Editing|\"Best Editing\"]] at the [[27th C\u00e9sar Awards]], where it was also nominated for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Music Written for a Film|\"Best Music\"]] and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Debut|\"Best Debut\"]].\n\n\u2022\tOscar 2003\nBest Documentary Feature (nominated) \u2013 Jacques Perrin\n\n\u2022\tEuropean Film Award 2002\nBest Documentary Feature (nominated) \u2013 Jacques Perrin\n\n\u2022\tCFCA Award 2004\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Laurent Charbonnier\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Luc Drion\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Laurent Fleutot\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Sylvie Carcedo\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Philippe Garguil\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Olli Barb\u00e9\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Dominique Gentil\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Thierry Machado\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 St\u00e9phane Martin\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Fabrice Moindrot\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Ernst Sasse\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Thierry Thomas\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Michel Terrasse\nBest Documentary (nominated)\n\n\u2022 Chicago Film Critics Circle Awards 2004\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Bernard Luti\nBest Cinematography (nominated) \u2013 Michel Benjamin\n\n\u2022\tC\u00e9sar 2002\nBest Editing (Meilleur montage) Marie-Jos\u00e8phe Yoyotte\nBest First Work (Meilleure premi\u00e8re oeuvre) (nominated) \u2013 Michel Debats\nBest First Work (Meilleure premi\u00e8re oeuvre) (nominated) \u2013 Jacques Cluzaud\n\n\u2022\tThe European Film Award 2002\nBest Documentary Award (Nominated) \u2013 Jacques Cluzaud\nBest Documentary Award (Nominated) \u2013 Michel Debats\n\n==Images==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"275px\" heights=\"200px\">\nImage:Winged Migration CGI.jpg|One of the CGI shots in ''Winged Migration'', in which an [[Arctic tern]] flies above southern [[Africa]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bill Lishman]] \u2013 He imprinted geese and taught them to follow him in a low-speed ultralight aircraft in a migration path from Canada to Virginia. \"The idea of the traveling birds we owe to him.\" Lishman appears in the \"Making of\" documentary on the DVD release.<ref name=\"makingof\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sonyclassics.com/wingedmigration/home.html Official site]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20041204093806/http://www.bacfilms.com/site/peuple/home.htm Official site]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0301727|title=Winged Migration}}\n* {{tcmdb title|444613|Winged Migration}}\n*''[http://ffilms.org/category/documentary/page/12/ Winged Migration]'' on FFilms.org\n* {{Mojo title|wingedmigration}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2004 films]]\n[[Category:2005 films]]\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:French documentary films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German documentary films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Italian documentary films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:Swiss documentary films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French independent films]]\n[[Category:Films about birds]]\n[[Category:Bird migration]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Greenland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mauritania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 film}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{prose|date=September 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = Winged Migration\n| image           = Winged Migration movie.jpg\n| image_size      = 225px\n| caption         = theatrical poster\n| director        = [[Jacques Perrin]],<br>[[Jacques Cluzaud]],<br>[[Michel Debats]]\n| writer          = [[Jean Dorst]]<br>Jacques Perrin\n| narrator        = Jacques Perrin<br>[[Philippe Labro]]\n| producer        = [[Christophe Barratier]],<br>Jacques Perrin\n| music           = [[Bruno Coulais]]\n| cinematographer =\n| editing         =\n| distributor     = [[BAC Films]]\n| released        = 12 December 2001 ''(<small>France</small>)''\n| runtime         = 98 minutes\n| country        = France<br>Italy<br>Germany<br>Switzerland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.unifrance.org/movie/15634/winged-migration|title=Winged Migration (2000)|website=en.unifrance.org}}</ref>\n| language        = English, French\n| budget          = $23.6 million\n| gross           = $52.8 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=2089|title=Le Peuple migrateur (Winged Migration) (2001)- JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Winged Migration''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Le Peuple Migrateur'''}}, also known as '''''The Travelling Birds''''' in some UK releases, or '''''The Travelling Birds: An Adventure in Flight''''' in Australia) is a 2001 [[documentary film]] directed by [[Jacques Cluzaud]], [[Michel Debats]] and [[Jacques Perrin]], who was also one of the writers and narrators, showcasing the immense journeys routinely made by birds during their [[Bird migration|migrations]].\n\nThe film is dedicated to the French [[ornithologist]] [[Jean Dorst]].\n\n==Production==\nThe movie was shot over the course of four years on all seven continents. It was shot using in-flight cameras, most of the footage is aerial, and the viewer appears to be flying alongside birds of successive species, especially [[Canada geese]]. They traverse every kind of weather and [[landscape]], covering vast distances in a flight for survival. The filmmakers exposed over 590 miles of film to create an 89-minute piece. In one case, two months of filming in one location was edited down to less than one minute in the final film.\n\nMuch of the aerial footage was taken of \"tame\" birds. The filmmakers raised birds of several species, including [[stork]]s and [[pelican]]s, from birth. The newborn birds [[imprinting (psychology)|imprinted]] on staff members, and were trained to fly along with the film crews. The birds were also exposed to the film equipment over the course of their lives to ensure that the birds would react the way the filmmakers want. Several of these species had never been imprinted before. Film was shot from [[ultralight aviation|ultralights]], [[paraglider]]s, and [[hot air balloon]]s, as well as [[truck]]s, [[motorcycle]]s, [[motorboat]]s, remote-controlled [[robot]]s, and a [[French Navy]] warship. Its producer says that \"Winged Migration\" is neither a documentary nor [[fiction]], but rather a \"natural tale\".<ref name=\"makingof\">\"Making of\" special feature on the DVD</ref>\n\nThe film states that no [[special effect]]s were used in the filming of the birds, although some entirely [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] segments that view Earth from outer space augment the real-life footage.\n\nThe film's soundtrack by [[Bruno Coulais]] was recorded by Bulgarian vocal group [[Bulgarka Junior Quartet]] in Bulgarian, as well as [[Nick Cave]] in English and [[Robert Wyatt]]. The vocal effects include sequences in which panting is superimposed on wingbeats to give the effect that the viewer is a bird.\n\n'''Release Date'''\n\n*\tFrance  2001/12/12                    \n*\tBelgium  2001/12/12\n*\tSwitzerland  2001/12/13...(German speaking region)\n*\tGreece  2001/12/14\n*\tSouth Korea  2002/03/29\n*\tGermany  2002/04/04\n*\tNetherlands  2002/04/18\n*\tHong Kong  2002/06/20\n*\tRussia  2002/06/21...(Moscow Film Festival)\n*\tCzech Republic  2002/07/8...(Karlovy Vary Film Festival)\n*\tCzech Republic  2002/07/18\n*\tCanada  2002/09/08...(Toronto Film Festival)\n*\tTurkey  2002/09/13\n*\tIsrael  2002/09/19\n*\tHungary  2002/09/19\n*\tSpain  2002/09/27\n*\tItaly  2002/11/15\n*\tLithuania  2002/12/27\n*\tPoland  2003/04/04\n*\tJapan  2003/04/05...(Tokyo)\n*\tUSA  2003/04/5...(Philadelphia International Film Festival)\n*\tSlovenia  2003/04/17\n*\tUSA  2003/04/18...(Limited)\n*\tNorway  2003/05/02...(Kristiansand International Children's Film Festival)\n*\tCanada  2003/05/30\n*\tAustralia  2003/06/19\n*\tNorway  2003/06/20\n*\tNew Zealand  2003/07/13...(Auckland International Film Festival)\n*\tMexico  2003/07/25\n*\tDenmark  2003/08/15...(Copenhagen International Film Festival)\n*\tFinland  2003/09/05\n*\tUK  2003/09/05\n*\tDenmark  2003/09/12\n*\tSweden  2003/ 11/07\n*\tIceland  2004/01/23...(French Film Festival)\n*\tArgentina  2004/07/29\n*\tChile  2005/03/31\n*\tIreland  2011/07/10...(Galway Film Fleadh)\n\n==Reception==\n''Winged Migration'' has an overall approval rating of 96% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/winged_migration/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>\nBy gross ticket sales, the film still holds seventh place in nature documentaries <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=naturedoc.htm|title=BoxOfficeMojo.org |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref> and eighteenth in documentary overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=documentary.htm |title=BoxOfficeMojo.org |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/259504/Winged-Migration/details |title=NY Times: Le Peuple Migrateur |accessdate=2008-11-23|work=NY Times}}</ref> It won [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Editing|\"Best Editing\"]] at the [[27th C\u00e9sar Awards]], where it was also nominated for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Music Written for a Film|\"Best Music\"]] and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Debut|\"Best Debut\"]].\n\n\u2022\tOscar 2003\nBest Documentary Feature (nominated) -Jacques Perrin\n\n\u2022\tEuropean Film Award 2002\nBest Documentary Feature (nominated) -Jacques Perrin\n\n\u2022\tCFCA Award 2004\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Laurent Charbonnier\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Luc Drion\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Laurent Fleutot\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Sylvie Carcedo\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Philippe Garguil\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Olli Barb\u00e9\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Dominique Gentil\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Thierry Machado\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -St\u00e9phane Martin\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Fabrice Moindrot\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Ernst Sasse\nBest Cinematography (nominated) -Thierry Thomas\nBest Cinematography (nominated) - Michel Terrasse\nBest Documentary (nominated)\n\n\u2022\tChicago Film Critics Circle Awards 2004\nBest Cinematography (nominated) - Bernard Luti\nBest Cinematography (nominated) - Michel Benjamin\n\n\u2022\tC\u00e9sar 2002\nBest Editing (Meilleur montage) Marie-Jos\u00e8phe Yoyotte\nBest First Work (Meilleure premi\u00e8re oeuvre) (nominated) - Michel Debats\nBest First Work (Meilleure premi\u00e8re oeuvre) (nominated) - Jacques Cluzaud\n\n\u2022\tThe European Film Award 2002\nBest Documentary Award (Nominated) - Jacques Cluzaud\nBest Documentary Award (Nominated) - Michel Debats\n\n==Images==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"275px\" heights=\"200px\">\nImage:Winged Migration CGI.jpg|One of the CGI shots in ''Winged Migration'', in which an [[Arctic tern]] flies above southern [[Africa]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bill Lishman]] - He imprinted geese and taught them to follow him in a low-speed ultralight aircraft in a migration path from Canada to Virginia. \"The idea of the traveling birds we owe to him.\" Lishman appears in the \"Making of\" documentary on the DVD release.<ref name=\"makingof\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sonyclassics.com/wingedmigration/home.html Official site]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20041204093806/http://www.bacfilms.com/site/peuple/home.htm Official site]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0301727|title=Winged Migration}}\n* {{tcmdb title|444613|Winged Migration}}\n*''[http://ffilms.org/category/documentary/page/12/ Winged Migration]'' on FFilms.org\n* {{Mojo title|wingedmigration}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2004 films]]\n[[Category:2005 films]]\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:French documentary films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German documentary films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Italian documentary films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:Swiss documentary films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French independent films]]\n[[Category:Films about birds]]\n[[Category:Bird migration]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Greenland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mauritania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winged_Migration"}
{"title_page": "Edge of the City", "text_new": "{{short description|1957 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Edge of the City\n| image          = Edge of the City 1957 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster designed by [[Saul Bass]]\n| director       = [[Martin Ritt]]\n| producer       = Jim Di Gangi<br>[[David Susskind]]\n| screenplay     = [[Robert Alan Aurthur]]\n| story          = Robert Alan Aurthur\n| starring       = [[John Cassavetes]]<br>[[Sidney Poitier]]<br>[[Jack Warden]]\n| music          = [[Leonard Rosenman]]\n| cinematography = [[Joseph C. Brun|Joseph Brun]]\n| editing        = Sidney Meyers\n| studio         = David Susskind Productions<br/>Jonathan Productions\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{film date|1957|1|29}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $493,000<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n| gross          = $760,000<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n}}\n'''''Edge of the City''''' is a 1957 American [[film-noir]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Martin Ritt]], starring [[John Cassavetes]] and [[Sidney Poitier]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/90305/Edge-of-the-City/overview |title=New York Times: Easy Living |accessdate=July 19, 2008|work=The New York Times | first=Bosley | last=Crowther}}</ref> It was Ritt's [[List of directorial debuts|debut film]] as a director. [[Robert Alan Aurthur]]'s screenplay was expanded from his original script, staged as the final episode of ''[[Philco Television Playhouse]]'', ''A Man Is Ten Feet Tall'' (1955), also featuring Poitier.\n\nThe film was considered unusual for its time because of its portrayal of an interracial friendship, and was praised by representatives of the [[NAACP]], [[Urban League]], [[American Jewish Committee]] and Interfaith Council because of its portrayal of racial brotherhood.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Dee Poitier and Cassavetes in Edge of the City.jpg|thumb|left|260px|[[Ruby Dee]], [[Sidney Poitier]] and [[John Cassavetes]]]]\nYoung drifter Axel Nordmann ([[John Cassavetes]]) arrives at the waterfront on the west side of Manhattan, seeking employment as a [[longshoreman]], and giving his name as \"Axel North.\" He goes to work in a gang of [[stevedore]]s headed by Charlie Malick ([[Jack Warden]]) a vicious bully, and is befriended by Tommy Tyler ([[Sidney Poitier]]), who also supervises a stevedore gang and has an engaging, charming sense of humor. Malick resents blacks in positions of authority, and is antagonized when Axel goes to work for Tommy.\n\nAxel moves into Tommy's neighborhood and becomes friends with Tommy's wife Lucy ([[Ruby Dee]]) and develops a romantic relationship with her friend Ellen Wilson ([[Kathleen Maguire]]). Tommy serves as a mentor to Axel, urging him to stand up to Malick, and that if he does he will be \"ten feet tall.\" It is apparent from the start that Axel is hiding something, and it emerges that he is a deserter from the United States Army. Malick is aware of that, and is extorting money from him.\n\nMalick frequently tries to provoke Tommy and Axel into fights, with Tommy coming to Axel's aid. Malick finally provokes Tommy into a fight, with both men using their baling hooks. At one point, Tommy disarms Malick and implores him to stop, but Malick seizes the hook and kills him. The police investigation is stymied by lack of cooperation from the longshoremen, including Axel. But after meeting with the distraught Lucy, who accuses him of never being Tommy's friend as he knows who killed Tommy but has not told the police, Axel finally decides to cooperate. He goes to Malick to tell him that. They get into a fight, and in the end, though beaten, Axel strangles Malick unconscious and drags him away to face justice.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Cassavetes]] as Axel Nordmann\n* [[Sidney Poitier]] as Tommy Tyler\n* [[Jack Warden]] as Charlie Malick\n* [[Kathleen Maguire]] as Ellen Wilson\n* [[Ruby Dee]] as Lucy Tyler\n* [[Val Avery]] as Brother\n* [[Robert F. Simon]] as George Nordmann (as Robert Simon)\n* [[Ruth White (actress)|Ruth White]] as Katherine Nordmann\n* William A. Lee as Davis\n* [[John Kellogg (actor)|John Kellogg]] as Detective\n* [[David Clarke (actor)|David Clarke]] as Wallace (as David Clark)\n* [[Estelle Hemsley]] as Mrs. Price\n* [[Perry Greene]] as son of Tommy and Lucy Tyler\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Edge of the city title.jpg|thumb|260px|Title Card]]\n[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] budgeted only $500,000 for the film because its racial content was believed to limit its marketability in the south. Poitier was paid $15,000 for the role and received his first co-star billing, though it was considered small by movie industry standards. Ritt, who had been blacklisted, was paid only $10,000. The film was shot on location at a railroad yard in Manhattan and on St. Nicholas Terrace in New York's [[Harlem]].<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nPoitier was the only actor remaining from the TV version, in which the Jack Warden character was played by [[Martin Balsam]] and the Cassavetes character was played by [[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]]. The TV version was directed by [[Robert Mulligan]]. The script was completely rewritten for the film.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nThe opening title sequence and theatrical release poster were designed by [[Saul Bass]]. The score was composed, conducted and orchestrated by [[Leonard Rosenman]].<ref>{{cite journal\n| title      = The Cobweb/Edge of the City\n| others    = Leonard Rosenman\n| date      = 2003\n| url       = \n| last      = Bond\n| first     = Jeff\n| author2 = Lukas Kendall\n| pages     =23\n| type    = CD insert notes\n| journal = [[Film Score Monthly]]\n| volume=6 |issue=14\n| location  = Culver City, California, U.S.A.\n| language  = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe film earned positive reviews,<ref name='Jackson'>{{cite book | last = Jackson | first = Carlton | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Picking Up the Tab: The Life and Movies of Martin Ritt | publisher = Popular Press | year = 1994 | location = | pages = 40\u201341 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-87972-672-0 }}</ref> with critics praising the unusual multiracial relationship between the Poitier and Cassavetes characters. Up till then, whites were ordinarily shown in positions of authority. ''[[Time magazine]]'' noted that the Poitier character \"is not only the white man's boss, but is his best friend, and is at all times his superior, possessing greater intelligence, courage, understanding, warmth and general adaptability.\" ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said the film was \"a milestone in the history of screen in its presentation of an American Negro.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'/> The London ''[[Sunday Times]]'' said the film was \"splendidly directed\" by Ritt.<ref name='Jackson'/>\n\nPoitier's performance received glowing reviews, and the film, along with ''[[Blackboard Jungle]]'', helped establish him as \"one of Hollywood's few established representatives for black Americans.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'>{{cite book | last = Goudsouzian | first = Aram | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Sidney Poitier: Man, Actor, Icon | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press | year = 2003 | location = | pages = [https://archive.org/details/sidneypoitierman00goud/page/117 117]\u2013122 | url = https://archive.org/details/sidneypoitierman00goud| url-access = registration | quote = Edge of the city poitier. | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8078-2843-4 }}</ref>\n\nCassavetes also won acclaim for his portrayal, which resembled that of [[Marlon Brando]] in ''[[On the Waterfront]]'' (1954).<ref name='Man-Actor'/> The Cassavetes character was notable for its hint of homosexuality, which was uncommon for the time. The [[Hays Office|Motion Picture Production Code Administration]] allowed the innuendo, but recommended \"extremely careful handling to avoid planting the suspicion that he may be homosexual.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' film critic [[Bosley Crowther]] called ''Edge of the City'' an \"ambitious little film\" and \"at times close to some sort of fair articulation of the complexities of racial brotherhood.\" In one scene in which they have lunch at the river, \"the attitudes of the young fellows\u2014the white man with terrors in his mind and the Negro with cordial disposition to be as generous with his friendship as with food\u2014are swiftly and trenchantly established in this little scene and the pattern of deep devotion in their subsequent comradeship is prepared.\" At those times, Crowther said, ''Edge of the City'' was a \"sharp and searching film.\" But more often, he said, Aurthur and Ritt \"have let their drama fall too patly into the pattern and the lingo of an imitative television show\u2014a television show imitating the film ''On the Waterfront.''\"<ref name='Crowther'>{{cite news | first=Bosley | last=Crowther | coauthors= |authorlink= Bosley Crowther | title=Screen: On Brotherhood | date=January 30, 1957 | publisher= | url =https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?_r=1&res=9D04E6DF143EE23BBC4850DFB766838C649EDE | work =The New York Times | pages = | accessdate = December 8, 2009 | language = }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nMGM delayed release of the film because it was uneasy with the racial theme. However, the film was released after receiving rave reviews from preview audiences.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nThe film was not a commercial success. It did not play in the [[Southern United States]], and was refused by many theater managers because of its depiction of an interracial relationship.<ref name='Jackson'/> According to MGM records the film earned rentals of $360,000 in the US and Canada and $400,000 elsewhere resulting in a loss of $125,000.<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n\n===Legacy===\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' critic Dennis Lim, writing in 2009, described ''Edge of the City'' and ''[[Something of Value]]'' (1957) as \"variations on an early Poitier specialty, the black-white buddy movie, the most vivid example of which is perhaps [[Stanley Kramer]]'s ''[[The Defiant Ones (film)|The Defiant Ones]]'' (1958),\" in which Poitier and [[Tony Curtis]] played escaped convicts shackled to each other.<ref name='LATimes'>{{cite news | first=Dennis | last=Lim | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Sidney Poitier's roles as a historical marker | date=January 25, 2009 | publisher= | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/25/entertainment/ca-2ndlook25 | work =Los Angeles Times | pages = | accessdate = December 5, 2009 | language = }}</ref>\n\nOne history of African-Americans in film, originally published by author [[Donald Bogle]] in 1973, was critical of Poitier's portrayal, referring to him as portraying a \"colorless black\" with \"little ethnic juice in his blood.\" His death scene is described as being in the tradition of \"the dying slave content that he has served the massa.\" Bogle writes that Poitier's \"loyalty to the white Cassavetes destroys him just as much as the old slave's steadfastness kept him in shackles.\"<ref name='Bogle'>{{cite book | last = Bogle| first = Donald | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Toms, Coons, Mulattoes, Mammies & Bucks: An Interpretive History of Blacks in American Films | publisher = Continuum (paperback ed.) | date = December 2001 | location = | pages = [https://archive.org/details/tomscoonsmulatto0004bogl/page/181 181] | url = https://archive.org/details/tomscoonsmulatto0004bogl | url-access = registration| quote = sidney poitier edge of the city.| doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8264-1267-6 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0050347|title=Edge of the City}}\n* {{Allmovie title|90305|title=Edge of the City}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|id=2999|title=Edge of the City}}\n\n{{Martin Ritt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edge Of The City}}\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:African-American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Film noir]]\n[[Category:Films about racism]]\n[[Category:Films based on television plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Ritt]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Leonard Rosenman]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:1957 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1957 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Edge of the City\n| image          = Edge of the City 1957 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster designed by [[Saul Bass]]\n| director       = [[Martin Ritt]]\n| producer       = Jim Di Gangi<br>[[David Susskind]]\n| screenplay     = [[Robert Alan Aurthur]]\n| story          = Robert Alan Aurthur\n| starring       = [[John Cassavetes]]<br>[[Sidney Poitier]]<br>[[Jack Warden]]\n| music          = [[Leonard Rosenman]]\n| cinematography = [[Joseph C. Brun|Joseph Brun]]\n| editing        = Sidney Meyers\n| studio         = David Susskind Productions<br/>Jonathan Productions\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{film date|1957|1|29}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $493,000<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n| gross          = $760,000<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n}}\n'''''Edge of the City''''' is a 1957 American [[film-noir]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Martin Ritt]], starring [[John Cassavetes]] and [[Sidney Poitier]].<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/90305/Edge-of-the-City/overview |title=New York Times: Easy Living |accessdate=July 19, 2008|work=The New York Times | first=Bosley | last=Crowther}}</ref> It was Ritt's [[List of directorial debuts|debut film]] as a director. [[Robert Alan Aurthur]]'s screenplay was expanded from his original script, staged as the final episode of ''[[Philco Television Playhouse]]'', ''A Man Is Ten Feet Tall'' (1955), also featuring Poitier.\n\nThe film was considered unusual for its time because of its portrayal of an interracial friendship, and was praised by representatives of the [[NAACP]], [[Urban League]], [[American Jewish Committee]] and Interfaith Council because of its portrayal of racial brotherhood.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Dee Poitier and Cassavetes in Edge of the City.jpg|thumb|left|260px|[[Ruby Dee]], [[Sidney Poitier]] and [[John Cassavetes]]]]\nYoung drifter Axel Nordmann ([[John Cassavetes]]) arrives at the waterfront on the west side of Manhattan, seeking employment as a [[longshoreman]], and giving his name as \"Axel North.\" He goes to work in a gang of [[stevedore]]s headed by Charlie Malick ([[Jack Warden]]) a vicious bully, and is befriended by Tommy Tyler ([[Sidney Poitier]]), who also supervises a stevedore gang and has an engaging, charming sense of humor. Malick resents blacks in positions of authority, and is antagonized when Axel goes to work for Tommy.\n\nAxel moves into Tommy's neighborhood and becomes friends with Tommy's wife Lucy ([[Ruby Dee]]) and develops a romantic relationship with her friend Ellen Wilson ([[Kathleen Maguire]]). Tommy serves as a mentor to Axel, urging him to stand up to Malick, and that if he does he will be \"ten feet tall.\" It is apparent from the start that Axel is hiding something, and it emerges that he is a deserter from the United States Army. Malick is aware of that, and is extorting money from him.\n\nMalick frequently tries to provoke Tommy and Axel into fights, with Tommy coming to Axel's aid. Malick finally provokes Tommy into a fight, with both men using their baling hooks. At one point, Tommy disarms Malick and implores him to stop, but Malick seizes the hook and kills him. The police investigation is stymied by lack of cooperation from the longshoremen, including Axel. But after meeting with the distraught Lucy, who accuses him of never being Tommy's friend as he knows who killed Tommy but has not told the police, Axel finally decides to cooperate. He goes to Malick to tell him that. They get into a fight, and in the end, though beaten, Axel strangles Malick unconscious and drags him away to face justice.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Cassavetes]] as Axel Nordmann\n* [[Sidney Poitier]] as Tommy Tyler\n* [[Jack Warden]] as Charlie Malick\n* [[Kathleen Maguire]] as Ellen Wilson\n* [[Ruby Dee]] as Lucy Tyler\n* [[Val Avery]] as Brother\n* [[Robert F. Simon]] as George Nordmann (as Robert Simon)\n* [[Ruth White (actress)|Ruth White]] as Katherine Nordmann\n* William A. Lee as Davis\n* [[John Kellogg (actor)|John Kellogg]] as Detective\n* [[David Clarke (actor)|David Clarke]] as Wallace (as David Clark)\n* [[Estelle Hemsley]] as Mrs. Price\n* [[Perry Greene]] as son of Tommy and Lucy Tyler\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Edge of the city title.jpg|thumb|260px|Title Card]]\n[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] budgeted only $500,000 for the film because its racial content was believed to limit its marketability in the south. Poitier was paid $15,000 for the role and received his first co-star billing, though it was considered small by movie industry standards. Ritt, who had been blacklisted, was paid only $10,000. The film was shot on location at a railroad yard in Manhattan and on St. Nicholas Terrace in New York's [[Harlem]].<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nPoitier was the only actor remaining from the TV version, in which the Jack Warden character was played by [[Martin Balsam]] and the Cassavetes character was played by [[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]]. The TV version was directed by [[Robert Mulligan]]. The script was completely rewritten for the film.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nThe opening title sequence and theatrical release poster were designed by [[Saul Bass]]. The score was composed, conducted and orchestrated by [[Leonard Rosenman]].<ref>{{cite journal\n| title      = The Cobweb/Edge of the City\n| others    = Leonard Rosenman\n| date      = 2003\n| url       = \n| last      = Bond\n| first     = Jeff\n| author2 = Lukas Kendall\n| pages     =23\n| type    = CD insert notes\n| journal = [[Film Score Monthly]]\n| volume=6 |issue=14\n| location  = Culver City, California, U.S.A.\n| language  = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe film earned positive reviews,<ref name='Jackson'>{{cite book | last = Jackson | first = Carlton | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Picking Up the Tab: The Life and Movies of Martin Ritt | publisher = Popular Press | year = 1994 | location = | pages = 40\u201341 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-87972-672-0 }}</ref> with critics praising the unusual multiracial relationship between the Poitier and Cassavetes characters. Up till then, whites were ordinarily shown in positions of authority. ''[[Time magazine]]'' noted that the Poitier character \"is not only the white man's boss, but is his best friend, and is at all times his superior, possessing greater intelligence, courage, understanding, warmth and general adaptability.\" ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said the film was \"a milestone in the history of screen in its presentation of an American Negro.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'/> The London ''[[Sunday Times]]'' said the film was \"splendidly directed\" by Ritt.<ref name='Jackson'/>\n\nPoitier's performance received glowing reviews, and the film, along with ''[[Blackboard Jungle]]'', helped establish him as \"one of Hollywood's few established representatives for black Americans.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'>{{cite book | last = Goudsouzian | first = Aram | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Sidney Poitier: Man, Actor, Icon | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press | year = 2003 | location = | pages = [https://archive.org/details/sidneypoitierman00goud/page/117 117]\u2013122 | url = https://archive.org/details/sidneypoitierman00goud| url-access = registration | quote = Edge of the city poitier. | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8078-2843-4 }}</ref>\n\nCassavetes also won acclaim for his portrayal, which resembled that of [[Marlon Brando]] in ''[[On the Waterfront]]'' (1954).<ref name='Man-Actor'/> The Cassavetes character was notable for its hint of homosexuality, which was uncommon for the time. The [[Hays Office|Motion Picture Production Code Administration]] allowed the innuendo, but recommended \"extremely careful handling to avoid planting the suspicion that he may be homosexual.\"<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' film critic [[Bosley Crowther]] called ''Edge of the City'' an \"ambitious little film\" and \"at times close to some sort of fair articulation of the complexities of racial brotherhood.\" In one scene in which they have lunch at the river, \"the attitudes of the young fellows\u2014the white man with terrors in his mind and the Negro with cordial disposition to be as generous with his friendship as with food\u2014are swiftly and trenchantly established in this little scene and the pattern of deep devotion in their subsequent comradeship is prepared.\" At those times, Crowther said, ''Edge of the City'' was a \"sharp and searching film.\" But more often, he said, Aurthur and Ritt \"have let their drama fall too patly into the pattern and the lingo of an imitative television show\u2014a television show imitating the film ''On the Waterfront.''\"<ref name='Crowther'>{{cite news | first=Bosley | last=Crowther | coauthors= |authorlink= Bosley Crowther | title=Screen: On Brotherhood | date=January 30, 1957 | publisher= | url =https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?_r=1&res=9D04E6DF143EE23BBC4850DFB766838C649EDE | work =The New York Times | pages = | accessdate = December 8, 2009 | language = }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nMGM delayed release of the film because it was uneasy with the racial theme. However, the film was released after receiving rave reviews from preview audiences.<ref name='Man-Actor'/>\n\nThe film was not a commercial success. It did not play in the [[Southern United States]], and was refused by many theater managers because of its depiction of an interracial relationship.<ref name='Jackson'/> According to MGM records the film earned rentals of $360,000 in the US and Canada and $400,000 elsewhere resulting in a loss of $125,000.<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n\n===Legacy===\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' critic Dennis Lim, writing in 2009, described ''Edge of the City'' and ''[[Something of Value]]'' (1957) as \"variations on an early Poitier specialty, the black-white buddy movie, the most vivid example of which is perhaps [[Stanley Kramer]]'s ''[[The Defiant Ones (film)|The Defiant Ones]]'' (1958),\" in which Poitier and [[Tony Curtis]] played escaped convicts shackled to each other.<ref name='LATimes'>{{cite news | first=Dennis | last=Lim | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Sidney Poitier's roles as a historical marker | date=January 25, 2009 | publisher= | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/25/entertainment/ca-2ndlook25 | work =Los Angeles Times | pages = | accessdate = December 5, 2009 | language = }}</ref>\n\nOne history of African-Americans in film, originally published by author [[Donald Bogle]] in 1973, was critical of Poitier's portrayal, referring to him as portraying a \"colorless black\" with \"little ethnic juice in his blood.\" His death scene is described as being in the tradition of \"the dying slave content that he has served the massa.\" Bogle writes that Poitier's \"loyalty to the white Cassavetes destroys him just as much as the old slave's steadfastness kept him in shackles.\"<ref name='Bogle'>{{cite book | last = Bogle| first = Donald | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Toms, Coons, Mulattoes, Mammies & Bucks: An Interpretive History of Blacks in American Films | publisher = Continuum (paperback ed.) | date = December 2001 | location = | pages = [https://archive.org/details/tomscoonsmulatto0004bogl/page/181 181] | url = https://archive.org/details/tomscoonsmulatto0004bogl | url-access = registration| quote = sidney poitier edge of the city.| doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8264-1267-6 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0050347|title=Edge of the City}}\n* {{Allmovie title|90305|title=Edge of the City}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|id=2999|title=Edge of the City}}\n\n{{Martin Ritt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edge Of The City}}\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:African-American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Film noir]]\n[[Category:Films about racism]]\n[[Category:Films based on television plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Ritt]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Leonard Rosenman]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:1957 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_of_the_City"}
{"title_page": "Singaravelan", "text_new": "{{Short description|1992 film by R. V. Udayakumar}}\n{{long plot|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Singaravelan\n| image          = Singaravelan.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[R. V. Udayakumar]]\n| producer       = R. D. Bhaskar\n| writer         = [[Panchu Arunachalam]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kamal Haasan]]\n* [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = Abdul Rehman\n| editing        = [[B. Lenin]]<br />[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor    = Pavalar Creations\n| studio         = \n| released       = {{film date|1992|4|13|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sify.com/movies/top-7-memorable-tamil-new-year-film-releases-news-tamil-reoqhSegehfag.html |title=Top 7 memorable Tamil New Year film releases |last=Sambandan |first=Aparanjeetha |date=9 August 2017 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-date=20 December 2019 |access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Singaravelan''''' is a 1992 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[R. V. Udayakumar]], starring [[Kamal Haasan]] in the lead role. The film also stars [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]], [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]], [[Mano (singer)|Mano]], [[Jaishankar]], [[Goundamani]], [[Vadivelu]], [[Charle]] and [[Nizhalgal Ravi]], among others. The film was produced by R. D. Bhaskar under the production company Pavalar Creations. The film's script was written by Panchu Arunachalam. The film's soundtrack was composed by Ilaiyaraaja. Abdul Rahman handled cinematography, while B. Lenin and V. T. Vijayan handled editing respectively. The film was released on 13 April 1992 and became successful at the box office. In 2017, it was dubbed into [[Hindi]] as ''Rakhwala Mohabbat Ka''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=WuMhUwQyDJY |title=Rakhwala Mohabbat Ka (2017) full movie |publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSingaravelan \"Velan\" lives with his widowed mother Parvathy in village. Velan's father died heartbroken that his marriage with Velan's mother was not accepted by her sister-in-law and they had broken all links. Further, they believe that it was Parvathy's curse that killed her brother and sister-in-law in a car accident and they get a promise from the guardian, that their daughter should not be married to Parvathy's son. Velan's mother reveals that it is Velan's duty to marry her brother's daughter Sumathi to bring the separated family back together. Armed with only a picture of the girl when she was four, he leaves for Madras to fulfill his mother's wishes.\n\nVelan arrives at his friend Mano's house to implement his mission. Mano lives with three more roommates: Charlie, Vadivelu and Goundamani. Velan explains his mission and all of them offer to help him.\n\nThe next day, they visit a computer centre where the clerk generates an image of the teenage Sumathi. Velan  and his friends visit the beach to think for a plan but luckily they find a woman playing tennis to be Sumathi, the girl they search for. When Sumathi goes to fetch the ball from the sea, and Velan goes to help her. But he accidentally drowns her, but manage to pull an unconscious Sumathi out of the water. When she becomes conscious, she blames him for drowning her and didn't need any help as she was a trained long distance swimmer. Despite his friends' advice to drop the love for Sumathi due to her arrogant nature, Velan proceeds with next step of his mission as a challenge.\n\nLater, Velan and his friends follow Sumathi to a 5-star restaurant. On the stage in the dining hall, a flautist is performing. Once the performance ends, Sumathi gets up and kisses the old flautist's hand. Velan too offers his hand to be kissed, wherein he is asked whether he knows anything about music. To prove her wrong, Velan dresses up in a fancy leather suit, adorned with various musical instruments, singing \"Pudhu Cheri Katcheri\". But Sumathi insults the performance. Velan on his part teases with harmless intention, which also earns Sumathi's dislike.\n\nVelan meanwhile attempts to attract Thaiamma, the guardian of Sumathi by visiting her house daily. Thaiamma is attracted by Velan's entertaining nature. Velan lies by saying his mother's name as Mahalakshmi. Though Thaiamma certifies Velan as a good chap, Sumathi continues to hate him. Sumathi's uncle Natesan, who is a retired IG of police visits Velan to warn him to stop teasing his niece. There he comes to know about his father is an industrialist Kaliannan Gounder who has disowned him due to his passion for music. Unfortunately, he manages to meet the Industrialist to verify the Velan's family background and finds everything true via the mouth of industrialist. But Velan and his friends have already visited the industrialist and convinced him to lie to the general to help them out.\n\nThen Velan managed to attract Sumathi gradually through a series of events, which makes Sumathi realize her femininity. Their love becomes strong when Sumathi hears that Velan is very serious at hospital as he was attacked by some men hired by her uncle as he lied that he was the son of an industrialist. She finds Velan dressed up with full bandages on his body (a drama by Velan who counterattacked the men sent by the uncle and instructs them to convey that the men attacked Velan, to Sumathi as part of the love mission). Velan's mother is informed about her son's hospitalization by a person from Madras and immediately rushes to see her son. There she understands that facts are not true and feels easy. Velan and Sumathi's love grows steadily and they decide to get engaged.\n\nOn the day of engagement, through 'Sincere' Sivamani, the manager at Sumathi's factory, Sumathi come to know that Velan is, in fact, the son of Paravathy, cancels the engagement and refuses to speak to him. In the meantime, the general finds that Sivamani is a crook who has been using Sumathi's premises to print [[Counterfeit money|counterfeit bills]]. Sivamani kills the General and frames Velan. Velan escapes the police and goes on the run. His friends, mother and the industrialist are arrested as accomplices. Sivamani decides to kill Velan and marry Sumathi for her wealth and tricks Thaiamma to accept his proposal to marry Sumathi. He also uses one of his men to bring Velan in and to kill him, but Velan beats up all the bad guys and calls the police.\n\nTogether with the police, Sivamani's ally, his mother and friends he goes to the wedding hall and proves that Sivamani was the real killer and stops the wedding and gets him arrested. Sumathi realizes the true love of Velan and requests his mother to marry them. Velan and Sumathi then marry. The story ends with the happiness of all members re-united at Velan's house.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] as Singaravelan a.k.a. Velan\n* [[Kushboo Sundar|Khushboo]] as Sumathi\n* [[Sumithra (actress)|Sumithra]] as Parvathi\n* [[Jaishankar]] as Retired IG Natesan\n* [[Mano (singer)|Mano]] as Mano\n* [[Goundamani]] as Drums Mani\n* [[Vadivelu]] as \"Michael Jackson Thangachi\" Subha\n* [[Charle]] as Flute Ramasamy\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Thaiyamma<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/when-the-camera-rolled-she-lived-the-character/article7751052.ece |title=When the camera rolled, she lived the character' |last=Yamunan |first=Sruthisagar |date=12 October 2015 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as \"Sincere\" Sivamani\n* [[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramaswamy]] as Kaliannan Kounder\n* [[Ajay Rathnam]] as thug\n* [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] as Velan's father (cameo)<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2017/jun/16/daddy-dearest-1617504.html</ref>\n* [[Malaysia Vasudevan]] as Sumathi's father (cameo)\n* [[Venniradai Moorthy]] as Doctor\n* Peelisivam as inspector\n* [[Swaminathan]] as one of the constables (uncredited)\n* S. R. Veeraraghavan as Commissioner\n* [[Shanmuga Sundaram]] (cameo)\n* [[Sangili Murugan]] (cameo)\n* [[Vinu Chakravarthy]] (cameo)\n* [[C R Saraswathi]] as Sumathi's mother (cameo)\n* [[Oru Viral Krishna Rao]] (as marriage broker)\n{{colend}}\n\n== Reception ==\n''[[The Indian Express]]'' wrote, \"The script betrays an episodic approach, but [Kamal Haasan] carries himself with poise in a role that does not make much demands on him, except for some spirited dancing and singing, and the pack of comedians made up of Goundamani, Charlie, Vadivelu and Manorama, despite some ridiculous attempts at humour off and on, make a generally good impression.\"<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920417&printsec=frontpage&hl=en</ref> ''Singaravelan'' did well at the box office.  It was the first movie of any kind to be released in more than two theatres in a single complex in Chennai.<ref>http://www.mayyam.com/talk/archive/index.php/t-5142.html?s=a72a80636254df9525a498e59afb530b</ref> The scene where Singaravelan and his friends visits a computer centre to digitally visualise what Sumathi looks like in present-day gained popularity for its comedy.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/What-did-Kamal-Haasan-teach-us/article16439215.ece</ref><ref>http://www.sify.com/movies/computer-poche-the-demise-of-kollywood-s-funny-futuristic-side-news-kollywood-nlgtBRacjchsi.html</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Singaravelan\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1992\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 30:18\n| label      = [[Pyramid Saimira|Pyramid]]\n| language   = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = Maappillai Vandhaachu\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Innisai Mazhai]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{External media\n | audio1     = {{YouTube|IQOHaS9vLAs| Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n}}\nThe soundtrack was composed by [[Ilaiyaraaja]],<ref>http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0000160</ref> \"Pottu Vaitha Kathal Thittam\" song the high pitch parts were sung by both Kamal and Mano.<ref>https://www.tamil2lyrics.com/lyrics/pottu-vaitha-kathal-thitam-song-lyrics/</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Track list\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 30:18\n| title1 = Pottu Vaitha Kathal Thittam\n| lyrics1 = [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]]\n| extra1 = [[Kamal Haasan]] and [[Mano (singer)|Mano]]\n| length1 = 5:00\n| title2 = Innum Ennai Enna\n| lyrics2 = [[R. V. Udayakumar]]\n| extra2 = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], [[S. Janaki]]\n| length2 = 4:03\n| title3 = O Ranga Sriranga\n| extra3 = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| lyrics3 = Vaali\n| length3 = 5:11\n| title4 = Pudhu Cheri Katcheri\n| lyrics4 = Vaali\n| extra4 = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| length4 = 6:22\n| title5 = Sonnapadi Kelu\n| lyrics5 = Vaali\n| extra5 = Kamal Haasan\n| length5 = 5:13\n| title6 = Thoodhu Selvadharadi\n| lyrics6 = Ponnadiyan\n| extra6 = S. Janaki\n| length6 = 2:26\n| title7 = Pudhu Cheri Katcheri\n| note7 = Sad\n| lyrics7 = Vaali\n| extra7 = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| length7 = 2:03\n| all_writing = 30:38\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0318696}}\n\n{{R. V. Udayakumar}}\n\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Ilaiyaraaja]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Panchu Arunachalam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1992 film by R. V. Udayakumar}}\n{{long plot|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Singaravelan\n| image          = Singaravelan.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[R. V. Udayakumar]]\n| producer       = R. D. Bhaskar\n| writer         = [[Panchu Arunachalam]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kamal Haasan]]\n* [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cinematography = Abdul Rehman\n| editing        = [[B. Lenin]]<br />[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor    = Pavalar Creations\n| studio         = \n| released       = {{film date|1992|4|13|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sify.com/movies/top-7-memorable-tamil-new-year-film-releases-news-tamil-reoqhSegehfag.html |title=Top 7 memorable Tamil New Year film releases |last=Sambandan |first=Aparanjeetha |date=9 August 2017 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-date=20 December 2019 |access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Singaravelan''''' is a 1992 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[R. V. Udayakumar]], starring [[Kamal Haasan]] in the lead role. The film also stars [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]], [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]], [[Mano (singer)|Mano]], [[Jaishankar]], [[Goundamani]], [[Vadivelu]], [[Charle]] and [[Nizhalgal Ravi]], among others. The film was produced by R. D. Bhaskar under the production company Pavalar Creations. The film's script was written by Panchu Arunachalam. The film's soundtrack was composed by Ilaiyaraaja. Abdul Rahman handled cinematography, while B. Lenin and V. T. Vijayan handled editing respectively. The film was released on 13 April 1992 and became successful at the box office. In 2017, it was dubbed into [[Hindi]] as ''Rakhwala Mohabbat Ka''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=WuMhUwQyDJY |title=Rakhwala Mohabbat Ka (2017) full movie |publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSingaravelan \"Velan\" lives with his widowed mother Parvathy in village. Velan's father died heartbroken that his marriage with Velan's mother was not accepted by her sister-in-law and they had broken all links. Further, they believe that it was Parvathy's curse that killed her brother and sister-in-law in a car accident and they get a promise from the guardian, that their daughter should not be married to Parvathy's son. Velan's mother reveals that it is Velan's duty to get married to her brother's daughter Sumathi to bring the separated family back together. Armed with only a picture of the girl when she was four, he leaves for Madras to fulfill his mother's wishes.\n\nVelan arrives at his friend Mano's house to implement his mission. Mano lives with three more roommates: Charlie, Vadivelu and Goundamani. Velan explains his mission and all of them offer to help him.\n\nThe next day, they visit a computer centre where the clerk generates an image of the teenage Sumathi. Velan  and his friends visit the beach to think for a plan but luckily they find a woman playing tennis to be Sumathi, the girl they search for. When Sumathi goes to fetch the ball from the sea, and Velan goes to help her. But he accidentally drowns her, but manage to pull an unconscious Sumathi out of the water. When she becomes conscious, she blames him for drowning her and didn't need any help as she was a trained long distance swimmer. Despite his friends' advice to drop the love for Sumathi due to her arrogant nature, Velan proceeds with next step of his mission as a challenge.\n\nLater, Velan and his friends follow Sumathi to a 5-star restaurant. On the stage in the dining hall, a flautist is performing. Once the performance ends, Sumathi gets up and kisses the old flautist's hand. Velan too offers his hand to be kissed, wherein he is asked whether he knows anything about music. To prove her wrong, Velan dresses up in a fancy leather suit, adorned with various musical instruments, singing \"Pudhu Cheri Katcheri\". But Sumathi insults the performance. Velan on his part teases with harmless intention, which also earns Sumathi's dislike.\n\nVelan meanwhile attempts to attract Thaiamma, the guardian of Sumathi by visiting her house daily. Thaiamma is attracted by Velan's entertaining nature. Velan lies by saying his mother's name as Mahalakshmi. Though Thaiamma certifies Velan as a good chap, Sumathi continues to hate him. Sumathi's uncle Natesan, who is a retired IG of police visits Velan to warn him to stop teasing his niece. There he comes to know about his father is an industrialist Kaliannan Gounder who has disowned him due to his passion for music. Unfortunately, he manages to meet the Industrialist to verify the Velan's family background and finds everything true via the mouth of industrialist. But Velan and his friends have already visited the industrialist and convinced him to lie to the general to help them out.\n\nThen Velan managed to attract Sumathi gradually through a series of events, which makes Sumathi realize her femininity. Their love becomes strong when Sumathi hears that Velan is very serious at hospital as he was attacked by some men hired by her uncle as he lied that he was the son of an industrialist. She finds Velan dressed up with full bandages on his body (a drama by Velan who counterattacked the men sent by the uncle and instructs them to convey that the men attacked Velan, to Sumathi as part of the love mission). Velan's mother is informed about her son's hospitalization by a person from Madras and immediately rushes to see her son. There she understands that facts are not true and feels easy. Velan and Sumathi's love grows steadily and they decide to get engaged.\n\nOn the day of engagement, through 'Sincere' Sivamani, the manager at Sumathi's factory, Sumathi come to know that Velan is, in fact, the son of Paravathy, cancels the engagement and refuses to speak to him. In the meantime, the general finds that Sivamani is a crook who has been using Sumathi's premises to print [[Counterfeit money|counterfeit bills]]. Sivamani kills the General and frames Velan. Velan escapes the police and goes on the run. His friends, mother and the industrialist are arrested as accomplices. Sivamani decides to kill Velan and marry Sumathi for her wealth and tricks Thaiamma to accept his proposal to get married to Sumathi. He also uses one of his men to bring Velan in and to kill him, but Velan beats up all the bad guys and calls the police.\n\nTogether with the police, Sivamani's ally, his mother and friends he goes to the wedding hall and proves that Sivamani was the real killer and stops the wedding and gets him arrested. Sumathi realizes the true love of Velan and requests his mother to marry them. Velan and Sumathi get married. The story ends with the happiness of all members re-united at Velan's house.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] as Singaravelan a.k.a. Velan\n* [[Kushboo Sundar|Khushboo]] as Sumathi\n* [[Sumithra (actress)|Sumithra]] as Parvathi\n* [[Jaishankar]] as Retired IG Natesan\n* [[Mano (singer)|Mano]] as Mano\n* [[Goundamani]] as Drums Mani\n* [[Vadivelu]] as \"Michael Jackson Thangachi\" Subha\n* [[Charle]] as Flute Ramasamy\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Thaiyamma<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/when-the-camera-rolled-she-lived-the-character/article7751052.ece |title=When the camera rolled, she lived the character' |last=Yamunan |first=Sruthisagar |date=12 October 2015 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as \"Sincere\" Sivamani\n* [[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramaswamy]] as Kaliannan Kounder\n* [[Ajay Rathnam]] as thug\n* [[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] as Velan's father (cameo)<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2017/jun/16/daddy-dearest-1617504.html</ref>\n* [[Malaysia Vasudevan]] as Sumathi's Father (cameo)\n* [[Venniradai Moorthy]] as Doctor\n* Peelisivam as inspector\n* [[Swaminathan]] as one of the constables (uncredited)\n* S. R. Veeraraghavan as Commissioner\n* [[Shanmuga Sundaram]] (cameo)\n* [[Sangili Murugan]] (cameo)\n* [[Vinu Chakravarthy]] (cameo)\n* [[C R Saraswathi]] as Sumathi's Mother(cameo)\n* [[Oru Viral Krishna Rao]] (as marriage broker)\n{{colend}}\n\n== Reception ==\n''[[The Indian Express]]'' wrote, \"The script betrays an episodic approach, but [Kamal Haasan] carries himself with poise in a role that does not make much demands on him, except for some spirited dancing and singing, and the pack of comedians made up of Goundamani, Charlie, Vadivelu and Manorama, despite some ridiculous attempts at humour off and on, make a generally good impression.\"<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920417&printsec=frontpage&hl=en</ref> ''Singaravelan'' did well at the box office.  It was the first movie of any kind to be released in more than two theatres in a single complex in Chennai.<ref>http://www.mayyam.com/talk/archive/index.php/t-5142.html?s=a72a80636254df9525a498e59afb530b</ref> The scene where Singaravelan and his friends visits a computer centre to digitally visualise what Sumathi looks like in present-day gained popularity for its comedy.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/What-did-Kamal-Haasan-teach-us/article16439215.ece</ref><ref>http://www.sify.com/movies/computer-poche-the-demise-of-kollywood-s-funny-futuristic-side-news-kollywood-nlgtBRacjchsi.html</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Singaravelan\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Ilaiyaraaja]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1992\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 30:18\n| label      = [[Pyramid Saimira|Pyramid]]\n| language   = 