{"title_page": "Order of Prohibited Legitimacy", "text_new": "{{short description|Carlist order of chivalry}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox order\n| title = Order of Prohibited Legitimacy\n| image = [[File:Cruz de la Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita.jpg|240px]]\n| caption = The Cross of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy\n| awarded_by = [[File:Coat of arms of the House of Bourbon-Parma.svg|18px]] [[House of Bourbon-Parma|The Carlist Pretender to the Spanish Throne]]\n| type = [[dynastic order]]\n| ribbon = \n| motto =\n| day = \n| eligibility = \n| for = Service to the [[Carlism|Carlist Cause]]\n| status = Active\n| founder = [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]]\n| founded =  16 April 1923\n| head_title = [[Duke of Parma]]\n| head = [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma|Prince Carlos of Bourbon-Parma]]\n| head2_title = Duke of Aranjuez\n| head2 = [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]]\n| commander = \n| grades =\n| former_grades = \n| post-nominals = \n| date = 16 April 1923\n| first_induction = [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]]\n| last_induction = \n| total = \n| recipients = \n| individual = \n| higher = \n| lower =\n| image2 = [[File:Carlistenorde van de Legitieme Opvolging Ridderkruis.png|90px]]\n| caption2 = Venera of the Order with its original design preserved by the branch in obedience to [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]]\n}}\nThe '''Order of Prohibited Legitimacy''', known as '''La Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita''' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], is a Spanish [[dynastic order of knighthood]] awarded by the [[House of Bourbon-Parma]] to its [[Carlism|Carlist]] supporters. The order was founded in 1923 by [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]], a Carlist claimant to the [[Spanish throne]] and a Legitimist claimant to the [[French throne]], for rewarding loyalists to the Carlist movement. In modern times, there are two branches of the Order. One branch's [[Grand master (order)|Grand Master]] is [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma]] while the other's is his uncle, [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Sixtus Henry, Duke of Aranjuez]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Order of Prohibited Legitimacy was created on 16 April 1923 by [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]]. From exile in Paris, he sent a letter to his political secretary [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]], explaining his creation of the order stating that it served to recognize \"all those who by their sufferings or services become worthy of it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.cmd?path=3062557&interno=S&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina|title=Biblioteca Virtual de Prensa Hist\u00f3rica > B\u00fasqueda \u203a 'El Eco de Gerona : Semanario de Acci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica' - A\u00f1o...|website=prensahistorica.mcu.es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=fAUqAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA268#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol|date=April 2, 1941|publisher=Ediciones Trajano|via=Google Books}}</ref> The Marquis de Villores was decorated with the Order soon after.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=fAUqAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol|date=April 2, 1941|publisher=Ediciones Trajano|via=Google Books}}</ref> By a Royal Decree on 8 December 1923, he granted it to Carlist loyalist youths and [[Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra|Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra, Count of Urquijo]] in Madrid.\n\nSince the death of Jaime, Duke of Madrid, the claimants to the Carlist dynastic legitimacy have acted as Grand Masters of the Order. Prince Jaime was succeeded as Head of the Order by [[Infante Alfonso Carlos, Duke of San Jaime]] in 1931. Infante Alfonso was succeeded by [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier, Duke of Parma]].  Prince Xavier was succeeded by his son [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma]] in 1977.\n\nPrince Carlos Hugo embraced [[Titoism|Titoist]] socialism in the 1970s and sought to reform the [[Carlist Party]]. In 1979 he renounced his Carlist claims. In response, his traditionalist brother [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]], established himself as the Grand Master of the Order and Head of the House of Bourbon-Parma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oocities.org/faroagencia/documentosdonsixtoenrique.html|title=Agencia FARO - Documentos Don Sixto Enrique de Borbon|website=www.oocities.org}}</ref> In 2003, while in France, Prince Carlos Hugo re-asserted his Carlist claims and assumed the title [[Count of Montemolin]], also bestowing the Carlist titles [[Duke of Madrid]], [[Duke of San Jaime]], and [[Duchess of Guernica]] upon his children. He reestablished himself as the Grand Master of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy. His brother, Prince Sixtus Henry, and the supporters of his brother did not recognize the claim made by Carlos Hugo. Therefore, the order maintains two branches, one headed by Prince Sixtus Henry and the other by Carlos Henry's successor, [[Carlos, Duke of Parma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.docelinajes.org/2011/02/sobre-la-actualidad-de-la-orden-de-la-legitimidad-proscrita-y-sus-distintas-obediencias/|title=SOBRE LA ACTUALIDAD DE LA ORDEN DE LA LEGITIMIDAD PROSCRITA Y SUS DISTINTAS OBEDIENCIAS.}}</ref>\n\n== Insignia ==\nThe insignia of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy consist of a Covadonga Cross hanging on a ribbon with vertical black and green bars. The ribbon is in a simpler form for [[gentlemen]], and is decorated with a small rosette for officers and a large rosette for commanders.\n\n== Notable recipients ==\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra|Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra, Count of Urquijo]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Roca y Ponsa]], Spanish Catholic priest\n* [[Josep de Suelves i de Montagut|Josep de Suelves i de Montagut, 9th Marquis de Tamarit]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Esteban de Bilbao Egu\u00eda]], Spanish Carlist and Francoist politician\n* [[Ram\u00f3n del Valle-Incl\u00e1n]], Spanish dramatist and novelist\n* [[Melchor Ferrer Dalmau]], Spanish historian and Carlist militant\n* [[Claro Ab\u00e1nades L\u00f3pez]], Spanish journalist\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Zamanillo Gonz\u00e1lez-Camino]], Spanish politician\n* [[Dolores Gort\u00e1zar Serantes]], Spanish writer\n* [[Manuel Fal Conde|Manuel Fal Conde, 1st Duke of Quintillo]], Spanish Carlist politician and Catholic activist\n* [[Rafael Gambra Ciudad]], Spanish philosopher and Carlist politician\n* [[Juan Mar\u00eda Bordaberry]], President of Uruguay<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=2a7RCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Tupamaros. Derrota militar, metamorfosis pol\u00edtica y victoria electoral|first=Bordas Mart\u00ednez|last=Julio|date=April 21, 2015|publisher=Dykinson|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* [[Osvaldo Lira]], Chilean Catholic priest and theologian\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1923 awards]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Carlism]]\n[[Category:Dynastic orders]]\n[[Category:Orders, decorations, and medals of Spain]]\n[[Category:Orders of chivalry of Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Carlist order of chivalry}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox order\n| title = Order of Prohibited Legitimacy\n| image = [[File:Cruz de la Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita.jpg|240px]]\n| caption = The Cross of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy\n| awarded_by = [[File:Coat of arms of the House of Bourbon-Parma.svg|18px]] [[House of Bourbon-Parma|The Carlist Pretender to the Spanish Throne]]\n| type = [[dynastic order]]\n| ribbon = \n| motto =\n| day = \n| eligibility = \n| for = Service to the [[Carlism|Carlist Cause]]\n| status = Active\n| founder = [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]]\n| founded =  16 April 1923\n| head_title = [[Duke of Parma]]\n| head = [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma|Prince Carlos of Bourbon-Parma]]\n| head2_title = Duke of Aranjuez\n| head2 = [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]]\n| commander = \n| grades =\n| former_grades = \n| post-nominals = \n| date = 16 April 1923\n| first_induction = [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]]\n| last_induction = \n| total = \n| recipients = \n| individual = \n| higher = \n| lower =\n| image2 = [[File:Carlistenorde van de Legitieme Opvolging Ridderkruis.png|90px]]\n| caption2 = Venera of the Order with its original design preserved by the branch in obedience to [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]]\n}}\nThe '''Order of Prohibited Legitimacy''', known as '''La Orden de la Legitimidad Proscrita''' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], is a Spanish [[dynastic order of knighthood]] awarded by the [[House of Bourbon-Parma]] to its [[Carlism|Carlist]] supporters. The order was founded in 1923 by [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]], a Carlist claimant to the [[Spanish throne]] and a Legitimist claimant to the [[French throne]], for rewarding loyalists to the Carlist movement. In modern times, there are two branches of the Order. One branch's [[Grand master (order)|Grand Master]] is [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma]] while the other's is his uncle, [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Sixtus Henry, Duke of Aranjuez]]. \n\n== History ==\nThe Order of Prohibited Legitimacy was created on 16 April 1923 by [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid]]. From exile in Paris, he sent a letter to his political secretary [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]], explaining his creation of the order stating that it served to recognize \"all those who by their sufferings or services become worthy of it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.cmd?path=3062557&interno=S&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina|title=Biblioteca Virtual de Prensa Hist\u00f3rica > B\u00fasqueda \u203a 'El Eco de Gerona : Semanario de Acci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica' - A\u00f1o...|website=prensahistorica.mcu.es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=fAUqAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA268#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol|date=April 2, 1941|publisher=Ediciones Trajano|via=Google Books}}</ref> The Marquis de Villores was decorated with the Order soon after.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=fAUqAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol|date=April 2, 1941|publisher=Ediciones Trajano|via=Google Books}}</ref> By a Royal Decree on 8 December 1923, he granted it to Carlist loyalist youths and [[Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra|Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra, Count of Urquijo]] in Madrid. \n\nSince the death of Jaime, Duke of Madrid, the claimants to the Carlist dynastic legitimacy have acted as Grand Masters of the Order. Prince Jaime was succeeded as Head of the Order by [[Infante Alfonso Carlos, Duke of San Jaime]] in 1931. Infante Alfonso was succeeded by [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier, Duke of Parma]].  Prince Xavier was succeeded by his son [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma]] in 1977. \n\nPrince Carlos Hugo embraced [[Titoism|Titoist]] socialism in the 1970s and sought to reform the [[Carlist Party]]. In 1979 he renounced his Carlist claims. In response, his traditionalist brother [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma]], established himself as the Grand Master of the Order and Head of the House of Bourbon-Parma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oocities.org/faroagencia/documentosdonsixtoenrique.html|title=Agencia FARO - Documentos Don Sixto Enrique de Borbon|website=www.oocities.org}}</ref> In 2003, while in France, Prince Carlos Hugo re-asserted his Carlist claims and assumed the title [[Count of Montemolin]], also bestowing the Carlist titles [[Duke of Madrid]], [[Duke of San Jaime]], and [[Duchess of Guernica]] upon his children. He reestablished himself as the Grand Master of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy. His brother, Prince Sixtus Henry, and the supporters of his brother did not recognize the claim made by Carlos Hugo. Therefore the order maintains two branches, one headed by Prince Sixtus Henry and the other by Carlos Henry's successor, [[Carlos, Duke of Parma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.docelinajes.org/2011/02/sobre-la-actualidad-de-la-orden-de-la-legitimidad-proscrita-y-sus-distintas-obediencias/|title=SOBRE LA ACTUALIDAD DE LA ORDEN DE LA LEGITIMIDAD PROSCRITA Y SUS DISTINTAS OBEDIENCIAS.}}</ref>\n\n== Insignia ==\nThe insignia of the Order of Prohibited Legitimacy consist of a Covadonga Cross hanging on a ribbon with vertical black and green bars. The ribbon is in a simpler form for [[gentlemen]], and is decorated with a small rosette for officers and a large rosette for commanders.\n\n== Notable recipients ==\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina|Jos\u00e9 Selva Mergelina, 5th Marquis de Villores]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra|Julio de Urquijo e Ibarra, Count of Urquijo]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Roca y Ponsa]], Spanish Catholic priest\n* [[Josep de Suelves i de Montagut|Josep de Suelves i de Montagut, 9th Marquis de Tamarit]], Spanish Carlist politician\n* [[Esteban de Bilbao Egu\u00eda]], Spanish Carlist and Francoist politician\n* [[Ram\u00f3n del Valle-Incl\u00e1n]], Spanish dramatist and novelist\n* [[Melchor Ferrer Dalmau]], Spanish historian and Carlist militant\n* [[Claro Ab\u00e1nades L\u00f3pez]], Spanish journalist\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Zamanillo Gonz\u00e1lez-Camino]], Spanish politician\n* [[Dolores Gort\u00e1zar Serantes]], Spanish writer\n* [[Manuel Fal Conde|Manuel Fal Conde, 1st Duke of Quintillo]], Spanish Carlist politician and Catholic activist\n* [[Rafael Gambra Ciudad]], Spanish philosopher and Carlist politician\n* [[Juan Mar\u00eda Bordaberry]], President of Uruguay<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=2a7RCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Tupamaros. Derrota militar, metamorfosis pol\u00edtica y victoria electoral|first=Bordas Mart\u00ednez|last=Julio|date=April 21, 2015|publisher=Dykinson|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* [[Osvaldo Lira]], Chilean Catholic priest and theologian\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1923 awards]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Carlism]]\n[[Category:Dynastic orders]]\n[[Category:Orders, decorations, and medals of Spain]]\n[[Category:Orders of chivalry of Spain]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Therefore \u2192 Therefore,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_Prohibited_Legitimacy"}
